<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-01 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gaining weight accompanies gaining office
for many members of the General Assembly.
   Lunches with lobbyists, snacks during committee meetings and
rounds of receptions and late-night dinners at the state capital's
leading restaurants make staying thin as tough as _ and sometimes
tougher _ than getting re-elected.
   Just talk to Delegates Gene W. Counihan, Elijah E. Cummings,
Howard P. Rawlings, and William R. McCaffrey.
   The foursome top the scales at 1,200 pounds collectively and, in
a well-publicized weigh-in, they vowed to lose weight by the end of
the assembly's 90-day session.
   ``There are just too many opportunities for too much eating,''
said Counihan, who put on 25 pounds during his first year in
Annapolis six years ago and has steadily gained since then.
   Delegate Richard A. Palumbo, who picked up a few pounds each
session until he hit 200, said he understood his problem graphically
when he started looking at photographs taken during his Annapolis
career: ``Me getting fatter and fatter and fatter.''
   ``It's hard. There is food everywhere,'' Palumbo said. ``You go
to a reception and you are talking with someone about something
important to them. They have a drink in their hand, you have a
drink. They are plucking shrimp off a shrimp tree, so you pluck
some, too. ... You end up eating both sides of an issue.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife specialist Peter T. Bromley has a
way to get rid of mosquitoes in the yard: put up a bat house, which
is similar to a bird house except it attracts a different type of
winged occupant.
   ``A bat might eat up 2,000 mosquitoes every night,'' said Bromley
of the Virginia Cooperative Extension Service at Virginia Tech. ``If
you have six or seven bats in your house, that's more than 10,000
mosquitoes.''
   Besides, a bat house can be entertaining for homeowners, Bromley
said.
   ``On a summer night, you just have to get a lawn chair, sit it
outside and wait to see if a bat flits out the bat house,'' Bromley
said.
   ``They're great fliers, so they have aesthetic appeal. Plus, it's
fun to have guests look at your bat house and say, `There's no hole
in the front.' Then you can say, `That's a bat house,' and have a
lot of fun talking about it around your place.''
   Virginia Tech said people can get free plans for a bat house by
sending in a self-addressed, stamped envelope. But so far, the
Extension Service has not been going bats answering requests: it
hasn't received any inquiries yet.
</TEXT>
