<FIRST>r a PM-LateNightTown     03-01 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Late Night Town,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bolan, Iowa, Residents Off to Letterman Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOLAN, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volleyball and bowling leagues, two big
attractions this time of year in northern Iowa, will play second
fiddle tonight to NBC-TV's ``Late Night With David Letterman.''
   Letterman's show will feature the town of Bolan _ all 16
residents.
   ``I don't think there's anybody in Worth County that won't be
watching it,'' said Diane VanHorn, a secretary in the county
sheriff's department.
   At JJ's tavern in Northwood, home of about 2,000 people, Larry
and Judy Jorgensen are planning a ``Bolan Bonus'' night, featuring a
``Bolan cocktail'' and a ``Bolan burrito.''
   ``We were going to promote Wednesday night as `Northwood _ the
suburb of Bolan,'' Jorgensen said.
   Mrs. Jorgensen said the usual crowd that comes to her place after
volleyball and bowling leagues will likely stay a little longer to
watch ``Late Night'' on the color TV above the bar.
   ``If I had any influence with those people in New York, I'd have
them put the Bolan people on at the very end of the show so
everybody will stay longer,'' she said.
   Area residents are proud of the Bolanites, who will be seated
together in the ``Late Night'' audience before being introduced. One
or two will be on stage with Letterman.
   The show and all the national attention has given the little town
a big-city attitude.
   Bolan residents have arranged for friends to stay at each of
their homes, and they've hired additional security officers to
protect their belongings while they are being wined and dined in New
York.
   Sheriff Chuck Storffregen's deputies also will patrol the town at
all hours until the homeowners return.
</TEXT>
