<FIRST>r i PM-SisterSuicide     03-01 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sister Suicide,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Young Sisters' Suicide Bid An Attempt To Help Impoverished Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four young daughters of a poor factory
worker swallowed rat poison in a suicide attempt aimed at easing the
family's economic plight and enabling their brother to get an
education, police said today.
   The youngest girl, 6, died. The others, aged 8, 10 and 13, were
in serious condition.
   Their mother, Kim Ok-soon, found the girls in the family's rented
two-room apartment when she returned from grocery shopping Monday.
Their 3-year-old brother was nearby _ unharmed.
   Police said the eldest daughter, Soon-mi, 13, regained
consciousness and told police the sisters decided to kill themselves
because it would leave more money for the parents and for education
expenses to raise their brother.
   Seoul newspapers quoted the girls' teachers as saying they
studied hard and were quiet, model students. But a neighborhood
store owner said Soon-mi recently told him she could not afford
$5.80 worth of notebooks and pencils she needed for school and asked
to pay later.
   The father, Yang Tae-bum, 44, supported the family of seven on
$362 a month in factory wages, police said.
</TEXT>
