<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     03-01 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Comes on Strong, But NBC Extends Its Nielsen Streak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even Al Capone and Maxwell Smart were no match
for Victoria Principal in a TV movie called ``Naked Lie,'' whose
strong performance helped CBS remain out of last place for the
fourth time in five weeks.
   ``The 31st Annual Grammy Awards'' also helped CBS take second
place last week. NBC has won every week except for one tie with CBS.
Never mind that the Grammys had its lowest rating ever, 16.0, and
ranked 26th. It still did better than CBS usually does on Wednesday
nights.
   Another strong performer for CBS was a special two-hour
``Dallas'' that wound up with the highest-rated episode of the
durable night-time soap so far this season. It had a 17.9 and was
ranked 17th.
   Principal's thriller ``Naked Lie'' vanquished NBC's ``The Revenge
of Al Capone'' and ABC's reunion movie ``Get Smart, Again!'' to win
Sunday night and finish ninth in the weekly A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   Otherwise, the usual suspects rounded up the top 10: ``The Cosby
Show,'' NBC; ``A Different World,'' NBC; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``60
Minutes,'' CBS; ``Cheers,'' NBC; ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS;
``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC. NBC's ``Dear John''
finished 10th, behind ``Naked Lie.''
   NBC, which at 36 straight weeks is creeping up on CBS' record
40-week victory streak from 1962-63, won the week that ended Sunday
with an average, prime-time rating of 16.2. CBS had a 14.6. ABC had
11.7.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with televisions.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   Taking the three network news anchors to Japan for Emperor
Hirohito's funeral didn't seem to produce extra ratings. The ``CBS
Evening News'' had a rating of 11.7 and a 20 share. ``ABC World News
Tonight'' had an 11.5 and 20 share. ``NBC Nightly News'' had an 11.0
and 20 share.
   The lowest-rated prime-time network shows of the week were:
``Mission Impossible,'' ``Dolphin Cove,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Almost
Grown,'' ``Beverly Hills 75th Anniversary,'' ``Great Circuses of the
World,'' ``TV 101,'' ``HeartBeat,'' ``A Fine Romance'' and
``Murphy's Law.''
</TEXT>
