<DOCNO> AP890301-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpeechDemons     03-01 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speech Demons,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Does Da Mayah Want Good English? You Betcha!</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If youse talk like dis and don't know nuttin'
about grammah and good English, don't let Mayah Edward I. Koch know.
Yup, you be axin' for it.
   This spring, the mayor and schools chancellor Richard Green are
beginning a program to exorcise what Green calls ``speech demons''
from the lexicons of young New Yorkers who don't know or use
standard English usage.
   ``Axe'' instead of ``ask,'' for example. And ``pitcher'' instead
of ``picture,'' ``brang'' for ``brought'' and ``meetcha'' for ``meet
you.''
   And, as Koch himself used to say, ``liberry'' instead of
``library.''
   ``It was brought to my attention that I was saying `liberry.' I
wasn't aware of it,'' Koch admitted Tuesday.
   The program grew out of Koch's conversations with some of the
nearly 1 million students in the city school system.
   ``It's New Yorkese _ it's white, Hispanic, black,'' Koch said,
responding to suggestions that the new language program was aimed at
ethnic or racial groups.
   ``The language in some cases was un-understandable,'' Koch said,
coining a word of his own.
   The mayor had asked Green to come up with a program to tackle the
problem, and last week Green outlined it for Koch and provided a
list of the most commonly mispronounced and misused words and
phrases.
   The effort starts this spring with a one-day ``Putting Your Best
Speech Forward Day,'' during which teachers in all grades will focus
on the list of speech demons. A poster contest will produce graphics
that will be circulated throughout the system.
   The long-term plan includes more debating, oral reports, public
service announcements and a booklet of classroom activities aimed at
improving English.
   All this, Green wrote, should lead to ``substantive improvement
of oral communication skills.'' (Say what? Better speaking, you
betcha).
   Koch said for young New Yorkers to compete with the best students
across the nation and get good jobs, they must be able to speak
English properly and ``at the same time maintain your own heritage
and wherever possible to learn the language of your ancestors.''
   Some linguistic experts say such ``non-standard English'' is a
kind of dialect that isn't considered incorrect in the students'
social setting.
   Professor John Mayer of New York University's English Education
Department said the effort could stigmatize some students. The
chancellor's list, he said, included many phrases used by blacks and
Hispanics.
   In his memo, Green pointed out that the program will make clear
that ``our purpose is not to devalue anyone's home language. We will
encourage students to recognize that to be successful in school and
in the workplace, they must be able to use formal English
effectively.''
   ``This has nothing to do with accents,'' Koch said, although the
list shows ``cau-nuh'' for ``corner.'' ``It has nothing to do with
diction, it has to do with syntax, grammar. And the expressions
they're going to concentrate on are effectively New Yorkese, and
they cut across economics and race and ethnicity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpeechDemons-Example     03-01 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speech Demons-Example,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>This Be Talkin' Terrible? Yup, You Betcha</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Speech Demons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An example of the ``speech demons'' targeted for
extinction in the New York City schools:
   ``Fred says he wasn't doin' nuttin'. So, I says to him, `I'm
goin' to da liberry, I'll meetcha there.' But he didn't know where
da liberry was at. I axe him, `Are youse foolin' round? It's like,
in midtown, you know. Pacifically, at da cau-nuh of 41st and Fifth.'
He axes me if I was on'y goin' to da liberry. No, I says. `What-cha
doin' next?' he axed. `First,' I says, `I'm goin' to da museum to
see some pitchers. Then, I'm goin' to see Lorenzo _ he be sick, and
he ain't got no food. I brang some soup for him.' I says I think
this is da right thing to do. `Yup, you betcha,' Fred says.''
   Now, the same encounter rendered in proper English.
   ``Fred said he wasn't doing anything. I told him, `I'm going to
the library. I'll meet you there.' He didn't know where the library
was. I asked him, `Are you fooling around? It's in midtown.
Specifically, it's at the corner of 41st Street and Fifth Avenue.'
He asked me if I was going only to the library. No, I said. `What
are you doing next?' he asked. `First,' I said, I'm going to the
museum to see some pictures. Then, I'm going to see Lorenzo _ he's
sick and he has no food. I brought some soup for him.' I said I
thought this was the right thing to do. `Yes, you're right,' Fred
said.
</TEXT>
