<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0409 to change spelling to Gadhafi to conform AP
style</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Lookalike at Denny's Prompts Call to 911</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERRITT ISLAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheriff's Deputy Charles White
responded skeptically when someone phoned 911 to report that Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi was dining at Denny's.
   But when White and another deputy arrived at the restaurant
Sunday night, he quickly spotted the customer that had prompted the
call.
   Michael Belman, 34, was eating quietly with his 3-year-old son.
   ``We sat down beside him, and we were just laughing about the
whole situation,'' White said. ``He favors him.''
   Belman, a jeweler from Cocoa, said his face has gotten him into
trouble before.
   ``At times it's fun and at times it's fearful,'' he said. ``I've
seen (Gadhafy) on TV just a few times. We do favor each other quite
a bit.''
</TEXT>
