<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DeceptiveMailings     03-01 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deceptive Mailings,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Service Welcomes Legislation on Government Look-Alike Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service wants to zero in on
direct-mail groups that try to look like the government and sound
like the government in order to get consumers to open their
checkbooks.
   Private fund-raising appeals made to look as if they are from
government agencies are among the biggest consumer complaints
inadequately addressed by current law, Jack Swagerty, assistant
chief postal inspector for criminal investigations, told a Senate
Governmental Affairs subcommittee Tuesday.
   Swagerty told the Subcommittee on Federal Services at a hearing
that he endorsed legislation introduced by Sens. John Heinz, R-Pa.,
and David Pryor, D-Ark., requiring eye-catching ``look-alike'' mail
to carry a clear notice on the envelope disclaiming any connection
with the federal government.
   The bill would deal with ads such as those that appear to come
from the U.S. mint, from agencies offering surplus property or from
the Interior Department offering ``some inside track for obtaining
mining rights in public lands,'' Swagerty said.
   Currently, the Postal Service can do little to stop thousands of
pieces of mail it finds deceptive.
   For example, a private group's fund-raising appeal that said
``important Justice Department request enclosed'' was not deemed
illegal because the contents showed that it was not actually from
the government, said Tim Mahoney of the Postal Service.
   Under the proposed legislation, the envelope _ as well as the
contents _ would require a notice that it is a private solicitation.
   Under penalty of fines, the bill would require a similar
disclaimer for envelopes with official-looking seals or colors and
for organizations with important-sounding names such as the
``Federal Record Service.''
   The record service sent letters ``worded to intimidate
unsuspecting parents into believing they must obtain a Social
Security number for their newborn child,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., told the panel. He said the group charged $10, even though
anyone can get a number from the government at no charge.
   An entity called the Social Security Protection Bureau sponsored
a $50,000 sweepstakes, prompting a confused constituent to ask Heinz
when the government got into the ``gambling business.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
