<FIRST>r w PM-HijackingTrial     03-01 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Receive Federal Protection to Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two witnesses in the hijacking trial of Fawaz
Younis said they and their families were uprooted from the Middle
East and given new identities to protect against possible terrorist
reprisal for their testimony.
   The Lebanese passenger and Jordanian flight attendant are among
four witnesses who have so far identified Younis as the leader of
five heavily armed men who stormed aboard a Royal Jordanian Airliner
on June 11, 1985, and held about 70 passengers and crew members
hostage for 30 hours.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. instructed courtroom
artists not to sketch the two witnesses as they testified Tuesday.
   Two American passengers also have identified hijackers, who took
control of the airplane in an effort to publicize their efforts to
force Palestinian refugees to leave Lebanon.
   Younis, 30, has pleaded innocent to a six-count sky piracy
indictment. The trial in U.S. District Court is a test of a 1984 law
in which the United States asserts ``long-arm'' jurisdiction over
cases involving Americans taken hostage overseas.
   The protection given the witnesses and their families shows the
lengths to which the government has gone to bring Younis to trial,
beginning with his dramatic capture on a boat near Cyprus two years
after the hijacking.
   One of the protected witnesses, Mouin Ajam, 24, said he
originally went to jail for five days rather than testify. ``I was
concerned about the danger to my parents,'' said Ajam, a Lebanese
who was one of the passengers.
   Ajam, his wife and their infant son are living under new
identities at an undisclosed location.
   Flight attendant Sawson Odetalleh, 22, testified that federal
authorities had moved her, her mother, sister, brother-in-law and
five nieces and nephews to this country under new names to guard
them against revenge.
   ``If I would come out to testify in the USA, I would be sure 100
percent that it would jeopardize my family,'' the Jordanian native
said.
   Miss Odetalleh testified that shortly after the hijackers rushed
onto the aircraft, one demanded that she identify plainclothes
Jordanian security guards on board and asked a colleague to hand him
a knife.
   ``If you don't show me the marshals, I will cut your fingers and
make your face ugly,'' she testified that the hijacker, not Younis,
told her.
   Later, the same hijacker approached her with two hand grenades,
Miss Odetalleh testified.
   ``This one will kill you, this one will burn you. Which do you
want?'' she quoted him saying.
   At another point, the same hijacker placed her between himself
and a window, explaining that he wanted a shield in case snipers
started firing, and also wrote his nickname on her leg with a pen.
   Defense counsel Francis D. Carter tried to show that Ajam and
Miss Odetalleh benefited from their agreements to testify against
Younis.
   But they argued that they had sacrificed important parts of their
lives in order to testify.
   ``We can't see my parents, they can't visit us. They can't know
where we are. That's hard for the mothers,'' Ajam testified.
   ``I left my memories. I left my language,'' said Miss Odetalleh.
``It is hard to be in the witness program ... You start from zero.''
   More than two years after the hijacking, Younis was lured on
Sept. 13, 1987, to a sailboat and arrested in international waters
13 miles off the coast of Cyprus in the Mediterranean Sea, testified
David W. Johnson, who led the team of a dozen FBI agents aboard the
boat.
   Younis was interrogated for four days aboard the Navy munitions
ship USS Butte and then flown to Andrews Air Force Base near
Washington, Johnson testified.
   Carter sought to convince the jury that the FBI coerced a
confession from Younis, who was seasick and suffering from two
broken wrists after his arrest.
</TEXT>
