<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneEmergency 3rdLd-Writethru a0437 03-01 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Emergency, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0437,0975</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect 747 Cargo Door Had Earlier Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Navy detecting what it believes
to be the plane's cargo door. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, `Meanwhile, a...'
^With AM-Aging Airliners Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boeing 747 front cargo door that may have
popped open during a United Airlines' flight, sending nine
passengers to their deaths, had a recent history of problems,
federal investigators said.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said Tuesday that the
Navy had tracked a falling object it believed to be the cargo door
on radar to a point 86 miles south-southwest of Honolulu, where the
ocean is 16,800 feet deep.
   The cargo door would be ``very helpful to us in our analysis,''
NTSB investigator Lee Dickinson said at a late-night briefing,
although he did not know whether an attempt would be made to
retrieve it.
   Meanwhile, a similar United jumbo jet scheduled to land Tuesday
in Honolulu from Sydney, Australia, was delayed 18 hours because of
a faulty rear cargo door, the airline said.
   While the repair took only a short time, it extended the
allowable working time for the flight crew beyond the Federal
Aviation Adminstration limit, so the flight was delayed until a
rested crew was available, a United spokesman said.
   The forward cargo door on the 18-year-old 747 that ripped open at
22,000 feet after leaving here for Auckland, New Zealand, on Friday
had electrical problems more than once in December and had to be
closed manually, said Lee Dickinson, investigator for the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   A seal on the same door was repaired in January, he said.
   At an NTSB news briefing Monday night, Dickinson would not
characterize the seriousness of the problems that were found by NTSB
investigators by checking the aircraft's maintenance records.
   United Airlines spokesman Rob Doughty said the electrical
problems are not considered serious and were on a list of deferred
items that do not affect the airworthiness of the plane.
   ``That's a list that includes things like a reading light not
working,'' he said.
   As for the faulty door seal, it is something that would be fixed
before the plane was allowed to fly, he said.
   FAA spokeswoman Bobbie Mardis in Oklahoma City, where the
maintenance records are kept, said the recent cargo door repairs
were not listed on the jet's service difficulty report, possibly
because they were minor or were completed recently and had not yet
been logged.
   FAA records show that two other airlines reported faulty Boeing
747 cargo doors in the past five years.
   One was on a Pan American 747 that departed London's Heathrow
Airport in March 1987. The airliner returned to the airport after
the crew was unable to pressurize the cabin following takeoff,
according to the records.
   A worn part on a cargo door latch was blamed for the problem.
   In the other case, the rear cargo door warning light blinked on a
Trans World Airlines 747 during departure from O'Hare International
Airport in Chicago in December 1983. Ice on a master lock pin was
the cause, investigators said.
   The United jet's cockpit voice recorder indicates that the pilot,
Capt. David M. Cronin, had no warning before the plane rapidly
decompressed, Dickinson said.
   On the recording, the cockpit crew discussed only emergency
procedures after the accident, not a possible cause or warning, he
said. Cronin managed to turn the plane around and land safely in
Honolulu on only two of the four engines.
   For Cronin, 59, the ill-fated Flight 811 was to be his
next-to-last before retirement, according to his daughter, Karen
Twigg-Smith, who lives on the island of Hawaii.
   Cronin, a 34-year veteran pilot with United, told his daughter
that he credits ``the Heavenly Father watching over him.''
   ``That's one of the first things he told me when I first talked
to him,'' she said.
   United has refused to allow Cronin and the other 17 crewmembers
of Flight 811 to talk publicly about the flight, although he is
expected to participate in a news conference in San Francisco on
Thursday.
   Of the 354 people aboard the plane, 27 were treated at hospitals,
mostly for minor injuries caused by flying debris. Two remained
hospitalized Tuesday, both United crewmembers.
   In Washington, aviation industry and government safety experts
recommended Tuesday that the Federal Aviation Administration require
$800 million worth of mandatory work on older airliners to ensure
safety of the nation's aging airliner fleet.
   The unprecedented program would affect more than 1,300 early
Boeing 747, 737 and 727 models at a cost of over $600,000 each.
   United's Flight 812 from Sydney, which was delayed because of a
rear cargo door problem, was scheduled to arrive in Honolulu at 1:10
a.m. Tuesday, according to United's reservations desk.
   United spokesman Sean McNamara in Sydney said engineers replaced
a safety pin in the cargo door as a precaution in line with a
company order to check all of the airline's aircraft.
   The federal investigation of Flight 811 has focused on the cargo
door latching mechanism, and airlines around the world took Boeing
Co.'s advice and checked the cargo doors of their 747s.
   ``What this is from us is by no means interfering or speculating
on the probable cause of the accident,'' Boeing Spokesman David
Jiminez said Monday. ``It's more of a prudent act on our part to
keep customers appraised of what we know.''
   United's headquarters in Chicago issued a statement that more
than 900 cargo doors in a fleet of 399 operational aircraft were
inspected, and seven repairs were required. Doughty said no repair
was urgent and all would have been performed in normal maintenance.
</TEXT>
