<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-China     03-01 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-China,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Defends not Telling China about Invitation to Dissident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he's not bothered by the
row over the Chinese dissident who couldn't come to dinner and says
he won't clear such social invitations in advance with the country
hosting his visit.
   Discussing the communist government's decision to bar
astrophysicist Fang Lizhi from attending a dinner he hosted in
China's capital city last weekend, Bush said he hoped that people
wouldn't make too much over the incident.
   ``That's not the whole question when it comes to the United
States' commitment to human rights,'' the president said during a
photo session while meeting with members of his Cabinet.
   Asked whether the flap could have been averted if the U.S.
government had notified the communist government in advance of those
invited to the Texas-style barbecue at the Sheraton Great Wall hotel
_ as the Chinese have suggested _ Bush said, ``They may have a
point, that it might have been avoided.''
   But when asked if he would tell a communist host government ahead
of time about invitations to dissidents, he replied, ``No, and I
think they understand that.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater defended Bush's advocacy
of human rights during the two-day visit to China but acknowledged
``there is some degree of difference'' between Bush's handling of
the issue and the way former President Reagan dealt with it.
   Reagan met with dissidents during his visit to Moscow in 1988,
and the former president often gave human rights a high profile
during his public statements in foreign settings.
   Fitzwater said that Bush believes he should push human rights in
talks with communist leaders but that it should not be pursued to
the exclusion of other concerns.
   Questions have been raised about how much emphasis Bush will
devote to human rights in the wake of the flap over Fang.
   Fitzwater said that Bush chose to voice his complaint _ quietly _
to Chinese Vice Premier Wu Xuequian on Monday, the day after Chinese
police barred Fang, 52, from attending the event.
   Fitzwater said that Bush ``does feel that there are any number of
ways to call attention to our human rights policy, but to make the
views known diplomatically in a quiet way that does not disrupt or
infringe on many of the other objectives that need to be raised with
these countries.''
   ``So there is some degree of difference there,'' Fitzwater said,
``but I'll let you define'' it.
   Fitzwater said that Bush's invitation to Fang and a handful of
other dissidents was intended to make a human rights statement, and
said that the president had pushed the issue ``in any number of
ways.''
   ``I suppose maybe the proof is in the pudding, in the sense that
China today is saying the United States is to blame for the
diplomatic row,'' he said. ``Which is true. ... Which is to say that
the president invited dissidents to this banquet for a reason.''
   Four other dissidents attended the banquet, but kept a low
profile there.
</TEXT>
