<FIRST>r w PM-DerwinskiConfirmation     03-01 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Derwinski Confirmation,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans Nominee Faces Questions on Korean Leak</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Hearing begins 1:30 p.m. EST; top unlikely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators are asking Edward J. Derwinski about
his exposure of a South Korean informant in a congressional bribery
case, but the nominee to run the new Veterans Affairs Department
says his nomination is proceeding well.
   After almost two hours with the Veterans Affairs Committee on
Tuesday, Derwinski said, ``I don't see anything, as a result of this
meeting, detrimental or negative.''
   The senior Republican on the committee, Frank Murkowski of
Alaska, said the nominee was ``healthy and handles himself well.''
But the chairman, Alan Cranston, D-Calif., declined comment.
   The department is being formed on March 15 by elevation of the
Veterans Administration to Cabinet status. Derwinski has been
nominated for both the jobs of administrator of the VA and the
secretary of the department.
   Derwinski was undersecretary of state for security assistance,
science and technology when President Bush chose him in January to
handle the veterans department.
   Derwinski also served 12 terms in the House as an Illinois
Republican.
   Tuesday's session went over a 1977 episode in which Derwinski
tipped off the Korean embassy that an agent of the Korean Central
Intelligence Agency was about to defect to the United States.
   Derwinski at the time was a member of a House committee
investigating the ``Koreagate'' scandal _ bribes by the Korean
government for members of Congress to ensure their support.
   The agent, Sohn Young Ho, was spirited away from his New Jersey
home by FBI agents just a half-hour before colleagues from the
Korean Central Intelligence Agency arrived.
   After his testimony, he received a new identity in the
government's protected witness program.
   In 1978, Derwinski denied being the source of the tip and
declined to testify before a grand jury. The House Ethics Committee
did not pursue the matter, saying that doing so would compromise
intelligence sources and methods.
   But in 1983, appearing before the Senate Foreign Affairs
Committee for confirmation as counselor to the State Department,
Derwinski admitted being the tipster.
   Derwinski said he did not realize there was any danger to the
agent, whom he did not identify to the embassy.
   The committee was to cover the same ground in public this
afternoon.
