<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SmokelessCigarette Bjt   03-01 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smokeless Cigarette, Bjt,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reynolds Finds Out It's What's Up Front That Counts</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier was a cigarette designed for people who
hate cigarettes: a butt that didn't cause cancer, that didn't cloud
the air with smoke, that didn't even dribble ashes.
   It also didn't taste very good. And that apparently is what made
the planned billion dollar project go up in smoke.
   On Tuesday, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. announced that after five
months of test marketing in Missouri and Arizona, it had snuffed out
Premier because it ``has not achieved adequate consumer acceptance.''
   During its short life, Premier neither satisfied cigarette
smokers nor placated cigarette haters. Despite its label, it was not
exactly smokeless. It gave off a steamy vapor reminiscent of
cigarette smoke.
   It was a clever bit of engineering, so high-tech that it was
probably the first cigarette to come with instructions on how to
smoke it.
   Its advantages seemed impressive. It produced almost no tar, so
it probably did not cause lung cancer. And no smoke curled off its
lighted tip, so non-smokers were less likely to become upset.
   But like many compromises, this one seemed to please nobody. To
smokers, it did not taste, feel or look enough like a real
cigarette. And to doctors who worry about smoking's effects, this
one was still a coffin nail because it almost certainly would have
caused heart disease.
   Smokers who tried it complained it was hard to light, it went
out, it did not burn down like a normal cigarette and it was hot to
hold. But worst of all was the flavor.
   ``People smoke for taste. It's very bland, and you have to draw
until you get a headache to get any taste out of it at all,'' said
Dave Grinstead, tobacco buyer for the Shop &amp; Save chain in Missouri.
   ``I thought the project initially was revolutionary in concept,''
said analyst Lawrence Adelman of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``But the
technology wasn't there yet to satisfy consumer requirements.''
   Reynolds maintained that people needed to smoke two or three
packs to develop a taste for Premier. But instead, retailers said
smokers often bought a pack, smoked one or two, passed around the
rest and never came back for more.
   Doctors noted that even though Premier lacked cancer-causing tar,
it delivered nicotine and carbon monoxide like other cigarettes.
Those things cause heart disease, which is an even bigger smoking
hazard than lung cancer.
   ``Given the fact that more people die from cardiovascular disease
associated with smoking than from cancer, it's like comparing
jumping from the 10th floor of a building with jumping from the
seventh floor,'' said Dr. Gregory Connolly, director of the
Massachusetts Office for Nonsmoking and Health.
   Dr. Dietrich Hoffmann of the American Health Foundation, a
long-time opponent of cigarettes and member of a panel that reviewed
Reynolds' scientific data on Premier, said the product represented
``some progress for those who cannot be turned off smoking.''
   While Premier clearly seemed aimed at answering some of the major
health complaints about cigarettes, Reynolds never actually made any
health claims. Instead, the brochure that came with a pack called it
``the cleaner smoke'' and said it reduced many of the
``controversial compounds'' found in ordinary cigarette smoke.
   In fact, Reynolds could not flatly state that the new cigarette
was safer. That would have been an admission that regular cigarettes
are unsafe, something the tobacco industry has never acknowledged.
   Here's how Premier worked: Instead of packed tobacco, the end of
the cigarette contained a round piece of charcoal. Behind the
charcoal was an inch-and-a-quarter long hollow aluminum capsule
surrounded by tobacco. Inside the capsule were tiny beads containing
dried tobacco, glycerin and two secret flavorings.
   When the smoker lit up and took a drag, he sucked hot air through
the metal capsule. The heat vaporized the glycerin and nicotine in
the dried tobacco as well as the flavorings. The vapor then passed
through two filters and into the smoker's mouth.
   Analysts estimated the company spent about $325 million to
develop and test market Premier, and Reynolds had said a full
nationwide launch would have raised the cost to $1 billion.
   Several analysts speculated that the timing of Premier's demise
was due to the recent buyout of RJR Nabisco by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co., which needs to cut costs at RJR to pay off the debt
it took on in the record $24.53 billion takeover.
   But others said Premier was doomed no matter what.
   ``I think the consumer reaction was so negative that it pretty
much was a foregone conclusion,'' Adelman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CleanAir     03-01 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tough Clean-Air Bill Promised by July 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate clean air supporters have promised to
write a tough, new anti-pollution bill by July 4, an announcement
made while environmental experts were telling a House panel that
healthy adults and children are now at risk from dirty air.
   The House Energy and Commerce health subcommittee was told
Tuesday that the nation faces a health emergency, with 150 million
Americans now living in areas with unsafe levels of ozone and carbon
monoxide.
   Dr. Philip J. Landrigan, representing the American Academy of
Pediatrics and the American Public Health Association, said children
are especially vulnerable to air pollution because their airways are
more narrow than those of adults, and because of their increased
frequency of respiratory infections.
   He said studies of children in summer camps show those exposed to
ozone at concentrations even below current allowable levels
developed temporary respiratory problems.
   ``Children's often high levels of activity put them at risk for
acute respiratory effects due to ozone exposure,'' Landrigan said.
   Dr. Thomas Godar, representing the American Lung Association,
said Americans mistakenly ``accept dirty air as one of the facts of
life.''
   ``Ozone can cause immediate, short-term changes in lung function
and increased respiratory symptoms in healthy adults and children
who exercise moderately or heavily during periods of elevated ozone
concentrations,'' he said.
   ``Significant decreases in lung function and symptoms such as
coughing and pain ... are experienced by exercising individuals
exposed to ozone for one to two hours at levels comparable to those
frequently found'' in unsafe air quality areas, he said.
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who will sponsor the Senate's clean air
bill this year, announced that sections of the legislation will be
introduced at these time intervals: toxic air pollutants, April 3;
new air quality standards, including controls on auto emissions, May
1, and acid rain control, June 1.
   He said a complete bill should be written before Congress' July 4
recess.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, sponsor of
clean air legislation that died last year, told senators,
``Americans are suffering from a manmade phenomenon that can be
controlled. We have developed the technologies of control. We have
the resources to apply those technologies. Until now, we have lacked
the political will to do so. We must now develop that will.''
   Clean air legislation has been stalled for a decade, as
supporters of industry and environmental groups _ and different
regions of the country _ have fought to a standstill.
   Only one witness at the House hearing, representing General
Motors, said that there was no conclusive evidence that current air
quality levels caused lasting health problems.
   The chief of General Motors Research Laboratories, Dr.
Christopher C. Green, said the potential health effects from
exposure to current levels of ozone and carbon monoxide ``have been
the subject of considerable overstatement.''
   The Environmental Protection Agency said 62 areas have failed to
meet air quality standards for ozone and 59 for carbon monoxide, a
list based on readings from 1985 to 1987. The list does not yet
include 28 cities that exceeded the safe ozone levels last summer,
according to EPA data.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
