<FIRST>r w PM-Nunn-Tower     03-01 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nunn-Tower,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Must Overcome Nunn's Influence To Win on Tower Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In lobbying senators to support John Tower for
secretary of defense, President Bush has the difficult task of
overcoming the reputation Sen. Sam Nunn has built over the past 16
years as the Senate's bipartisan leader on defense issues.
   ``That's probably the toughest single obstacle the president
faces,'' Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., said Tuesday.
   Nunn, a Georgia Democrat who has been chairman of the Senate
Armed Services Committee since 1986 and a member of the panel since
1973, led the committee's Democrats in a 11-9 party-line vote last
week to reject the Tower nomination.
   Since then, he has made the case against Tower on national
television, in private meetings with other senators and in the
written report of the Armed Services Committee. But he insisted
Tuesday that he has not been ``strong-arming anybody'' to vote
against Tower.
   ``I'm not saying my prestige is on the line,'' said Nunn, who has
been described by Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell as ``one of
_ if not the most _ respected'' members of the Senate.
   ``I give them my views and I don't make any bones about where I
stand,'' Nunn said. ``But I'm not asking them to vote on anything
other than their conscience.''
   Nunn's views are that the FBI report on Tower provides evidence
of a ``clear pattern of alcohol abuse'' and that the former Texas
senator's recent work as a high-paid consultant to defense
contractors raises serious conflict-of-interest questions.
   Those views carry substantial weight, primarily because of Nunn's
reputation among both Democrats and Republicans as a senator who
does his homework and who speaks with authority on defense issues.
   ``I have never known him to do anything in Congress that would
appear to have self-serving, narrow political implications when
dealing with national defense or foreign policy,'' former Alabama
Sen. Jeremiah Denton said Tuesday.
   Denton, a conservative Republican who served on the Armed
Services Committee with both Nunn and Tower, said he supports Tower
for secretary of defense but, unlike some Republicans, does not
believe Nunn's opposition is motivated by partisan politics.
   Nunn has resisted Republican efforts to paint the Tower
nomination as a partisan fight waged by the Democratic-controlled
Congress in an effort to weaken the new president.
   ``The Republicans, if you agree with them, they say you're a
patriot, but if you disagree, all of a sudden it's partisan,'' said
Nunn, who during the Reagan years consistently ranked as one of the
Senate's top Democratic supporters of the Republican president.
   Nunn said he realized when Tower was nominated that he would be
subjected as committee chairman to a barrage of criticism,
regardless of whether he supported or opposed the nomination.
   ``Either I would be the scapegoat because I was taking on the
president, or I would be the chairman of the Armed Services
Committee covering up the alleged transgressions of the nominee,''
he said.
   The criticism intensified Tuesday when the Wall Street Journal
reprinted a Dec. 4, 1972, article from The Atlanta Journal detailing
an Oct. 31, 1964, automobile accident in which Nunn pleaded guilty
to leaving the scene of an accident.
   In an accompanying article, the newspaper said: ``If the Senate
is entitled to pass judgment on John Tower's personal history, then
the public is also entitled to know the salient facts about those
who judge Mr. Tower.''
   Nunn acknowledged that his ``driving and judgment were impaired''
on the evening of the accident because he had too much to drink. But
he said an accident 24 years ago is not relevant to the Tower
nomination.
   ``The implication is that if I have an automobile accident in
1964, then I'm not qualified under the Constitution to render advice
and consent in 1989,'' Nunn said. ``I don't think that logic holds.''
</TEXT>
