<FIRST>r w PM-AgricultureCuts     03-01 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agriculture Cuts,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Commodity Programs Likely Budget Target</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter says he
is still looking for areas to reduce his budget by $1.1 billion, but
believes most of the money will come from commodity programs.
   President Bush has called for the reduction, but not specified
which programs should be cut, leaving Congress with only Reagan
administration proposals.
   Yeutter assured the House Budget Committee on Tuesday he was not
wedded to the Reagan proposals.
   For example, he said ground water and food programs cut in the
proposed Reagan budget will be restored.
   He said Farmers Home Administration programs and those of the
Rural Electrification Administration, however, will be reduced along
with commodities.
   After the hearing, Yeutter told reporters that cuts in
commodities wouldn't be arbitrary.
   ``We have to go through a sophisticated analysis to determine the
extent of the changes. It may vary from commodity to commodity,'' he
said.
   ``We have to decide the best way to achieve the reduction while
still keeping a safety net for farmers. It's not an easy trick,'' he
said.
   He mentioned cutting target prices, but said they may not be cut
by the same percentage for every commodity. He also suggested that
there may be a reduction in permitted acreage.
   Yeutter told committee members who asked specifically about the
school lunch program that it was unlikely to see any reduction,
though President Reagan had suggested it be cut by $950 million.
   The secretary said he wanted to evaluate it and all nutrition
programs run by the department, but he doubted that there would be
any cuts in them.
   Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., gave Yeutter a list of programs for
low-income Americans which he said the committee over the years has
agreed must never be cut, including school lunch and other child
nutrition programs.
   An area Yeutter said should get more money is the Export
Enhancement Program.
   ``Export expansion and long-term market development are of key
importance to U.S. agriculture,'' he told the committee.
   Discussing the ongoing negotiations under the General Agreement
on Trade and Tariffs, known as GATT, Yeutter said the United States
is still committed to removing trade barriers worldwide.
   But he said the difficulty in achieving that end was demonstrated
at the midterm review of the Uruguay Round last December in Montreal
when the United States was unable to get other countries to go along
with its desire to do away with government subsidies.
   Following a meeting with Yeutter on Monday, Australian trade
chief John Duffy said the United States had softened its position,
and ``put the ball very much in the European Community's court.''
   Yeutter said after the hearing Tuesday that Duffy was correct in
saying that the ball was in the hands of the EC, but said the United
States had not softened.
   ``We formulated our proposal in a more palatable way,'' Yeutter
said.
   Trade talks resume in Geneva in April.
</TEXT>
