<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Future Travel on Hold Pending First Litter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has scrapped a planned trip to
his family retreat in Maine this month because of an impending birth
in the First Family.
   ``You just don't travel those last few days,'' insisted First
Lady Barbara Bush, who said she told the president to forget about
plans for a pre-Easter visit to Kennebunkport, Maine.
   And that was that.
   The family dog, Mildred K., or ``Millie,'' an English springer
spaniel, is expecting _ and due sometime between March 15 and 20.
   While awaiting the new canine arrival, Mrs. Bush says she plans
to ride around the White House grounds on one of the two new
``Flying Pigeon'' bicycles that she and the president were presented
during their visit last week to Beijing.
   It's the same kind of bike that she and Bush used to ride in the
mid-1970s when they lived in the Chinese capital, where cars are few
and most people get around on bikes.
   The president was head of the U.S. mission there from 1974-75.
   The oval on the South Lawn of the White House is exactly one
quarter mile, Mrs. Bush said. She said it was a good place to use
the new bicycle.
   When they were presented with the gift bikes, Chinese Premier Li
Peng suggested that that the Bushes ride the bikes around the White
House grounds.
   The president, who gave Li a pair of black Texas boots in return,
said he and Mrs. Bush would probably ride the bicycles in
Kennebunkport.
   Li indicated that the boots, boasting flags of the United State
and China, probably would not get as much of a workout. He said it
wasn't a custom in China to go around with boots bearing flags, but
he might wear them if he ever visited the United States.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater selected an unusual
way to announce his engagement.
   ``The Chinese security dislocated my fiance's jaw,'' Fitzwater
complained, thereby confirming what many associates knew but which
Fitzwater had never before announced.
   Chinese security guards, during Bush's visit last week to
Beijing, engaged in what appeared to be a favorite pastime: pushing,
shoving and pummeling U.S. news media.
   At one point, Carol Powers, a photographer who works for the
White House, was slammed into a door.
   Mrs. Bush shouted at the security folks to ``calm down.''
   ``This girl's job is to take my picture,'' she said. ``She works
for my husband.''
   Said a blushing Fitzwater of Ms. Powers, his fiancee: ``We
haven't really made an official announcement. But we are engaged.''
   He said the decision had been made ``the weekend before we left''
for the China trip. No date has been set.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>__</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   When the president went on Chinese television earlier this week,
he became the first foreign leader ever to do so.
   Chinese officials said the live, unedited interview reached
between 400 to 600 million Chinese, an audience even Johnny Carson
would envy.
   But Bush had a hard time making it to the TV studio on time. His
meeting with Chinese Communist party leader Zhao Ziyanf dragged on
and on.
   The session went 25 minutes beyond its scheduled close. Bush's
motorcade, racing at speeds up to 60 mph, sped to the TV studio and
arrived with less than five minutes to spare before air time. Bush
sprinted up the outside stairs to the studio.
   He was rushed in, some makeup quickly applied to his face. The
time of the interview was selected by U.S. officials: it followed an
Italian soccer match and came before Mickey Mouse and Donald Duck
cartoons.
   ``We all agreed it was the best possible time,'' said Andrew C.
Koss, an official at the U.S. embassy in Beijing.
   ``The majority of viewers were tuned in to watch Mickey and
Donald,'' he said.
</TEXT>
