<FIRST>r w PM-FDA-Aflatoxin     03-01 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Aflatoxin,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Food Supply Safe from Cancer-Causing Fungus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government confirms the drought helped
increase the cancer-causing fungus aflatoxin in the 1988 corn crop
in the Midwest, requiring some corn to be diverted to feed non-dairy
cattle.
   But the government disputed concerns raised in a report by The
Wall Street Journal last week that aflatoxin-tainted corn is moving
through the nation's food chain because of inadequate sampling and
unreliable testing.
   In a statement Tuesday, the Food and Drug Administration said the
agency ``does not believe such concern is warranted because there is
plenty of aflatoxin-free corn available for human consumption, and
several layers of protection are in place.''
   Aflatoxin is linked to the development of liver cancer in
laboratory rats. Last year's heat and drought provided ideal
conditions for development of the fungus that produces aflatoxin.
   Primary concern has centered around possible contamination of the
milk and corn supply.
   The FDA said the agency reaffirmed to state health officials last
fall its aflatoxin limit of 0.5 parts per billion for milk.
   States and the National Conference on Interstate Milk Shipments,
which has prime responsibility for testing milk, expanded monitoring
and as a result some milk in Texas, Minnesota, Iowa and southern
Illinois had higher levels of aflatoxin than allowed and had to be
dumped, the FDA said.
   The level of aflatoxin allowed in corn is 20 parts per billion,
and about 6 percent _ 95 samples out of 1,650 _ of the field corn
tested in recent months had higher levels, the FDA said. This corn
cannot be used for human consumption but can be diverted to feed
non-dairy cattle, the FDA said.
   In addition to FDA testing, which is concentrated in high risk
areas, tests are conducted by the U.S. Agriculture Department and
the states, manufacturers and millers who buy corn for food products.
   The FDA also tested about 100 corn products on store shelves _
including cooked cereal, dry cereal, tortillas, corn chips and
popcorn _ and all were negative, agency spokesman Bill Grigg said.
   FDA tested about 263 samples of corn flour and corn meal and
found 2 percent, or six samples, to have more than 20 parts of
aflatoxin per billion. FDA policy requires that these products be
removed from the market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
