<FIRST>r a PM-USAToday-Water     03-01 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USA Today-Water,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drinking Water in Newsroom has Lead, Barium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests found excessive amounts of lead and
barium in the water from drinking fountains in USA Today's
newsrooms, but the cause of a high number of miscarriages among
employees remains undetermined, a spokeswoman for the newspaper says.
   Employees were notified of the levels in excess of the
Environmental Protection Agency's guidelines in a memo distributed
Monday, spokeswoman Sheila Gibbons said.
   But there was such a disparity in the levels of lead and barium
in the tests that the newspaper has asked for a new series of tests
of the drinking water, Ms. Gibbons said Tuesday.
   Ms. Gibbons said the water tests are part of an overall
environmental check which began a few months ago when the newspaper,
owned by Gannett Co. Inc., learned informally that a large number of
pregnant women on its staff had miscarried.
   ``We are looking at several things in the newsroom environment,''
she said. ``Preliminary tests have been made on building materials
and carpeting as well as the water.
   ``So far there has been nothing conclusive,'' she said.
   Concerns over the miscarriage rate at the newspaper's
headquarters here surfaced more than two months ago after an
informal survey found that 14 women who work on the 14th and 15th
floors of the building had suffered miscarriages since September
1987.
