<FIRST>r a PM-GumbelGrumble 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-01 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gumbel Grumble, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gumbel Spouts Off _ Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-15, `Nobody at...' with 9 grafs to UPDATE with
comments from Scott, Shalit, editing to conform; picks up next to last
graf, `Gartner has ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bryant Gumbel, who has snipped at David
Letterman, Connie Chung and Linda Ellerbee and others, is at it
again, this time firing a rocket at fellow ``Today'' show staffers
such as Willard Scott and Gene Shalit.
   In a 6-month-old memo made public by New York Newsday on Tuesday,
he accused weatherman Scott of holding NBC's top-rated morning talk
``hostage'' to his ``bad taste.'' He said consumer advocate David
Horowitz is a ``walking cliche.'' He said Shalit's movie reviews are
often too late and his interviews ``not very good.''
   Medical correspondent Art Ulene's theme weeks were dubbed
``boring,'' and many of New York-based consumer correspondent Betty
Furness' reports ``too local.''
   Jane Pauley escaped mention.
   Her co-host, who wrote the memo last August when he was
negotiating his three-year, $7 million contract, could not be
reached for comment Tuesday because he was on vacation.
   It's not the first time Gumbel's grumbles have made news. In a
September issue of Sports Illustrated, he recounted his
disenchantment with Chung, Ellerbee and Letterman, among others.
   Even Pauley, who keeps a scrupulously happy face, seemed
exasperated by Gumbel's long-time war of words with the host of
NBC's ``Late Night,'' which stemmed from Letterman's bullhorn
disruption of a prime-time ``Today'' special. During an interview
with Don Johnson and Philip Michael Thomas of ``Miami Vice,''
Letterman shouted from an upper floor of the NBC building, ``I'm
Larry Grossman, president of NBC News, and I'm not wearing pants!''
   NBC's producer later confirmed that the bit had been arranged,
though not cleared with the ``Today'' stars. Pauley said even she
wasn't angry at Letterman, and she was the one doing the interview
when the disruption occurred, not Gumbel.
   That didn't keep Gumbel from launching and continuing a feud with
Letterman that escalated to the point of Gumbel questioning
Letterman's manhood, during a news conference last summer. Letterman
has since said the feud is a joke, but anyone who's seen Gumbel
discuss the matter would be hard to convince.
   Scott was the target of Gumbel's toughest jabs.
   ``This guy is killing us and no one's even trying to rein him
in,'' Gumbel complained, and suggested ``nuking'' the assistant who
supplies Scott with viewers' birthdates for Scott's birthday
greetings to centenarians.
   Scott called Gumbel's comments ``old stuff.''
   ``It's all water over the dam,'' Scott said. ``I don't think he's
a happy man. We're all here to have fun and make money.''
   Shalit said: ``I love what I do and I'm proud of my work. People
always have something to say in any creative organization. It
doesn't bother me. Besides, I think Bryant is a terrific guy.''
   Furness said she reports only on stories that are of national
interest. Ulene said Gumbel is a smart guy about television, though
he apparently doesn't understand the importance to viewers of, say,
Cholesterol Week. Horowitz said he stands on his record.
   Gumbel also griped to executive producer Marty Ryan about Ryan's
alleged ``lack of guidance and a lack of willingness to stand on
folks and make sure they do what's necessary.''
   Ryan, who was the recipient of the memo, told Newsday it was
``stolen'' out of a computer file and that ``Bryant and I always
have candid exchanges about the show.''
   NBC News President Michael G. Gartner declined to comment, but
was supportive of Ryan in his regular, weekly interoffice newsletter
to the staff.
   Gartner has his share of negative press coming. An article in
March's Manhattan,inc. magazine, due on newsstands Thursday, says
many at NBC News fear Gartner, who signed on last summer, is a
short-term ``hatchet man'' brought in by budget-conscious parent
corporation G.E.
   Gartner's most visible-to-viewers action so far was to
consolidate NBC's ballyhooed new ``Sunday Today'' with ``Meet the
Press,'' a move credited with prompting former NBC White House
correspondent Chris Wallace, one of NBC's few big-name news stars,
to jump to ABC.
</TEXT>
