<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-Verses     03-01 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Verses,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenya Bans The Satanic Verses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the request of its Moslem minority, the
government of this predominately Christian country has banned the
sale and possession in Kenya of Salman Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic
Verses.''
   James Njiru, minister for national guidance and political
affairs, said Tuesday that the banning was based on ``a short
review'' of the book, which many Moslems consider blasphemous.
   The review, Njiru said, ``clearly indicates that the content of
the book is offensive to Moslems who constitute an important section
of the Kenyan community.''
   About 6 percent of this African country's 20 million people
belong to the Islamic community, which had asked the government to
institute the ban.
   Other countries that have banned the book include India,
Pakistan, Egypt and South Africa.
   Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini has called on Moslems to seek
out and kill Rushdie, who is in hiding, and his government has
threatened to break diplomatic relations with Britain unless it
denounces the author.
   Britain is among more than a dozen European countries that have
recalled their ambassadors from Iran over the death threat.
</TEXT>
