<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Timar     03-01 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Timar,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Andy Timar, AP Representative in Budapest, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andy Timar, longtime representative of
The Associated Press in Hungary and a senior correspondent of the
national news agency MTI, has died after a brief illness. He was 65.
   Timar died Tuesday at a Budapest hospital he had entered Sunday
for tests after becoming ill. He died in his sleep after developing
respiratory problems.
   From 1946 to 1947, Timar worked with the English-language section
of the Hungarian delegation to the Allied Control Commission, which
governed Hungarian affairs immediately after World War II.
   He then joined the press department of the British Embassy in
Budapest.
   Timar first worked for the AP as a stringer in 1957 and was hired
as its representative in Hungary in 1962.
   He had worked for MTI since 1962, first in the agency department
that sent news abroad, then as an editor on the English-language
Daily News newspaper.
   Timar was a serious student of languages, art and history and
traveled widely throughout the world in his years with MTI and the
AP. He also had been active for years in the Budapest foreign press
club.
   He is survived by his wife, Piroska.
</TEXT>
