<DOCNO> AP890301-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Transplants     03-01 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplants,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Network Discourages Using Deformed Babies As Donors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severely deformed babies facing certain death
should not be routinely considered as organ donors, even though
hundreds of children desperately need new hearts and livers, the
national transplant network said.
   Directors of the United Network for Organ Sharing adopted a
policy Tuesday discouraging, at least for now, use of anencephalic
infants as organ donors. The board noted, however, ``it is unwise to
recommend a moratorium.''
   The issue of whether to take organs from anencephalic infants _
babies born without most of their brains _ has troubled experts for
some time, but some say it is the only way to save other dying
babies and children for whom there are few organs.
   ``We're certainly not going to take organs from a live person,
but in our hearts and in our minds we know these people are not
alive,'' said Brian Broznick, director of the Pittsburgh Transplant
Foundation and a proponent of anencephalic donors.
   Broznick and many other procurement officials are distressed that
they must refuse organs from anencephalic infants until all brain
activity ceases. By then, the organs often are not fit for
transplantation due to infection.
   Anencephalic infants are born with only part of a brain stem,
which controls respiration. Because they do have slight brain stem
activity, they are not legally brain dead, a necessary state before
organs can be removed from a human body.
   Half the 1,000 to 2,000 anencephalic babies delivered each year
in the United States are stillborn. The other half generally die
within one week.
   ``Not all parents would do it (donate),'' said Art Caplan,
director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the University of
Minnesota. ``But I'm sure there would be a significant number of
donors.''
   Broznick, in fact, believes there probably would be enough organs
to accommodate the 400 to 500 children awaiting liver transplants in
this country.
   ``We could probably take care of all those kids, and we can't do
anything about it,'' he said. ``By the same token, we could offer
this couple (with an anencephalic baby) an opportunity for something
positive to come out of this life that they've tried to bring in.
It's a real sad situation.''
   Only one anencephalic child has ever had its organs removed for
transplantation in the United States. That case occurred on Oct. 16,
1987, at Loma Linda University Medical Center in California.
   The heart recipient, a boy who was born the day of the operation,
is doing well at home in British Columbia, said Loma Linda
spokeswoman Anita Rockwell.
   The hospital has had a moratorium since August on cases involving
infants suffering from the incurable birth defect. However,
anencephalic infants reportedly have been used as organ donors in
Canada, Europe and Japan.
   Because of the growing interest in the infants as donors, the
United Network for Organ Sharing's ethics committee began studying
the matter last year. The panel recently presented its
recommendation to the network's 32-member board of directors, which
adopted the position during a regular meeting Tuesday in New Orleans.
   The board said further study is needed and could prompt a
re-evaluation of its position.
   ``We must have agreement on how you diagnose death and
brain-death in anencephalic infants before we can go any further,''
said Caplan, an ethics committee member.
   The Virginia-based United Network administers the National Organ
Procurement and Transplantation Network.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
