<FIRST>r p PM-WichitaMayor     03-01 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wichita Mayor,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Picked In City's First Mayoral Race In 74 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chicago Mayoral, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters participating in the city's first
popular election of a mayor since 1915 picked John Bell and Bob
Knight to face each other in the April 4 general election.
   With all precincts reporting, Bell, executive vice president of
Security Abstract and Title Co., received 18,138 votes in the
nonpartisan primary election.
   Knight, 47, a Wichita City Council member since 1979, received
13,806 votes.
   Bell and Knight were the voters' top two choices from a field of
16 candidates. The two top votegetters in the primary automatically
face each other in the general election.
   Bell, 58, is a former two-term president of the Wichita Area
Chamber of Commerce and currently heads the Sales Tax Watch
Committee.
   Wichita's last mayor elected by popular vote was O.H. Bentley,
who won in 1915 and served two years, said Craig Miner, professor of
history at Wichita State University. Since 1917, the city has used a
city manager-city council system of government in which council
members chose the mayor from among themselves, Miner said.
   In November, Wichita voters approved a proposal to begin electing
the mayor by popular vote.
</TEXT>
