<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedBoy     03-01 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Boy,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Arrested After Homeless Men Found Babysitting For Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vermont woman was arrested on an abandonment
charge for allowing two homeless men to babysit for her 4-year-old
son at a bus terminal while she smoked crack on a street, police
said.
   Deborah Longueil, 23, of Brattleboro, also was charged with
endangering the welfare of a minor after she showed up at a police
station Tuesday and reported her child missing.
   Police had begun searching for the mother and they found the boy
with the homeless men in the Port Authority bus terminal Monday
evening.
   Before Longueil was booked, she ``said she was looking for the
kid all night _ in hotels, movie theaters and the Port Authority,''
said Sgt. Bernard Poggioli of the Port Authority youth services.
   ``But she wasn't looking too hard,'' Poggioli said. ``We have
people on the street who say they saw her doing crack. ... After 26
hours and you're not looking for your kid, I'd say that's
abandonment.''
   Port Authority police patrol the bus terminal, where dozens of
homeless people beg and sleep among thousands of commuters and
long-distance travelers.
   A police officer saw the two men with the child Monday evening
and became suspicious, said Juvenile Officer Manny Rivera.
   The men said the boy's mother had left him with them while she
went out to work as a prostitute, according to Rivera.
   ``They didn't even know her name, or the child's,'' said
Poggioli. ``They called her Sarah.''
   The two men, John Best, 39, and Nicholas Villardi, 31, were
arrested for trespassing. Rivera said the area in which they were
found is reserved for people with bus tickets.
   Police said they also discovered that Best was wanted on drug and
weapons possession charges here.
   The boy was handed over to the Bureau of Child Welfare.
   Armando Arrastia, a spokesman for the Port Authority police, said
the child's aunt and grandfather, who previously had custody of him,
were in New York and planned to go to Family Court today to try to
get the boy back.
   Poggioli said Longueil was wanted in Vermont on shoplifting
charges and once ``went through drug rehab.''
</TEXT>
