<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-DaleyProfile     03-01 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Daley Profile,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Younger Daley Struggling to Escape His Father's Long Shadow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley, owner of the most famous last
name in Chicago politics, rarely invoked his father's memory during
his Democratic mayoral primary campaign. But with his victory
secure, he made sure to pay his dues.
   ``Today, when I was walking down to vote with my wife ... when I
looked up, I know he was looking down on me,'' Daley said Tuesday
night of six-term Mayor Richard J. Daley.
   In unofficial returns, the younger Daley garnered 57 percent of
the vote in the primary to oust Mayor Eugene Sawyer and move to the
April 4 general election
   The elder Daley was the boss of big-city machine politics, the
purveyor of patronage, the last of a political breed, dying in 1976
three months into his third decade in office.
   His son, who often sat in the mayor's seat as a youngster,
recalled that his father had told him that in politics, ``you're
going to have ups and downs. You're going to win; you're going to
lose.''
   And despite the sterling showing Tuesday, the younger Daley has
had some of both, in politics and in life.
   He had to fight to overcome the shadow of his father as he worked
his way through his father's old high school and law school.
   But those difficulties paled compared to the great personal
tragedy Daley and his wife, Maggie, endured when their 33-month-old
son, Kevin, died in 1981 after a long battle with spina bifida.
   The couple's three other children, Nora, 15, Patrick, 13, and
Elizabeth, 5, stood alongside their 46-year-old father and his wife
on the victory platform Tuesday night. In a poignant moment, he
thanked each, then added, ``and especially, Kevin, who is always in
our hearts. And to the best campaigner in the family, my wife,
Maggie.''
   Daley also went through a hurtful defeat in a 1983 three-way
primary between himself, then-incumbent Democratic Mayor Jane Byrne,
and Harold Washington, who won and went on to become the city's
first black mayor.
   ``I've been on both sides of these election nights,'' he recalled
Tuesday. ``I know what it's like to win, and I know what it's like
to pour your heart into a campaign and lose.''
   It took Daley three tries to pass the bar exam to become a
lawyer, a sore point exploited during the campaign by Jesse Jackson
and other opponents.
   Daley responded with a brusqueness many say is reminiscent of his
father.
   ``I flunked the bar exam. So what? Maybe I should have committed
suicide,'' he said.
   Besides, he added, a passing grade only would have led to charges
that ``my father had it fixed for me.''
   To be sure, Daley has been helped by his name _ getting elected
to the Illinois Senate at age 29, and as Cook County state's
attorney three times, including the first win against a party-slated
candidate.
   But there's no easy way to say how strong his father's effect has
been, said Eugene Kennedy, a Loyola University professor and author
of a biography of the elder Daley entitled ``Himself.''
   ``There's nobody like his father. ... But Rich has acquired a
confidence in himself and his judgment that resemble the father in
some ways. And he's overcome enough adversity on his own ... to
establish a separate identity, to start the long climb out from
under his father's shadow,'' Kennedy said.
   The eldest of seven children, Daley had his first political post
as an 18-year-old page for the Illinois delegation to the 1960
Democratic National Convention.
   In the state Senate, he showed more acumen than many gave him
credit for, and forged alliances with anti-machine reformers on
social-welfare legislation affecting nursing homes and abolishing
taxes on certain foods and medicine.
   Frank Kruesi, a top aide, said Daley studied hard as a legislator
and knew his material.
   ``Rich has been handicapped by the fact that people have trouble
getting past his name,'' Kruesi said.
   ``If his name were Richard J. Schwartz, he'd be lionized for the
work he's done as a legislator and as state's attorney.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MissUSA     03-01 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss USA,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Miss USA Is Texas' Fifth in a Row</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor MOB7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the fifth year running, a Texan has
walked down the runway as the winner of the Miss USA contest.
   ``They called my name and I was shocked,'' Gretchen Polhemus said
after she won the pageant Tuesday night.
   The 23-year-old cattle broker and real estate agent from Fort
Worth said she thought her runner-up, Jill Scheffert of Oklahoma
City, was the winner.
   Richard Guy, director of the Texas USA pageant, said the state's
fifth winning entry in the Miss USA Pageant just showed that
``classy, elegant, today women'' are victorious.
   Guy was in the Texas cheering section waving a Lone Star flag.
   He and his partner, Rex Holt, have developed into pageant gurus,
coaching the last five Texas contestants, as well as the 1977 Texas
entry, to victory through their agency, Guyrex Associates.
   Guyrex last week was featured on an ABC-TV ``20-20'' segment that
detailed the rigorous training given winning contestants represented
by the agency.
   A ``20-20'' team was filming Guy again Tuesday night.
   Miss Polhemus was crowned at the conclusion of a dazzling,
internationally televised two-hour production on CBS from the Mobile
Civic Center. Dick Clark and Angie Dickinson served as masters of
ceremonies.
   ``I'm so proud of her,'' Miss Polhemus' mother, Pat, said,
hugging a ``lucky'' stuffed toy cow.
   Prizes and gifts amounting to $200,000 goes with the title.
   The other finalists, besides Miss Oklahoma, were Miss New Jersey
Deborah Lee Husti; Miss Louisiana Elizabeth Primm; and Miss Georgia
Michele Nemeth.
   After the winner was crowned, the contestants went to a
coronation ball.
   Fifty-one women from each state and the District of Columbia
competed.
   Miss Polhemus said she will pursue an entertainment career while
continuing her real estate and livestock businesses in Fort Worth.
   The program was highlighted by a dance number with broadway star
Tommy Tune and the 51 contestants stepping to ``Is It True What They
Say About Dixie?''
   Miss Polhemus inherited the crown from Miss USA Courtney Gibbs,
22.
   The 11-member judging panel consisted of author Jude Deveraux;
modeling manager Bonnie Kay; Dick Rutan and Jeana Yeager, pilots of
the experimental Voyager aircraft; actress Stella Stevens; tennis
player Roscoe Tanner; Linda Shelton, an aerobics instructor; Lillian
Glass, author of ``Talk to Win''; actor Richard Anderson; Cecilia
Bolocco, Miss Universe 1987; and former Olympic diver Jennifer
Chandler.
</TEXT>
