<FIRST>r a PM-People-CelebrityHarassment     03-01 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Celebrity Harassment,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Sent Letters To Fox Held; Woman Reappears at Letterman
House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who allegedly sent threatening letters to actor Michael
J. Fox was being held without bail, and a woman who had been charged
with trespassing at talk show host David Letterman's house was
arrested again for returning.
   In Los Angeles, a judge ruled that Tina M. Ledbetter, 26, poses a
risk to Fox and his pregnant wife, Tracy Pollan, in ordering her
held without bail Tuesday.
   She pleaded innocent to five felony counts of making terrorist
threats. Ledbetter had been free on $50,000 bail following her Feb.
3 arrest.
   In New Canaan, Conn., Margaret Ray was arrested Tuesday on
trespassing charges, marking the third time in recent months that
she has been apprehended inside Letterman's home.
   New Canaan police said they received a complaint of an ``unwanted
person'' in Letterman's home. Police said the complaint was not
filed by Letterman, the host of ``Late Night with David Letterman''
on NBC.
   Spokesmen for NBC and Letterman's manager, Jack Rollins, referred
all questions to New Canaan police.
   Ray, 36, was charged with first-degree criminal trespassing and
possession of marijuana. She was being held on $5,000 bond at the
New Canaan police station, pending arraignment today in Norwalk
Superior Court.
   Ray was arrested Friday for criminal trespassing when she was
found wandering in the foyer of Letterman's home.
   Superior Court Judge Edward Leavitt released her Monday on a
promise that she report twice a week to a bail commissioner and seek
further psychiatric treatment.
   Last spring Ray set up housekeeping in Letterman's home and was
arrested while driving his sports car after identifying herself to a
toll collector outside New York City as ``Mrs. David Letterman.'' In
September, Leavitt ordered Ray to undergo psychiatric treatment.
   Many of the more than 5,000 letters to Fox, signed ``Your No. 1
Fan,'' threatened that he and his wife would die if he didn't
divorce her, Deputy District Attorney Norm Shapiro said.
   Fox, who has won two Emmys for his portrayal as the conservative
son of liberal parents on NBC's ``Family Ties,'' hired a security
guard for himself and Miss Pollan.
   The letters began in February 1988, several months prior to Fox's
July 1988 marriage to Pollan, and they continued after the marriage,
said Al Albergate, a district attorney's office spokesman.
   A bail hearing is scheduled for March 7. Ledbetter faces up to
four years in state prison.
</TEXT>
