<FIRST>r a PM-FilmAnniversary     03-01 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Film Anniversary,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hollywood's First Feature Film Has Debut 75 Years Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie buffs and preservationists celebrated
Hollywood's first feature film with a showing of the long-lost movie
in the barn where it was filmed 75 years ago.
   On hand for Tuesday night's screening of ``The Squaw Man'' was
Betty Lasky, daughter of Hollywood pioneer Jesse L. Lasky. He made
the 90-minute melodrama about a British aristocrat's adventures in
America with Cecil B. DeMille, and the two men went on to found
Paramount Pictures.
   ``I first saw ``The Squaw Man'' five or six years ago,'' said Ms.
Lasky. ``It had been lost until then. Mr. DeMille hunted for it for
years.''
   Found in a vault at MGM, the film starring Dustin Farnum now is
at the Library of Congress, which helped arrange the special
screening.
   The barn had been rented by Lasky and DeMille for $75 and now has
been transformed into the Hollywood Studio Museum. It's the only
museum in Hollywood devoted to film history and contains such
memorabilia as Ben Hur's chariot, Mary Pickford's makeup case and
Mabel Normand's traveling trunk.
   ``This building played a very important part in the evolution of
movies,'' said Hollywood Councilman Michael Woo.
   Dan Sartell, a former assistant to Lasky who came from his home
in Jamesville, Wis., said Lasky would be thrilled to see the film so
well preserved, but might be disappointed with the current state of
the industry.
   ``In those days, men made films,'' said Sartell. ``Now, it's all
corporations.''
   A three-man musical group played the original background music
for, ``The Squaw Man,'' in which a British aristocrat confronts the
wild West and marries an Indian woman.
</TEXT>
