<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     03-01 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Converge On Capital To Protest Alleged Persecution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 Kosovo Slavs and their
children converged on Belgrade today to protest alleged ethnic
persecution by the majority Albanians in the impoverished southern
region, the state Tanjug news agency said.
   The flag-carrying, chanting Serbs and Montenegrins jammed steets
and interrupted traffic as they walked from the railroad station to
the downtown parliament.
   Taxi drivers, brandishing pictures of the popular Serbian party
chief Slobodan Milosevic, gave free rides to the elderly.
   Speaking to a rally in the capital Tuesday that drew an estimated
500,000 people, Milosevic vowed to arrest the organizers of protests
and strikes by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo _ an autonomous province
of the Serbian republic.
   Serbs who support Milosevic believe the Albanians in Kosovo,
which was ancient Serbia's heartland, want to unite the province
with neighboring Albania. About 90 percent of Kosovo's people are
ethnic Albanians.
   Growing ethnic nationalism has created the greatest threat to
Yugoslav unity since the 1980 death of President Tito, whose
leadership held the disparate nation of 23 million people together.
   An economic crisis has combined with the resurgence of ethnic and
religious rivalries to threaten the loose confederation of six
republics and two provinces.
   The republics of Slovenia and Croatia support demands by ethnic
Albanians for guarantees that Kosovo's autonomy will not be
restricted. The two are Yugoslavia's most liberal and economically
advanced republics.
   Macedonia supports the Serbs, the largest ethnic group in
Yugoslavia.
   Kosovo was outwardly peaceful Tuesday, except for scattered
Serbian protests, under emergency measures imposed Monday after a
week of unrest among the province's 1.8 million people.
   Official Yugoslav media said about 1,000 Slavs had announced
plans to leave Kosovo immediately, alleging harassment by ethnic
Albanians.
   Meanwhile, 500 ethnic Albanians in the Trepca lead-zinc mine in
Kosovo continued their strike to protest Serbian plans to change the
constitution in a bid to win greater control over their province.
   On Monday, 1,300 ethnic Albanian miners came out from pits after
an eight-day sit-in that forced the resignation of three Kosovo
Communist Party leaders they consider pro-Serbian.
   Doctors from Croatia said the exhausted miners would be unable to
work for at least a week.
   Tanjug said peace prevailed this morning in Kosovo's capital of
Pristina, where additional military vehicles and soldiers had been
sent on Monday.
   But in Sarajevo, capital of the republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina,
2,000 students lent support to Milosevic's drive for more control
over Kosovo, and demanded the resignations of the three leaders be
rescinded.
   Thousands of workers in Macedonia also sided with Serbia in more
protests today and sent messages of support to Belgrade students
saying ``Sarajevo Is With You'' and ``Slovenia Is Lying,'' Tanjug
said.
   About 1,000 Slovenian intellectuals held an anti-Serbian protest
Tuesday in Slovenia's capital, Ljubljana, and about 100,000
Slovenians have signed a petition against the emergency measures in
Kosovo.
</TEXT>
