<FIRST>r a PM-NonagenarianReleased     03-01 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nonagenarian Released,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>91-Year-Old Man Released From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 91-year-old man described by federal law
enforcement officials as a ``financial top man'' among bookies has
been freed despite his refusal to cooperate in a criminal
investigation.
   U.S. District Judge William G. Young ordered Harry ``Doc''
Sagansky released from the Plymouth County House of Correction on
Tuesday, reversing an earlier decision. He did not comment on the
decision.
   ``It feels good to be out,'' Sagansky said as he left with his
son. ``I'm just going to go home and have some dinner.''
   His lawyer, Morris M. Goldings, described Sagansky as suffering
from depression last week in asking the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals to review the case. Goldings said the appeals court
suggested that Young review the case.
   In court papers, Sagansky said he feared ``bodily harm'' to
himself and his family if he answered a grand jury's questions about
a case involving the New England Organized Crime Task Force.
   At one point, Sagansky said he would rather die in jail than
share his knowledge with law enforcement officials.
   The FBI in June 1987 said that Sagansky and two men reputed to be
potential leaders in the Boston mob were targets of a racketeering
investigation. But Goldings said his client was being sought as a
witness and was not a target of investigators.
   Sagansky invoked the Fifth Amendment before a federal grand jury
on July 1, 1987, and declined to answer questions. He was later
granted immunity from prosecution but still refused to answer
questions.
   He was ordered jailed by Young on Feb. 3, 1988, after discussions
with federal prosecutors concerning the federal witness protection
plan fell through.
</TEXT>
