<FIRST>r a PM-WyethSale     03-01 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wyeth Sale,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wyeth's Helga Collection For Sale at $40 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTOWN SQUARE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The once-secret ``Helga'' portfolio of
paintings and drawings by Andrew Wyeth is for sale for $40 million.
   Leonard E.B. Andrews, the Newtown Square publisher and art
collector who bought the 240 works from Wyeth in 1986, said Tuesday
that his intention had been to show the collection to the American
public, ``and we've done that in spades.''
   The collection consists of nudes and other portraits of Helga
Testorf, a neighbor of Wyeth's. The works were created in secret for
15 years and caught the art world's eye when Andrews bought them.
   When he purchased the collection, Andrews said only that he had
paid ``several million.'' Estimates of the price have varied from $6
million to $20 million. Andrews said Wyeth agreed never to reveal
the price tag.
   Andrews said Wyeth ``is aware of (the sale) and understands my
reasoning.'' He said his reasons for selling include the lack of
facilities to house the collection.
   Andrews said he intends to sell the collection intact and not
piecemeal. He said he has been approached by American and Japanese
interests.
   The Helga works have been exhibited to more than 1 million people
at six museums across the country during the past two years but were
not favorably received by many critics and scholars.
   They are to be displayed this summer at the Brooklyn Museum in
New York. The collection also is committed for exhibition in Japan
throughout 1990.
</TEXT>
