<FIRST>r i PM-Laos-Kidnapping     03-01 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laos-Kidnapping,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Businessman Kidnapped in Laos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four gunmen kidnapped a Japanese businessman in
Vientiane, Laos, early today after breaking into his home and tying
up his wife and two maids, government officials said.
   Yoshiaki Asao, 61, branch manager of Mitsui and Co.'s Vientiane
office, was abducted, a company spokesman quoted Asao's wife as
saying.
   Goverment sources said four men participated in the kidnapping,
none of them Japanese.
   The company spokesman, Shuzo Uematsu, said no one has claimed
responsibility, nor had the company received any threats beforehand.
   At a news conference at Mitsui's Tokyo office, Uematsu said the
company contacted Asao's wife, Michiko, and confirmed the
kidnapping, but communication was too poor to learn details.
   Government sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Mrs. Asao and the two maids were not injured.
   It was the second kidnapping of an overseas Mitsui executive in
three years.
   Nobuyuki Wakaoji, the company's Manila branch manager, was
kidnapped in the Philippines in November 1986 and released in March
1987. The company reportedly paid a ransom for his release.
   Last year, police said the Japanese Red Army, a terrorist
organization, had kidnapped Wakaoji.
   In the past four years, at least four Japanese have been abducted
abroad, including Wakaoji.
   Japan established diplomatic relations with Laos in 1976 and has
donated more development aid to Laos than other Western countries.
In fiscal 1987, Japanese aid to Laos reached $13.7 million.
</TEXT>
