<FIRST>r a PM-AgingJets-Orders     03-01 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Jets-Orders,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Replacing Aging Jets Won't Be Easy, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Aging Airliners, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aircraft manufacturers will be hard-pressed to
meet the anticipated demand for new planes to replace aging
jetliners, industry analysts say.
   The Boeing Co., McDonnell Douglas and Airbus Industrie already
have ``interesting challenges ahead'' in meeting the ``delivery
commitments already made,'' said Wolfgang H. Demisch of Union Bank
of Switzerland in an interview from New York.
   Some models ordered today won't be delivered until 1996, he said.
   ``At this point, pouring more orders into the funnel isn't going
to make more airplanes come out at the bottom,'' said Demisch. ``The
greater risk is that in this rush suppliers will be overstretched
and can't deliver as quickly as expected. Already there are
components in tight supply, and that's not going to get much
easier.''
   With the joint government-industry Aging Aircraft Task Force
recommending that the Federal Aviation Administration order $800
million in maintenance, analysts predicted the pressure to replace
older planes will increase.
   Paul H. Nisbet of Prudential-Bache said airlines saw the need to
replace planes several years ago as maintenance costs began rising.
   ``I think a lot of orders seen in the last two or three years
have been for replacement,'' Nisbet said. ``Before that, orders were
just for traffic growth.''
   Nisbet said he expected 600 to 700 new plane orders annually over
the next few years, including as many as 200 to 300 to replace older
planes.
   Boeing's stock has held firm in the $60 range during the latest
incident involving a plane it built, a United Airlines 747 in which
the fuselage tore open after takeoff from Honolulu to New Zealand on
Friday.
   Nine passengers were sucked to their deaths from the plane.
Investigators have focused on a cargo door as a likely cause of the
incident.
   George Shapiro of Salomon Brothers in New York said consumers
haven't blamed carriers or Boeing for the accident, the recent crash
of a British Midland Airways 737 that killed 44 or the Aloha
Airlines 737 that ripped open in April, sending a flight attendant
to her death.
   ``There's no question Boeing is going through a string of
unfortunate troubles, from crashes, holes developing in its planes
in flight, and with quality problems on new aircraft,'' he said,
``but Boeing has more planes out there than any other manufacturer
and they are getting older.''
   Boeing officials have denied any connection between the recent
spate of incidents.
</TEXT>
