<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     03-01 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Called By Guerrilla Group As Peace Commission Begins Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest guerrilla group has
declared a unilateral cease-fire in the latest bid to end an
insurgency that has claimed 76,000 lives in the last quarter-century.
   Jacobo Arenas, leader of the leftist Colombian Revolutionary
Armed Forces, declared in a recorded message broadcast over radio
nationwide that the cease-fire began at 6 p.m. Tuesday.
   While no incidents had been reported early today, President
Virgilio Barco's administration has expressed pessimism about the
chances of stopping the insurrection.
   Right-wing death squads have sprung up in response to the leftist
guerrillas, and the rightists have been blamed for killing at least
1,000 people in the last three years.
   Also on Tuesday, a peace commission in Bogota began work toward a
general cease-fire to the insurrection, which has claimed 76,000
lives in the past 76 years.
   Raul Orejuela Buena, minister of government, said last week the
guerrillas were manipulating the Roman Catholic church-sponsored
commission and it had little more chance of success than the last
president, Belisario Betancur, experienced in pursuing a cease-fire.
   Betancur's government negotiated a truce with most of the
estimated 10,000 guerrillas in Colombia's five guerrilla armies, but
it collapsed under the weight of accusations by rebels and security
forces.
   Alfonso Lopez Michelsen, a former president from Barco's Liberal
Party, on Tuesday rejected the government minister's criticism of
the commission.
   ``Trying to save human lives and put an end to the spilling of
blood, I am disposed to hear all those of good faith and even bad
faith who might have something to suggest,'' he said in a statement.
   Two other rebel groups, the April 19 Movement and the Quintin
Lame, said last month they would like to begin peace talks, but the
remaining two have shown no inclination to negotiate.
   One, the People's Revolutionary Army, claimed responsibility for
a bomb that exploded Monday at the Bogota offices of an American
missionary group, the Summer Institute of Linguistics of
Duncanville, Texas.
   The National Liberation Army has said it will never stop fighting.
</TEXT>
