<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DetroitHomeless     03-01 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Homeless,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Vetoes Ordinance Making Public Buildings Shelters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman Young vetoed an ordinance offering
shelter in municipal buildings to thousands of homeless people,
calling it unnecessary, costly and potentially damaging to Detroit's
convention business.
   Tuesday's veto came a day after the City Council voted 8-0 to use
municipal buildings to provide shelter, heat, restrooms and security
for homeless people for 60 days.
   The ordinance would have opened up Recreation Department
buildings, the vacant Detroit General Hospital, Ford Auditorium and
a Civic Center meeting place where an estimated 40,000 people are
attending a convention of automotive engineers.
   ``To begin with, more effective and responsible plans for the
homeless already have been and are being implemented,'' Young said
in a statement. ``In addition, this ordinance is so broad and
far-reaching as to be unworkable.
   ``It would cost over $2 million to operate, it would seriously
curtail vital neighborhood programs run by the Recreation Department
and Police Athletic League, and it would seriously damage our
ability to bring meetings and conventions and the thousands of jobs
they create to the Civic Center,'' he said.
   Young said existing shelters had beds available every night and
that the city's Homeless Intervention Program has placed 400
homeless families in permanent housing. But advocates for the
homeless disputed that claim.
   ``We don't have any records of him placing anybody, and
especially not ... 400 people,'' said Theresa Smith, spokeswoman for
the Detroit-Wayne County Union of the Homeless. ``He's not done half
of what he says he's done.''
   Councilman Clyde Cleveland said Tuesday he expects the Council to
attempt to override Young's veto.
   Cleveland said he had not reviewed Young's veto message and could
not comment on it. He also would not predict whether an override
would succeed.
   Estimates of the number of homeless people in the nation's
sixth-largest city range from 12,000 to 60,000 out of a population
of 1.1 million.
</TEXT>
