<FIRST>r i PM-Iraq-Amnesty     03-01 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iraq-Amnesty,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Denounces Amnesty Report on Child Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Iraqi News Agency today
denounced a report by Amnesty International that said the children
of political prisoners have been tortured, abused and imprisoned in
Iraq.
   INA quoted an unidentified editor as calling the report by the
international human rights organization ``cheap allegations'' in an
``anti-Iraqi propaganda campaign.''
   The editor pointed to the planned political reforms announced by
President Saddam Hussein to dispute the charges.
   ``These lies aired by enemy circles come at a time when Iraq
announces its serious efforts through continuous meetings of the
political leadership to set the permanent constitution of the
country and to permit ... political parties ... and press freedom,''
said the report, which was monitored in Nicosia.
   Hussein has said political parties will be permitted and has
encouraged the press to be more critical.
   The new laws have not been announced, but former opposition
parties such as the Islamic Call and the communists will not be
permitted on the ground they had dealings with Iran, Iraq's foe in
the eight-year Persian Gulf war.
   The editor said Iraqi children get free education, health care
and social security.
   Amnesty International issued a report on Tuesday saying that
``children and young people have become the innocent victims of a
policy of political repression'' in Iraq.
   It said opponents of Hussein's government have sometimes had to
pay for their activities with ``the welfare _ and sometimes the
lives _ of their children'' between 1983 and 1988.
   Children as young as five months old have been imprisoned, and
hundreds have disappeared, the report said.
</TEXT>
