<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Elections 2ndLd-Writethru a0522 03-01 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0522,0876</SECOND>
<HEAD>Likud Takes Labor Strongholds; Kollek Re-elected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more comments from Shamir and Peres,
dispute over vote count in mayor's race in Haifa. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Likud bloc upset the Labor Party
in nationwide municipal elections, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
said today the voting indicates Israelis support Likud's anti-PLO
policies.
   Shimon Peres, the Labor Party leader and finance minister,
insisted Tuesday's balloting had nothing to do with the Palestinian
issue and said he was willing to hold a separate referendum on the
subject.
   Other Labor leaders demanded a shakeup to halt a decline in their
party's standing since November, when Likud won the premiership in
national elections.
   Political analysts said the results showed Labor's historic
dominance of the grass-roots level had eroded.
   In a key race of Tuesday's election, Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek
was re-elected for a sixth term. But he lost control of the city
council as religious parties increased their representation to
nearly half the city council.
   The biggest gains were made by such ultra-Orthodox parties as
Shas, Agudat Israel and Degel Hatorah. Their success will probably
give them more power than the traditional, more moderate Orthodox
parties.
   The religious gains also could fuel tensions between secular and
observant Jews in the city, because Kollek will need to enlist the
support of the ultra-Orthodox to govern, Israeli news reports said.
   But the 77-year-old Kollek, who has been in office since 1965,
said he still expected to control the city. ``I will ... give other
people an ulcer instead of getting one myself,'' he said.
   Shlomo Lahat, Likud mayor of Tel Aviv, also won re-election.
   The results in Haifa, where Labor Mayor Aryeh Gurel was in a
tight race with his Likud rival, were uncertain after a dispute
developed today over the counting of ballots, Israel radio reported.
   Likud appeared to have won several Labor strongholds, including
the southern port of Ashdod and the town of Beersheba in the Negev
Desert.
   Israel and army radio said Likud also won several communities
around Tel Aviv that Labor had held, including Holon, Petach Tikvah
and Ramat Gan.
   Ultra-Orthodox religious parties scored gains throughout the
country, repeating their success of the November general elections,
according to unofficial results based on 43 percent of the vote.
   At stake were 147 local councils and mayoralities. In the last
national municipal elections in 1983, Labor won in 54 towns,
compared to 26 taken by Likud. The remainder went to local slates or
religious parties.
   Shamir, who had billed the elections as a referendum on Israel's
refusal to negotiate peace with the PLO, said on Israel radio the
results ``will signal to various people in the world, so they know
who is dominant in the Israeli political system, who is the one who
determines, who has the stronger voice.''
   ``There is no doubt that the elections ... show Likud is getting
stronger and at the same time the majority ... supports its
political positions.''
   Peres acknowledged in a radio interview that Labor ``has
definitely been dealt a blow, and I don't want to underestimate its
force.''
   But he disputed claims the results showed wide public support for
Likud's views on the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Officially both Labor and Likud oppose Palestine Liberation
Organization participation in peace talks, based on a claim that it
is a terrorist organization. But there are growing calls inside
Labor to reconsider this policy now that PLO chairman Yasser Arafat
has said he renounces terrorism and recognizes Israel's right to
exist.
   Labor leaders, including Peres aides, have met recently with
prominent Palestinians in the occupied territories who are known to
be PLO supporters.
   Energy Minister Moshe Shahal of Labor said his party's losses
were a further sign of the decline of the party that has failed to
win any of the last four general elections. On the national level,
Labor and Likud have been governing in an uneasy coalition since
1984, with neither party able to score an outright victory in
general elections.
   About 48 percent of Israel's 2.7 million voters went to the polls
on Tuesday, down from 55 percent in 1983. Voters cast two ballots,
one for mayor and the second for a party slate for city council.
   In Jerusalem, Kollek won 64 percent, while his slate received 12
of 31 council seats, down from 17. Religious parties, meanwhile,
increased their seats from 10 to 15.
   Kollek lost his majority in part because of the boycott of east
Jerusalem's 80,000 Arab voters, traditionally Kollek backers. Fewer
than 2 percent went to the polls, compared to 18 percent in 1983.
   The boycott was ordered by the PLO-allied leadership of the
15-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip. The leaders called a general strike
Tuesday to enforce the order and urged Palestinians to punish those
who ignored the boycott.
   In the Arab sector, Islamic fundamentalists ousted the communist
leadership of the second-largest city, Umm el Fahem, causing concern
that anti-Israeli sentiment is spreading among Israeli Arabs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
