<FIRST>r i PM-SnowlessOslo 1stLd-Writethru a0420 03-01 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Snowless Oslo, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0420,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Hauled in By Rail to Battle The Winter that Wasn't</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS one graf for 4th graf pvs, ``Last month ...'' to ADD average
temperature for February. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``The nice ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trains loaded with snow have been rattling
into this usually frozen capital in a costly battle to create the
winter that wasn't and save an annual tradition.
   A record warm winter threatened to melt away the Holmenkollen Ski
Festival, which begins Thursday, so organizers hauled in 5,600 tons
of snow by rail at about 1.5 cents a pound to rescue the event.
   ``Snow costs about the same per pound as wholesale sugar,'' said
Knut Almquist, secretary general of the Association for Promotion of
Skiing, which has organized the annual festival since 1892.
   Oslo and southern Norway experienced the mildest January ever
recorded. State meteorologist Oernulf Fremming said January was a
balmy 28 degrees above normal, and Oslo's February's average of 36.7
degrees was nearly 12 degrees warmer than the month's normal average
temperature of 24.8 degrees.
   The nice weather has left the Holmenkollen ski jump and
cross-country trail near Oslo without snow as its annual highpoint
approached _ four days of World Cup competitions that begin Thursday.
   Two of the week's major events, a World Cup 90-meter ski jump and
the annual ``Monolith'' cross-country ski race in Oslo's Frogner
Park have already been canceled.
   The state railroad NSB was hired to scoop up mountain snow from
the center of the country and ship it 186 miles by flatcar to
Holmenkollen.
   Railroaders joked that snow might be a important new cash crop.
   A giant Boeing Chinook twin-rotor helicopter had been slated to
carry flakes aloft and create its own blizzard above Holmenkollen,
but was grounded by fog, Almquist said.
   A lack of snow has not stopped Holmenkollen ski jumpers since
1925, and the association will do almost anything to save the event,
he said.
   ``It would cost more to cancel than to ship snow. Our insurance
pays for covering the ski area in snow but not for cancelling or
moving the event,'' he said of the more than $150,000 snow purchase.
   ``We'll take care of the snow if only nature will arrange the
cold weather,'' he said.
   High temperatures and a steady drizzle had threatened to wash
away transplanted snow _ but more recent colder weather and snow
flurries have raised hopes, he said.
   Tuesday's high in Oslo was 41 degrees, the low 36.
   The warm spell has left Norway's ski manufacturers, southern
resorts and even the ski association strapped for cash but brought
the railroad a windfall.
   ``We wouldn't mind seeing more ski races like this. It's great
for business,'' joked Per Kristian Flaten of NSB. ``We really do
hope the jumps and races go as planned after everyone's efforts.''
   NSB's Olav Hollerud, who engineered the snow lift, said 13 trains
have hauled 300 flatcars, each carrying 18.7 tons of snow, from the
mountains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0084 </DOCNO>
