<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DCCurfew     03-01 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC Curfew,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Law Would Impose 11 p.m. Weekday Curfew on Youngsters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law passed by the District of Columbia
Council in an effort to fight the city's soaring crime rate would
impose a curfew of 11 p.m. on weekdays and midnight on weekends for
people under 18 years of age.
   The temporary measure passed Tuesday would allow police to detain
violators at police stations until a parent or guardian signs for
their release. Those not picked up would be held until 6 a.m. the
next day.
   The measure, introduced as emergency legislation by council
member Frank Smith, calls for fining parents and guardians of repeat
offenders $100 to $500.
   Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr. has 10 days to sign the bill, which
would put it into effect immediately, or veto the measure. He has
taken no public position on it.
   City Corporation Counsel Frederick D. Cooke Jr. said his office
would study the legislation thoroughly before advising the mayor
whether or not to sign it.
   If approved, the curfew would expire after 90 days unless
permanent legislation is enacted.
   It would exempt young people engaged in ``specific business or
activity'' related to ``legitimate employment'' after the curfew
hours, but they would have to obtain an affadavit signed by a parent
or guardian and an employer.
   Some police officers said the curfew would be difficult to
enforce and would add to patrol officers' overburdened workload.
</TEXT>
