<FIRST>r i PM-France-Rushdie     03-01 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Rushdie,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer Deletes ``Allah'' Song From Repertoire Following Threats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French singer Veronique Sanson has withdrawn a pop
song entitled ``Allah'' from her repertoire following bomb threats
to the concert hall where she is performing.
   ``We made this decision ... after having received sufficient
threats to make us not want to run useless risks,'' the singer's
spokesman, Jean-Pierre Domboy, said today.
   None of the callers to the theater identified themselves, Domboy
said.
   ``I received frightful threats,'' Ms. Sanson said in a radio
interview following her opening performance Tuesday night at Olympia
music hall.
   She said callers said they would place bombs in the concert hall
and threatened to kill her and the musicians.
   Authorities had no comment about the reported threats.
   The incident comes amid controversy over the novel ``The Satanic
Verses'' and Iranian threats to kill its author, Salman Rushdie.
Many Moslems say the novel is blasphemous.
   Interior Minister Pierre Joxe has said security precautions have
been taken since Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini called
for Rushdie's death on Feb. 14. Joxe did not elaborate.
   Publisher Christian Bourgois, which will publish the French
version of Rushdie's book, is known to be under protection along
with three newspapers and weeklies that have published extracts.
   Ms. Sanson defended her song, a plaintive refrain about war and
misery.
   ```Allah' is absolutely not an insult, either for Islam or the
name of Allah,'' she said. ``It is, rather, a song of prayer and
love.''
</TEXT>
