<SECOND>PM-St Pete Mayoral,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Faces Runoff Election After Coming In Second</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Robert Ulrich faces a runoff
against a former state legislator after finishing second in a
four-way election.
   Ulrich, 55, will face 50-year-old Dennis McDonald in the March 28
runoff, prompted when no candidate received more than 50 percent of
the vote Tuesday.
   McDonald received 15,101 votes to Ulrich's 13,849.
   McDonald and the two other candidates, Sherman Seaborn and Freddy
Lopez, led an unsucessful recall effort in 1987 against the
first-term mayor, a lawyer and bank board chairman who has staunchly
supported downtown redevelopment.
   During Ulrich's two years in office, the city completed
waterfront renovations and began building a major league baseball
stadium.
   Opponents complained that downtown has been improved at the
expense of neighborhoods and basic city services.
   McDonald, who served in the House in the 1970s, organized a
recall effort because of disgust over back-to-back tax increases.
His group tried to oust the entire City Council, but the effort
failed to collect enough signatures.
