<FIRST>u w PM-PersonalIncome     03-01 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Personal Income,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Personal Income Up 1.8 Percent In January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income shot up 1.8 percent
in January, the biggest increase in more than a year, while the pace
of consumer spending was nearly flat after a strong gain in
December, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said income rose $74 billion to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $4.28 trillion in January,
following a 0.9 percent increase in December and a 0.2 percent drop
in November.
   January's income gain was the biggest monthly increase since a 2
percent jump in October 1987.
   Personal consumption spending, meanwhile, edged up just 0.1
percent in January to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $3.35
trillion, following a 0.8 percent gain in December and a 0.4 percent
jump during November. The figures include virtually all consumer
spending except interest payments on debt.
   January's 0.1 percent increase was the weakest performance for
consumer spending since a 1.5 percent decrease last September.
   A slowdown in consumer spending would be welcome news because of
worries that demand has been outstripping the production
capabilities of factories coping with high operating rates and tight
labor markets.
   The increase in income was paced by a 1.2 percent gain in the key
component of wages and salaries, reflecting continued strong
employment.
   The recent income gains were bolstered by several special
factors, including a 4.1 percent pay raise in January for federal
civilian and military personnel, a 4 percent cost-of-living increase
in Social Security benefits in January, and a December increase in
farm subsidy payments, the Commerce Department said.
   But even excluding such special factors, personal income still
increased 1.6 percent in January and 0.8 percent in December.
   Americans' disposable, or after-tax, incomes rose 1.7 percent in
January, after rising 0.9 percent in December and falling 0.3
percent in November.
   With the income gain strongly outpacing the rise in spending, the
personal savings rate, savings as a percentage of disposable income,
rose to 5.8 percent from 4.3 percent in December.
   Spending was held back by a 3 percent decrease in spending on
durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to last at least three
years. Purchases of services, which includes housing costs, were up
0.5 percent. Purchases of non-durable goods rose 0.9 percent.
</TEXT>
