<DOCNO> AP890301-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-ConstructionSpending     03-01 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Construction Spending,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Up 0.4 Percent in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending rose 0.4 percent in
January, led by a strong increase in work on non-residential
projects such as factories, offices and motels, the government said
today.
   Building activity rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
$424 billion in January, following a 2.1 percent increase in
December and a 1.3 percent jump in November.
   January's 0.4 percent increase was the weakest performance since
a 0.3 percent rise last October. Rising interest rates have dampened
activity in most sectors, with fixed-rate mortgages averaging 10.78
percent last week compared with 9.87 percent a year earlier.
   In January, residential construction rose 1.1 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $204.6 billion, reflecting an unchanged pace of
building activity on single-family homes and a 3.7 percent gain in
apartment construction.
   Apartment construction generally has been sluggish in recent
months, held back by high vacancy rates and reduced tax incentives
for investment in such projects. The category had declined 0.9
percent in December.
   Non-residential construction, meanwhile, rose 4.3 percent in
January to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $99.1 billion. Hotel
and motel building was up 8.7 percent and factory construction rose
7.3 percent.
   Activity in the industrial sector has been bolstered over the
past year as manufacturers expanded capacity to meet rising demand
generated by strong export sales, although the pace of exports
slowed during the last quarter of 1988.
   Construction of office buildings was up 2.2 percent during
January, while work on religious facilities rose 11.1 percent and
other commercial projects increased 5 percent.
   Government construction, meanwhile, declined 4.9 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $81.7 billion. The largest category for
government construction, highways and streets, was down 10 percent.
</TEXT>
