<FIRST>r a PM-LimerickSuit     03-01 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Limerick Suit,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Court Orders NRC to Reopen Limerick Licensing Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has ordered the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission to reopen licensing hearings for a
nuclear power plant 25 miles from Philadelphia because the NRC
disregarded safety modifications.
   An opponent of the Limerick plant hailed Tuesday's ruling by the
3rd U.S. Court of Appeals.
   The court said the NRC's failure to consider safety design
alternatives could have affected the decision in 1985 to grant a
full-power operating license to Philadelphia Electric Co.
   Spokesmen for PECO and the NRC declined to comment on the effect
of the ruling.
   But Charles W. Elliott, an attorney for plant opponent Limerick
Ecology Action, said the ruling forces the NRC to reopen the
licensing procedure.
   ``It certainly sets a precedent. It says that the NRC can no
longer violate the National Environmental Policy Act by refusing to
consider safer reactor designs. There is now no excuse for PECO not
to implement design changes to reduce accident risk,'' Elliott said.
   The Limerick plant, which went on line at full power in 1985, is
one of three operating in the country within 50 miles of a major
metropolitan area.
   Limerick Ecology Action had challenged the plant's licensing in a
lawsuit in 1987. The challenge to the Limerick license was supported
by the state and the national Union of Concerned Scientists in
friend-of-the-court briefs.
   ``We feel it's a big victory,'' said Limerick Ecology Action
president David G. Stone. ``Not only will it help us, it helps other
cases around the country.''
</TEXT>
