<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0493 03-01 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Ignore Cease-Fire Offer, Attack Garrison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with attacks on garrison, coffee plant, details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas today
attacked the main garrison of the easternmost province of La Union,
ignoring an army cease-fire and pleas to end the 9-year-old civil
war.
   Rebels late Tuesday also attacked a coffee processing plant that
local radio stations said belonged to the presidential candidate of
the rightist party favored to win elections scheduled this month.
   Insurgents of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said
they killed 67 soldiers and wounded 25 in the attack on the military
detachment in Santa Rosa de Lima, 110 miles east of San Salvador.
   The rebel report, broadcast on a clandestine radio station,
appeared to be greatly exaggerated.
   A military source, commenting on condition of anonymity, said
defenders of the detachment suffered ``some casualties'' but ``not
many.''
   The Armed Forces Press Committee, in a preliminary report, said
two guerrillas and one civilian were killed in the two-hour attack
on the garrison.
   The rebels also struck the Mecafe coffee processing plant outside
Nejapa, six miles north of San Salvador.
   A spokesman at the Nejapa Civil Defense post, contacted by
telephone, said the installation, which dries and bags coffee beans,
was completely destroyed by explosive charges detonated by the
rebels.
   About 20 soldiers stationed at the plant battled the attackers
briefly before retreating, said the spokesman, who commented on
condition of anonymity. He said no casualties were reported.
   Radio stations said the plant is the property of Alfredo
Cristiani, presidential candidate of Arena. The report could not be
immediately confirmed.
   Cristiani is favored to win the presidential election scheduled
for March 19. Arena has refused rebel demands to postpone the
elections.
   The military had said it would halt attacks at midnight and had
urged the guerrillas _ who are trying to negotiate participation in
national elections _ to also cease hostilities.
   The military announced the three-month halt in offensive
operations after the rebels offered to declare a unilateral
cease-fire of their own to help facilitate direct peace talks with
President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   However, the rebels rejected in their communique both the agenda
and venue for the talks that Duarte called for on Sunday.
   The armed forces said in a statement that the cease-fire took
hold at midnight Tuesday and would last until June 1, Duarte's last
day in office.
   It did not say whether the military would abide by the truce if
the guerrillas kept up their attacks.
   On Jan. 24, the rebels offered to take part in and respect the
results of the presidential vote if it was postponed several months.
They have boycotted the decade's five previous national elections.
   Duarte had called for a three-month cease-fire and for talks on
ending the civil war to begin Tuesday in Guatemala. He also said he
favored holding the presidential vote on April 30.
   The rebels rejected the site, saying talks should be Saturday and
Sunday in San Salvador. They also balked at an unilateral
cease-fire, insisting a lasting truce should be part of the
negotiations.
   An estimated 70,000 people have been killed and 500,000 to 1
million people displaced during the civil war.
</TEXT>
