<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Budget     03-01 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Budget,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Slashes Defense Spending, Pledges to Battle Poverty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's government
has slashed defense spending and diverted funds to fight hunger,
illiteracy and provide homes for the homeless.
   The unprecedented reduction in defense spending was contained in
the government's budget for 1989-90, introduced in Parliament on
Tuesday by Finance Minister Shankarrao B. Chavan.
   Gandhi's government reacted to criticism that it is oriented
toward the rich by pledging to reduce official expenditures and
slapping new levies on cars, televisions, electronic goods, air
travel and hotel tariffs.
   Analysts said the budget was aimed at wooing the electorate, most
of them the rural poor.
   Gandhi came to power in 1984 after the assassination of his
mother and predecessor, Indira Gandhi. Under Indian law he is
required to call national elections by the end of the year.
   India will spend 2 billion rupees ($133 million) less on defense
in the 1989-90 fiscal year compared to the previous year's expenses,
Chavan said.
   India's armed forces, with the sixth largest army in the world,
has 1.3 million soldiers.
   The budget proposal calls for total spending of 821.6 billion
rupees ($54.7 billion) in the 1989-90 fiscal year, which runs from
April 1 through March 31. In 1988-89, the total budget was 735.6
billion rupees ($56.6 billion.)
   In February 1988, the exchange rate was an estimated 12 rupees to
$1. The current rate is 15 rupees to $1.
   Chavan pledged to spend 17 billion rupees ($1.1 billion) on
programs to fight hunger, illiteracy and provide housing for the
homeless. The amount is up by 5 billion rupees ($333 million) from
last year.
   The increased funds for such programs will be raised directly
from taxing the upper-middle classes, including an 8 percent
surcharge on annual incomes of more than 50,000 rupees or ($3,333).
   Government estimates for March 1988 indicate that 16.5 million
families, defined as a unit of five people, need housing in India,
meaning that 82.5 million people are considered homeless.
   Chavan said the nation was proud of the armed forces for bringing
``credit to our country when called upon to help other countries in
their hour of need.'' But he added: ``All of us recognize that there
is continuing need for implementing measures for greater cost
effectiveness.''
   India is spending 24 million rupees ($1.6 million) a day to
maintain 40,000 troops in neighboring Sri Lanka. They have been
stationed there since 1987 to enforce a peace accord aimed at ending
the 5-year-old Tamil separatist war.
   Besides maintaining its armed forces on the frontiers with China
and Pakistan, India is spending a huge amount to keep its control
over a Himalayan glacial ridge on the borders with Pakistan.
   The 50-mile-long Siachen glacier, the longest in the Himalayas,
is strategic because it overlooks China and Indian military
concentrations in the valleys nearby. There have been a series of
confrontations on the glacier since 1983. But the skirmishes
escalated into a major clash in September 1987, followed by several
more clashes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   03-01 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0889</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Feb. 28
   Democrat and Chronicle and Times-Union, Rochester, N.Y., on John
Tower:
   If, as some of his critics say, (John) Tower really is a
``problem drinker,'' ... then he can't be counted on to keep that
promise (not to take an alcoholic drink if confirmed as defense
secretary) _ however much he means to do so now.
   True, some people who drink too much just up and quit. But many
others need treatment. And the Senate can't assume that a guy with a
drinking problem will stop just because he says he will. ...
   It's too late for Tower to take back his promise. But the Senate
shouldn't be moved by it.
   What matters is the evidence. If it shows that Tower's drinking,
or his recent work for prominent defense contractors, would intefere
with his duties, he should not be confirmed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 27
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on the Supreme Court private
violence ruling:
   The U.S. Supreme Court held the other day that states are not
obliged by the Constitution to protect children from abuse by their
parents. While that may be a technically correct ruling, many
citizens undoubtedly will feel that the decision somehow falls short.
   The case before the court involved a 4-year-old Wisconsin boy
whose father beat the child so severely that he suffered brain
damage that left him retarded and facing the rest of his life in an
institution.
   What's disturbing, aside from the father's inhumanity, is the
fact that state authorities knew that the child, Joshua DeShaney,
had been abused repeatedly before the final attack that put the boy
in a coma.
   The boy's mother, divorced from the father and living in another
state, sued Wisconsin on grounds of violating Joshua's
constitutional rights to life and liberty by not coming to his aid
when authorities knew he was being abused.
   While legally in the clear, Wisconsin authorities can hardly
escape bearing some moral responsibility for what happened to Joshua.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 27
   Los Angeles Times on the Bush budget breakdown:
   President Bush sent his budget changes to Congress two weeks ago
with the flourishes appropriate to a kinder, gentler nation, but it
soon became apparent that his famed flexible freeze is more of the
same old formula of cutting domestic spending. ...
   The Congressional Budget Office is correct, however, when it
considers the ``base-line budget'' the amount of money, allowing for
inflation, that a program would have to get in the succeeding year
to provide the same service as in the previous year for as many
people as are eligible for the service.
   Bush has (claimed) that he has frozen defense spending and many
domestic programs in like fashion.
   But defense is getting an inflation adjustment of $10.2 billion
while the domestic programs are being held to the same dollar
amounts as in the current budget year. Thus his flexible freeze
really is a $9.6 billion cut from the base-line budget.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 26
   Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune on acid rain:
   Americans can join Canadians in rejoicing over the announcement
by President George Bush during his recent visit to Ottawa that his
administration will seek an acid rain treaty, for it provides
recognition by the executive branch, after nearly a decade of
shilly-shallying, that the problem exists on both sides of the
border.
   It also denotes a postive step toward resolving a major foreign
policy issue disrupting northern-border relations. ...
   Bush's announcement, coupled with a budget address which included
a timetable for reducing emissions and proposed legislation to
strengthen the Clean Air Act, signaled a welcome change of attitude.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 24
   Journal-World, Lawrence, Kan., on IRS Commisson Lawrence Gibbs:
   After 2{ years as head of the Internal Revenue Service, Lawrence
B. Gibbs is calling it quits.
   But it's not, he insists, because he's frustrated with his job.
In fact, Gibbs says, the IRS is getting better at processing tax
forms and providing customer service.
   But it's clear from his comments that there's still room for
improvement.
   Probably few federal bureaucrats have a more difficult job than
the person in charge of the IRS. It certainly appears that Gibbs'
successor has his work cut out for him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 27
   San Antonio Express-News on single-parent children:
   Bad news from the Census Bureau: The number of single-parent
households is up sharply since 1980, continuing a trend that goes
back three decades. More than 15 million U.S. children now live
apart from their mother or father.
   In 1960, only 7 percent of white children and 22 percent of black
were so labeled. In 1988, the figures were 19 percent and 54
percent, respectively. Thus an absolute majority of black children
are now being raised by a single parent.
   No government program can substitute for the economic and moral
benefits of growing up in a family with loving, authoritative role
models of both sexes.
   Until our culture finds a way to reverse the collapse of such
families, welfare dependency will continue to perpetuate itself.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
