<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   03-01 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: perpetuate itself.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 26
   Statesman-Journal, Salem, Ore., on a U.S.-Mexico border ditch:
   The proposal to dig a ditch on the U.S.-Mexican border near San
Diego has swollen into an issue out of all proportion to its size or
importance.
   It should quickly be acknowledged for what it is: an
ill-conceived and poorly managed project. ...
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service has so badly
bungled publicity that the original purpose of the four-mile-long
ditch is uncertain.
   Some say it is to improve drainage on a flat bit of mesa. ...
Others say the 8-foot-deep, 14-foot-wide ditch is intended to block
what is said to be the most popular route used by drug smugglers and
illegal aliens to drive across the border. ...
   There is a problem of drug trafficking and illegal entry across
our southern border. ...
   It is time for the U.S. to acknowledge that the long-term
solution to the border conflict lies not in more conflict but in
understanding and economic assistance _ in building fences, not
barriers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 23
   The Kansas City (Mo.) Times on Ralph Nader and thrifts:
   Ralph Nader, the consumer activist, is angered by the
administration's plan to restore stability in the thrift industry
because this plan is to be financed in part by the Treasury.
   Average taxpayers, Nader says, should not be made to bear any
part of the burden.
   Most of Nader's proposals read like something out of the
stagflation '70s, but one proposal _ for a .5 percent tax on stock
sales _ would be especially damaging.
   Taxing these transactions would be contrary to the interests of
every American who contributes and depends on a pension fund.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 27
   The Evening Sun, Baltimore, on John Tower:
   John Tower ... promises he will quit drinking if he is confirmed
(as defense secretary). ...
   But under the present circumstances, taking the pledge begins to
resemble a man who, about to be thrown out of the house, desperately
promises his wife, ``I'll never take another drink!''
   But even if the no-drinking pledge is helpful, Sen. Sam Nunn
points out that a bad odor still hovers over Tower because of his
relations with defense contractors, whom he served at great profit
after leaving the Senate in 1984.
   Tower maintains his consulting business violated neither law nor
propriety. Dozens of other former lawmakers and bureaucrats, Tower
points out, have become consultants.
   But in the arcane world of national security, secrecy is the
critical edge of advantage. Even if he betrayed no secrets to
defense contractors, Tower unquestionably relied on his knowledge of
those secrets in giving the advice for which he was so handsomely
paid.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 28
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on John Tower:
   John Tower's pledge to swear off alcohol if he is approved as
secretary of defense is no justification for the Senate to confirm
his nomination.
   If he does still have a serious drinking problem, this pledge ...
is not enough. He would need rehabilitation. ...
   Even more troubling, however, are the potential conflicts of
interest involving Tower's dealings with defense contractors. He
left the Senate as an arms negotiator in 1984 to become a highly
paid consultant.
   Even though he reportedly did not violate any laws in his
consulting business, he profited handsomely from his willingness to
trade on his government position and his knowledge of government
secrets. ...
   John Tower has been a terrible nominee from the start. A more
thorough FBI investigation should have uncovered that.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee _ the body that would have to
work closest with Tower _ was absolutely right in rejecting his
nomination after its long and thoughtful hearings.
   Tower should step aside and President Bush should put the
interests of the Defense Department and the nation far ahead of his
loyalty to his longtime Texas friend.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 22
   New Jersey Herald, Newton, N.J., on unnecessary Caesarean
operations:
   A study (by Public Citizen, a Washington consumer-advocacy group)
showing that approximately 500,000 Caesarean sections were performed
unnecessarily in U.S. hospitals during 1987 raised frightful
questions about the quality of medicine.
   The study ... reported that Caesarean operations ... climbed to a
new high for a 12th straight year.
   The ... group states that the use of Caesarean sections, rather
than normal labor, can increase the risk of death or illness for
mothers, substantially raise the cost of having a baby and exact a
``psychological toll'' on the mother.
   The C-section procedure of cutting through the abdomen and uterus
to deliver the baby averages more than $3,000 above the cost of
vaginal deliveries.
   If the medical profession cannot discipline its members against
unnecessary, dangerous and money-grabbing surgery, the undesirable
alternative for society may well be to invite government
surveillance and control of the profession.
</TEXT>
