<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   03-01 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the profession.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 24
   The Journal, New Ulm, Minn., on John Tower:
   Don't get the idea that John Tower was rejected as defense
secretary by the Senate Armed Services Committee just because he has
a reputation as a man who likes an occasional glass of wine and has
an appreciation for a well-turned ankle.
   Let's put it on a slightly higher level.
   Let's look at Tower's background in defense. As a senator, Tower
was chairman of the Armed Services Committee, and he was well-known
as a senator who ``never met a defense system he didn't like.'' (As
defense secretary), more likely he would be a rubber stamp for any
wish list the military gives him.
   After he left the Senate, Tower became a consultant to the
defense industry. In a couple of years he had received around a
million dollars in consulting fees from defense contractors. He and
defense contractors get along very, very well.
   This is the man who is supposed to go before Congress and make
credible, plausible arguments as to why we need this weapon or that
defense system, or why we should pay so much more money for this
project?
   The rumors of womanizing and drinking are the least of Tower's
problems. Let the Senate forget those rumors and judge the man
solely on his defense background.
   The vote against him should be overwhelming.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 23
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on sewage treatment:
   The new and higher Environmental Protection Agency cost estimate
for upgrading sewage treatment facilities prompted EPA Administrator
William K. Reilly to say, ``We must think cooperatively about how we
are going to solve waste water treatment problems.''
   He seemed to have in mind, with good reason, not only
collaboration in planning the execution of problems, but also
broader sharing of the enormous financial outlay required.
   In its report to Congress, the agency set this at $83.5 billion.
... The figure, incidentally, points up something we have cause to
be glum about: Congress approved the Clean Water Act in 1972, yet 17
years later the problems it addresses still plague the nation. ...
   With two-thirds of the nation's waste water treatment plants
deficient in some way, it is clear that we need to put more effort _
and that means more money _ into achieving what Congress intended 17
years ago.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 23
   Bangor (Maine) Daily News on the Salman Rushdie affair:
   The ayatollah (Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran) is meddling directly in
the internal affairs of other states (with his execution order for
``The Satanic Verses'' author Salman Rusdie).
   He is using a new form of terrorism _ state-funded assassination
_ to intimidate into silence the resident of a country where freedom
of expression is cherished.
   He has created a new threat to world commerce. If one nation
dislikes a product or process allowed in another, Khomeini has
established his own corollary to caveat emptor: Paint a bull's-eye
on the head of the foreign manufacturer.
   What began as just another strange, almost comical episode in the
reign of Khomeini has evolved into a broad confrontation over
principles of personal and economic freedom.
   The U.S. and its European allies must maintain pressure on the
Iranian government to lift the death sentence on Rushdie, a British
citizen of Indian heritage who has been made an international symbol
of the value of freedom of expression. The Iranians must not be
allowed to make him a martyr.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 24
   The Morning News Tribune, Tacoma, Wash., on Hirohito's funeral:
   Few Americans would have blamed George Bush had he chosen to skip
Emperor Hirohito's funeral. ... The president had personal reasons
not to honor Hirohito's memory.
   Like millions of other Americans, he was drawn unwillingly into
World War II as a result of Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor. While
serving as a naval aviator, he was shot down by the Japanese over
the Pacific Ocean in 1944.
   Historians today dispute Hirohito's role in the Japanese
aggressions of that era. But there's no question the emperor at
least reluctantly endorsed Japan's decision to wage war against the
United States and other Pacific powers. ...
   By attending the funeral, Bush made it clear that what happened
in the Pacific nearly a half-century ago no longer has any bearing
on America's relationship with Japan. And that relationship _
despite all the grumblings about trade balances _ is one of
friendship. ...
   World War II is history. America's future is now inseparable from
Japan's. Nothing could demonstrate those realities better than
George Bush's presence in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
