<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru a0507 03-01 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black African States Lose: U.N. To Buy Namibia Supplies From South
Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with General Assembly approval.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Britain, France ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly today approved $416
million for the U.N. peacekeeping mission to free Namibia from 74
years of South African rule.
   On April 1, the world body plans to begin implementing a one-year
plan to create the world's newest independent nation, in the process
settling the last major colonial problem in Africa.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I, when it
captured the former German colony. In December, Pretoria finally
agreed to cooperate with the U.N.'s one-year plan to make the
territory a sovereign state.
   The General Assembly was able to clear the last hurdle to
implementing the plan after its budget subcommittee, overriding
objections from several African nations, decided Tuesday night that
U.N. peacekeepers in Namibia may buy goods from South Africa as long
as it continues to be the cheapest supplier.
   Countries led by Zambia and Zimbabwe had delayed approval of the
assessment for the force by trying to make the United Nations heed
its own calls for trade embargoes on South African products.
   Britain, France and the United States opposed the restrictions on
purchases for the force, citing the higher cost of buying goods and
services elsewhere that are available from South Africa.
   Late Tuesday, the assembly's budget committee adopted language
that noted the embargoes but called on the United Nations to buy
from the lowest bidder among the ``widest possible sources of
procurement'' in the interest of ``economy and efficiency.''
   A dejected Zambian Ambassador Peter Dingiswayo Zuze said he
viewed the compromise as the ``best as can be.''
   U.N. fiscal controller Luis Maris Gomez pledged that the world
body would not buy helicopters from South Africa, as the black
African states had feared.
   He said peacekeeping troops would bring their own military
vehicles, but mine-resistant vehicles would be needed in the early
stage of the mission, and these would likely be leased from South
Africa.
   Other U.N. officials noted that South Africa is readily able to
supply the $10.2 million in gasoline and aviation fuel the Namibia
force will need.
   The black African states had proposed that fuel be bought from
Angola or the Congo _ a more expensive proposition.
   In December, the five permanent members of the Security Council
had clashed with the black African states over the size and cost of
the mission. The Africans wanted 7,500 peacekeepers sent, at a cost
of up to $700 million.
   The Security Council instead adopted the Big Five plan of sending
just 4,650 personnel, with the rest held in reserve.
   The Big Five _ the United States, Soviet Union, Britain, France
and China _ pay 57 percent of all peacekeeping costs.
   The U.N. mission in Namibia is to oversee November parliamentary
elections in the territory also known as South-West Africa.
   South Africa agreed to grant Namibia independence as part of an
accords signed in December that also call for the withdrawal from
Angola of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops who have aided that
country's Marxist government in a 14-year-old war against South
African-supported rebels.
</TEXT>
