<FIRST>u a PM-FloridaWildfires 1stLd-Writethru a0536 03-01 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Wildfires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0536,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blaze Moves Away From Power Line After Firefighters Bombed It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with officials optimistic over
weather forecast; PICKS UP 6th graf, `Firefighters dropped ...'; SUBS 8th
graf, `Today, forestry ...' to UPDATE with blaze contained.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Everglades wildfire moved away from a major
interstate power line today after firefighters in a helicopter
dropped incendiary bombs the size of ping-pong balls to create a
buffer in the drought-parched region.
   Downpours that drenched parts of the southern Florida coast
Tuesday brought only a few light showers to the fire zone, but
optimism grew today with more rain in the forecast.
   ``We're probably in better shape than we have been all week,''
forestry division spokesman Jim Whitson said. ``It looks like we've
got some moisture coming into the state right now, and things have
cooled down considerably.''
   Fanned by steady 10 mph winds, the 3-day-old blaze burned an
estimated 12,000 acres before stalling at a drainage canal at the
Palm Beach County line northwest of Fort Lauderdale early this
morning, forestry officials said.
   Thick smoke from burning resins in sawgrass and melaleuca trees
forced the Florida Highway Patrol to close eight miles of highway
for about an hour Tuesday, and prompted complaints from as far as 30
miles away in Palm Beach, state forestry spokesman John Kern said.
   Firefighters dropped incendiary bombs from a helicopter to start
backfires designed to keep the 10-mile-long wall of flame away from
interstate power lines serving more than 3 million South Florida
residents.
   Florida Power &amp; Light Co. shut off power on the three
500,000-volt lines for four hours during Tuesday's operation. No
blackouts were reported. In 1985, a fire that burned more than
100,000 acres engulfed power lines and caused widespread blackouts
in southern Florida.
   Today, forestry officials on the western side of the Everglades
contained a 4,050-acre fire that burned through cypress and
palmetto-dotted scrubland, duty officer Debra Carter said. Officials
planned to use incendiary bombs on the blaze later today to burn
remaining fuel.
   That blaze was stalled just south of Alligator Alley, a two-lane
highway connecting Fort Lauderdale to the Gulf coast, said Fort
Myers forestry officer Roberta Smith.
   The two wildfires were the largest of more than 65 fires the
forestry division has fought since Monday with about 400
firefighters, said Charles Maynard, spokesman for the agency in
Tallahassee.
   Tuesday's rainfall caused flooding that closed the main runway at
Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport for two hours. The
rain also caused a rush-hour mudslide onto Interstate 95 that backed
traffic up for six miles.
   But little of it hit wilderness areas, where rainfall has
averaged less than half normal levels since last fall.
   The National Weather Service forecast scattered showers in some
parts of the state over the next few days, but nothing that would
alleviate the growing fire danger, Maynard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
