<FIRST>u a PM-AgentKilled     03-01 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Killed,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Drug Agent Shot To Death On Dead-End Street</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today searched for a paroled killer
suspected of shooting to death an undercover federal drug agent in
the officer's car.
   Everette Hatcher, 46, was shot three times _ in the eye, ear and
shoulder _ on a dead-end street in a remote area on Staten Island on
Tuesday night, police sources and the Drug Enforcement
Administration said.
   A backup surveillance team found the agent dead minutes after the
shooting, which neighbors reported hearing.
   The slaying was the first of a federal drug agent in the New York
area in more than a decade.
   The agent, assigned to the New York DEA office, had gone there to
meet Constible Farace, a 28-year-old New Yorker from whom he had
bought drugs before, said Robert Strang, a spokesman for the DEA's
New York office.
   The agent had not gone to buy drugs and was not carrying money or
drugs, Strang said.
   Strang said authorities believe Farace showed up at the meeting,
and he said the man is a suspect in the slaying. The DEA, the FBI
and police were searching for him. ``We believe he's on Staten
Island,'' Strang said.
   Farace, whose street name is Gus, had been released from prison
in Elmira in 1988 after serving nine years for manslaughter, said
police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. He was on parole
until 2002, the sources said.
   Asked whether the agent's cover might have been blown, Strang
answered: ``At this point we're not speculating anything. Anything
is possible.''
   ``His window was down, his foot was on the brake and it appeared
as if he had rolled down the window to talk to somebody,'' he said.
   ``We've had agents killed around the country, but this one here
is the first time we've had an agent killed here in over 10 years,''
Strang said.
</TEXT>
