<SECOND>AM-BRF--Philippines-Explosives,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seize Explosives Near U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized about 9,000 sticks of
dynamite and other explosives in a jeep that stopped near the U.S.
Embassy early Wednesday, police said.
   Officers were questioning four men who said they were hired to
transport the explosives to the northern province of Ilocos Sur,
according to police Capt. Rodolfo Ribal.
   Ribal said the men told him they did not know what the explosives
were for. He said the shipment was seized when a ``suspicious
looking'' jeep drove by two police patrol cars parked outside the
U.S. Embassy.
   Ribal said the explosives were buried under other goods loaded in
the jeep. ``It's possible the explosives were intended for illegal
fishing or something else, but it's possible they intended to use it
(for terrorism) here,'' Ribal said in an interview.
