<FIRST>r w AM-DCTourism     03-01 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC Tourism,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Tourism Grows Despite Crime Wave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trade group official says tourism in the
nation's capital grew by a ``comfortable rate'' last year despite a
drug-related crime wave in the city.
   ``Fortunately, we haven't found it affecting us,'' said Marie
Tibor, director of tourism for the Convention and Visitors
Association, a trade group that encourages tourists to visit the
city. ``We've had a nice comfortable rate of growth.''
   About 19.6 million visitors came to the Washington area last
year, up 3 percent from the previous year, according to the
association's annual report scheduled for release next month.
``We've done better than some of the previous doom-and-gloom
forecasts,'' she said Tuesday.
   The district had a record 372 homicides last year, and police
said 60 percent of them were related to drugs. A total of 91 people
were slain in January and February of this year, compared with 54 in
the same period last year.
</TEXT>
