<FIRST>u w PM-BennettConfirmation 4thLd-Writethru a0593 03-01 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett Confirmation, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0593,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biden Vows to Run Political Interference for Bennett</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with comments from Bennett, Simon;
picks up at pvs 4th graf pvs, Bennett was; trims throughout to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett Jr., President Bush's choice
to run the nation's war on drugs, said today that despite
pessimistic talk about his chances for success, he believes he can
help ``bring some change for the better soon.''
   At his confirmation hearing as director of national drug control
policy, Bennett told the Senate Judiciary Committee: ``I've been
struck ... these last few weeks, as I've met with people inside
government and out, by the pessimism, even fatalism, people have
about our mission in the war on drugs.
   ``Some have told me they wouldn't wish this job on their worst
enemy; others have made clear they think the war is already lost,''
he said. ``I think we must disagree. There are things that can be
done.''
   Bennett said he shared the concern of committee Chairman Joseph
R. Biden Jr., D-Del., about promising too much too soon.
   ``But at the same time, I remain convinced that concerted,
intelligent effort and strategy, if implemented, can bring change
for the better _ and bring some change for the better soon,'' said
Bennett, who was education secretary during the Reagan
administration.
   Biden extended some bipartisan support to Bennett, saying he
would run ``political interference'' for him if necessary.
   Biden told Bennett at the opening of his confirmation hearing
that ``as long as you make a good-faith effort to comply with this
statute (creating the post), you will have my personal and political
support ....''
   ``I personally will run all the political interference that you
need,'' said Biden, who worked for eight years to create the drug
czar position.
   Although the overwhelming tenor of the opening statements by
committee members was supportive of Bennett, Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., said he was ``somewhat troubled'' by the nomination and
might not vote for him.
   ``If we were to elect a national gadfly in this area, you would
have my vote,'' Simon said.
   The senator said that when Bennett was education secretary and
complained about the drug problem, he told other Cabinet secretaries
_ the secretaries of state and defense and the attorney general,
among others _ what they should be doing to fight the drug battle.
   ``In your own department, where you had a chance to do something,
you asked for a cut in one-half of the money for the drug problem,''
Simon said.
   ``If I vote no, and I think I may be the only one, I hope you do
a job that will make my vote wrong,'' Simon said.
   Bennett was introduced and endorsed by four senators and a House
member: Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Alfonse M. D'Amato,
R-N.Y.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; and Terry Sanford, D-N.C.; and Rep.
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Select Committee on
Narcotics Abuse and Control.
   Biden reiterated today his criticism of Bush for not giving
Bennett Cabinet status.
   ``At one time or another, you will have to go to the mat with
everyone of your Cabinet colleagues and you need to meet them on
equal terms in the decisive forum, the Cabinet Room,'' he said.
Biden described the job before Bennett as ``a Herculean task,'' and
said Bennett was ``bound to fail'' in some of his efforts.
   However, Biden said he would only criticize Bennett if he failed
to come up with a strategy to deal with the drug problem and did not
take full advantage of the powers his position holds.
   He said the position ``may be our last best chance to take hold
of an epidemic wave'' of drug abuse.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, the ranking Republican on
the Judiciary Committee, praised Bennett and said his initial doubts
about the wisdom of appointing one person to coordinate all federal
anti-drug activities had been relieved.
   In advance of the hearing, Biden said in a television interview
today that Bennett's pugnacious reputation as education secretary in
the Reagan administration will serve him well in his new job.
   Bennett is ``going to have to be combative, he's going to have to
be tough, he's going to have to be a real scrapper,'' Biden said on
ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
   ``The very things that made Bill Bennett controversial as
secretary of education are things that may make him particularly
useful as the so-called drug czar,'' Biden said. ``He was never
afraid of controversy, he was never afraid of being critical.
   ``This first drug director is going to have to be willing to take
on other Cabinet members ... and going to have to be willing to be
controversial,'' the committee chairman said.
   According to the bill passed last year creating the post, the
director must compile in his first 180 days a comprehensive drug
control strategy encompassing all aspects of the battle against
illegal drugs, from law enforcement here and abroad to treatment
programs for addicts.
   It may be that he's already leaped the toughest personal hurdle,
as he quit his two-pack-a-day cigarette smoking habit, Tell said.
   Although Biden said he doesn't care about the smoking, Bennett
made a commitment Jan. 12, the day President Bush nominated him to
become drug director, to stop smoking by the time he took office.
   He kicked the habit by attending a stop-smoking clinic, called
``Breathe Free,'' when he, his wife Elayne and son John went to the
Coolfont resort in Berkeley Springs, W.Va., last week, Tell said.
   ``I went in his office and there's no ashtray,'' said Tell, but
there are some crutches _ a bowl of fruit and lollipops.
</TEXT>
