<FIRST>r a PM-ScienceOverhaul     03-01 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Science Overhaul,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltimore Bows Out of National Effort To Change Science Curriculum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baltimore's school district has bowed out of a
national program to overhaul the way ycnence is taught because the
superintendent says he doesn't want his teachers to lose classroom
time working on the"soject.
   Superintendent Richard C. Hunter said the district will not
participate in the four-year, $10 million project, an unprecedented
nationwide effort to help American students catch up with their
peers in other countries.
   Project 2061, sponsored by the American Association for the
Advancement of Science and several other scientific institutions,
will bring teachers together, often with top scientists, to rethink
the way science, math, and history are taught.
   Baltimore was invited to participate, along with the school
systems of San Francisco; San Diego and San Antonio, Texas; two
smaller systems in Georgia, and one in Wisconsin.
   ``To have Baltimore out there as one of the national leaders
would have been nice,'' F. James Rutherford, director of the
project, said in today's The (Baltimore) Sun.
   ``I must say, in a way it's sad, because Baltimore is really a
very special place. If it works, it will really be one of the most
important changes in education in a long time.''
   Hunter told Rutherford that he did not want to spare teachers
from the city's classrooms.
   The plan would have required 20 teachers to be out of class three
or four days a month, and meet during the summer as well, for the
next two to three years.
   ``I can't blame him,'' said Rutherford. ``Our project would put a
tremendous demand on a district. The superintendent felt that given
his agenda it was just too ambitious a project for him to get into.''
   Rutherford said the project, named for the year in which Halley's
Comet will return, plans to arrange for substitute teachers to help
districts that take part.
</TEXT>
