<FIRST>r a AM-CrackHouse     03-01 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack House,0241</SECOND>
<UNK>Government Seizes Home Of Blind Man, 77, Who Sold Crack</UNK>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities said they will
seize the home of a 77-year-old blind man convicted last year of
selling crack cocaine from the house.
   Willie Frank Dudley was given two days Tuesday by the U.S.
Marshal's Service to move. He said he did not sell crack at the
house, but it was kept there. He denied having any involvement with
the drug himself.
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' he said.
   ``Blind people can be judges and bankers and can function in all
walks of life, and blind people also can become drug dealers, so
they're treated equally,'' Police Chief David Thompson said.
   Dudley has a criminal record that includes dealing crack cocaine
from the house, Thompson said. It was seized as a result of Dudley's
1988 arrest and conviction on the sale of crack.
   Dudley said he was blinded by a shooting in 1961 in front of the
house.
   The small wooden house and the half-acre of property are worth
about $20,000, Thompson said.
   The property was seized under the federal Controlled Substances
Act because police determined it had continually been used as a
storage place for crack cocaine, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Dorothea Beane.
   He can appeal the seizure by filing a claim of intent to hold
onto the property within 10 days.
</TEXT>
