<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FlagSuit     03-01 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Suit,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses NAACP Suit Over Rebel Banner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today threw out an NAACP
lawsuit seeking to remove the Confederate flag atop Alabama's
Capitol, ruling the banner did not violate the constitutional rights
of blacks.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Varner said the NAACP failed to show
that the flying of the flag somehow created a form of segregation.
   Former state Rep. Thomas Reed and 13 other black legislators
attempted to remove the flag in 1988 but were blocked by law
enforcement officers and arrested. They were convicted of
trespassing and fined.
   Later, Reed, state president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, and the NAACP sued to remove the
banner.
   ``Removal of the flag is suggested for the purpose of relieving a
feeling of Mr. Reed and his fellow blacks rather than for the
purpose of eliminating segregation in state government,'' Varner
wrote.
   He pointed out that Reed and other blacks were a part of state
government and had not been ostracized by any means.
   Gov. Guy Hunt has said he will remove the flag only at the
request of the Legislature, which has killed past such attempts.
</TEXT>
