<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--GermanTerrorist     03-01 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--German Terrorist,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terrorist Released After 17 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Red Army Faction terrorist was released
from prison Wednesday after serving 17 years of a life sentence for
killing a policeman.
   Manfred Grashof was convicted of killing a Hamburg policeman in a
1972 gun battle and of being an accessory to the murder of a second
police official during a 1971 bank robbery in Kaiserslautern.
   He was pardoned three months ago by former Rhineland-Palatinate
state governer Bernhard Vogel. The pardon specified the March 1
release date.
   Vogel said at the time that Grashof, 42, had ``clearly
demonstrated that he had renounced terrorism.''
   In June, Vogel pardoned Grashof's accomplice in the bank robbery,
Klaus Juenschke, who had also received a life sentence for murder.
   Terrorist pardons are an emotional issue in West Germany, with
proponents saying the government should show mercy where prisoners
repudiate violent crimes. Opponents contend terrorists should pay in
full for the bloody bombings and assassinations that rocked West
Germany in the late 1960s and 1970s.
</TEXT>
