<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Right     03-01 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Right,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nagasaki Mayor Receives Threat for Remark on Emperor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Nagasaki received a bullet enclosed in
a threatening letter Wednesday over his remark that the late Emperor
Hirohito bore some responsibility for World War II, a police
spokesman said.
   It was the second time in a week Mayor Hitoshi Motoshima received
threatening mail.
   The letter, signed by the unknown All Japan Patriotic Front, read
in part, ``You better quit soon. If not you may be killed,'' said
Akira Nagashima of the Nagasaki city police. Similar threatening
mail was delivered to Motoshima on Feb. 22.
   Nagashima said four policemen had been assigned to guard the
mayor to against rightist reprisals following his controversial
remarks about the emperor in December.
   At that time, Motoshima told a city assembly session that,
judging from historical accounts and his own wartime experience, ``I
believe the emperor shares responsibility for the war, as well as
all of us who lived in that period.''
   More than 100 sound trucks blaring rightist slogans drove through
Nagasaki streets to protest his remarks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
