<FIRST>u w PM-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0484 03-01 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel Refers Moonlighting Questions To Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 7 grafs new with decisions on outside income. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs, The panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's ethics commission agreed today
there should be a uniform limit on the outside income earned by top
government officials but called on Congress to set the limit and let
the President exempt some activities, such as scholarly writing.
   The eight-member panel completed its fifth and final working day
still sharply divided over moonlighting by judges, members of
Congress, top executive branch officials and the most senior aides
in all three branches.
   Their compromise recommendation was that Congress limit outside
earned income to a fixed percentage of an official's federal salary.
A majority of the group favored a figure closer to the 15 percent
which nows governs the executive branch rather than the higher
amounts allowed in Congress and the judiciary.
   And they asked that Congress allow to the president to exempt
from the limit income from categories of work that do not raise
ethical issues or interfere with the full performance of official
duties.
   They tried but failed to agree on a list of exemptions. Former
White House counsel Lloyd Cutler suggested listing teaching by
judges, among others. But former Attorney General Griffin Bell, who
wanted to exempt royalties, objected to exempting teaching.
   ``When you get above 15 percent of salary for teaching, you're
not a fulltime government worker,'' Bell said. ``You're not in your
office when you're teaching and you need to be there so other judges
can talk to you.''
   With that compromise, the panel completed work on the
recommendations due to go to Bush by March 9. The issue of
moonlighting income was the most divisive it encountered in a review
of all federal ethics laws and rules. This issue had consumed more
than an hour of debate on Tuesday.
   The panel was wrestling with questions such as how much money a
federal judge should be allowed to make teaching at a law school,
and whether federal officials should be allowed to make more money
writing novels or songs than from the government.
   These questions about the proper limits of income earned outside
government work have divided the commission more sharply than any
others it has confronted in four day-long meetings.
   The panel could not decide Tuesday whether to recommend a ceiling
on all outside earned income or whether certain activities should be
exempt from any ceiling because they pose no conflict of interest.
   At one point, former White House counsel Lloyd Cutler argued,
``Suppose you write a popular song one night; that doesn't belong to
the government.''
   To which former Attorney General Griffin Bell replied, ``We don't
want a government of songwriters.''
   Last week, the panel tentatively approved applying the executive
branch's outside-income limit _ 15 percent of the government salary,
with no exemptions _ to top officials of all three branches. There
is no limit now for judges; the House limits members to 30 percent
of salary and the Senate to 40 percent.
   Cutler argued, ``If the next Ernest Hemingway is deep in the
Internal Revenue Service, all he can get out of it is 15 percent of
a GS-14 salary or he'd have to quit.''
   Judy Bello, general counsel to the U.S. special trade
representative, replied that the ceiling would only apply to top
officials, at GS-17 and above.
   Cutler, however, found other examples: ``Suppose you work for the
Defense Department on the MX missile and you develop an idea for
hybrid corn one night that's worth $1 million _ you've got to give
it away.''
   ``I will dissent from a cap unless there are some totally
excepted categories of earned income, such as writing a popular
song,'' he said.
   Cutler said he had been called by a federal judge whose teaching
and legal writings bring him income greater than 15 percent of his
federal salary. He said the judge said he would quit the bench if
the cap were enacted by Congress.
   ``A judge teaching at an accredited law school is a fine activity
and there is not the shadow of the possibility of a conflict,''
Cutler said.
   Bell, who is a former appellate judge, responded, ``If you want
to be a judge, you ought to be a full-time judge.''
   Bell also said exemptions would send the message that ``we don't
think it's unethical not to give your full-time effort to your
government job.''
   Bello also backed the ceiling. ``I wouldn't want to drive a good
judge off the bench, but ... I oppose watering down the current
law.''
   ``These activities do take time from your work,'' she added.
``And public confidence can be undermined if public servants are
taking time from work.''
   The panel's chairman, Malcolm R. Wilkey, a former appellate
judge, advocated the exemptions, particularly for judges to teach
law. ``This interplay between a live judge and a law school is very
vital to our society.''
   If there are no exemptions, Wilkey said, ``We'll lose the
brightest minds _ people who've got the extra energy to do more
work. They're the big contributors to our society and we'll lose
them from government.''
   Fred Fielding, who was White House counsel for President Reagan,
said the panel seemed to be ignoring other kinds of outside earned
income, such as breeding race horses or rose-growing. Seeing no
reason to discriminate in favor of some outside activities over
others, Fielding said he leaned toward a cap.
</TEXT>
