<DOCNO> AP890301-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-BurlingtonProgressives Bjt   03-01 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burlington Progressives, Bjt,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Mayor Retiring, but Allies Can Continue the Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's third-party Progressive
Coalition is gearing up for an election in which it hopes to prove
that it can outlast its charismatic leader, Mayor Bernie Sanders.
   Sanders, often billed as the nation's only socialist mayor,
announced last fall that he would not seek a fifth term in city
elections March 7. He said he wants other Progressives to move up
the electoral ladder, in part to dispel the notion that the movement
is a ``one-man band.'' He plans to teach and write.
   Sanders, 47, was elected by 10 votes in 1981 over a 10-year Mayor
Gordon Paquette and a Democratic machine widely seen as having
atrophied. He promptly put his long-time leftist activism to work
building a political power base of his own in the Progressive
Coalition.
   He was re-elected three times by more comfortable margins,
winning in 1987 with 6,901 votes to 5,594 votes. And even his
critics, with a mixture of bemusement and grudging admiration, give
him credit for reinvigorating city politics.
   ``He brought a breath of fresh air to City Hall,'' said Patrick
Robins, owner of an office supply company and long-time Democratic
regular.
   U.S. News and World Report, not a publication known for radical
politics, picked Sanders in 1987 as one of the nation's 20 best
mayors. Meanwhile, Burlington, a city of 38,000 and the closest
thing Vermont has to a metropolitan area, has prospered and been
ranked high in national quality-of-life surveys.
   Love him or hate him, Robins said, ``Bernie Sanders will be a
tough act to follow.''
   A month ago, it looked as though Burlington's Progressive era
might end with Sanders' departure. The coalition picked as his
would-be successor Peter Clavelle, a city administrator with no
experience running for office and without the rhetorical flair and
propensity for bashing American corporate capitalism that has given
Sanders a national reputation.
   Clavelle, 39, faces tough opposition from Democrat Nancy Chioffi,
46, president of the Board of Aldermen and owner of a downtown
clothing and souvenir store. She has not only the Democratic
nomination, but support from Republicans. The GOP didn't even field
a candidate.
   Attacking Clavelle from the left is 48-year-old lawyer Sandra
Baird, whose fledgling Vermont Greens party advocates a moratorium
on ``development for profit.'' She denounces Sanders and Clavelle,
saying they've ``sold out'' to business interests.
   Initially, many political observers thought Clavelle was in
trouble, facing a single candidate backed by Democrats and
Republicans and likely to lose some of the hard-core left to Baird.
He also was criticized as bland, a mumbler unable to articulate
strong beliefs.
   But Clavelle appears to have turned things around, picking up
several key labor endorsements, solidifying support among peace
activists and Jesse Jackson Democrats.
   Clavelle, who helped develop several programs for women as chief
of the city's Community Economic Development Office, even picked up
an endorsement over his two female opponents from the local chapter
of the National Organization for Women. That was seen as a coup in a
university town with a strong feminist community.
   ``They're going to win, it's that simple,'' University of Vermont
political scientist Garrison Nelson said of Clavelle and the
Progressives.
   Nelson's view was supported by a poll published Sunday in The
Burlington Free Press, which showed Clavelle with 40 percent of
likely voters supporting him, 31 percent for Chioffi, 6 percent for
Baird, and 2 percent for Michael Hackett, an independent candidate
running on what he calls the ``tax revolt'' ticket.
   The telephone poll of 342 likely voters found 21 percent
undecided or refusing to answer. It had a margin of error of 6.5
percent. Those two factors appeared to leave open the possibility
that Chioffi still could win the race.
   Chioffi has emphasized her experience as a small business owner
and her belief that men and women and rich and poor are equal by
virtue of opportunity.
   ``(Clavelle) talks about helping the little guy, about helping
single mothers and poverty-stricken women,'' she told the Free
Press. ``I don't see anybody as being a little guy. Working people
are not little.''
   But that pitch of equality of opportunity has not resonated much
in a city schooled on eight years of Sanders' speeches about class
struggle.
   Clavelle says he will maintain the ideals of the city's
Progressives. He angered some of them when in his first batch of
campaign literature, he described himself as an ``independent''
rather than as a Progressive. And he does not embrace the socialist
label as Sanders does.
   But he says he wants to look out for the elderly, the poor and
``the little guy.''
   ``I'm no Bernie Sanders,'' Clavelle said. ``Our backgrounds are
different, our styles are different, but our political visions are
the same.''
</TEXT>
