<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Plane 1stLd-Writethru a0597 03-01 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Plane Lands In London After One Engine Stalls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout, engine given clean bill of health. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Orient DC-10 en route from Frankfurt to
Boston diverted to London's Gatwick Airport today after one engine
stalled, the airline said.
   Flight 47 touched down at Gatwick at 2:34 p.m. ``after a routine
two-engine landing'' and the 222 passengers and 10 crew disembarked
normally, an airline statement said.
   Airline spokesman Andy Plews said the No. 2 engine stalled on
takeoff from Frankfurt ``and instead of trying to restart the engine
in flight, the captain decided to divert to London Gatwick.''
   Mechanics checked out the engine on the tarmac, running it up to
full power in a test, ``and discovered that there was no problem
with it,'' he said.
   With its ``clean bill of health,'' Plews said, Northwest Orient
was assembling a new crew and planned to take off for Boston later
tonight.
   Meanwhile, he said, passengers were taken to an airport hotel for
dinner.
   Asked what might have caused the engine not to start, Plews said,
``We don't know, but it is possible for engines to do this
occasionally. It could be a lack of air flow through the engine
which can be caused by an atmospheric condition.''
</TEXT>
