<FIRST>u w PM-WatkinsConfirmation 2ndLd-Writethru a056sthedeal.ShorehamisonLongIsEnergySecretary
03-01 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Watkins Confirmation, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0565,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Watkins as Energy Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with full Senate approving Watkins; picks up
6th graf, Although he ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 99-0 today to confirm James D.
Watkins as energy secretary, handing the retired admiral the
``daunting challenge'' of refurbishing the Energy Department's
crippled network of nuclear weapons factories.
   The vote came less than four hours after the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee voted 19-0 to recommend that Watkins,
61, be made the first career military man to head the department
since it was created in 1977.
   J. Bennett Johnston, D.-La., chairman of the committee, told the
Senate that the job of reviving and cleaning up the nuclear weapons
complex was a top priority.
   ``It is perhaps the most daunting challenge that we have ever
given to anybody in the Cabinet ... anytime in the history of this
country,'' Johnston said.
   Johnston called Watkins ``a man of that substance and that
reputation,'' echoing the warm praise Watkins won during his
confirmation hearing last Wednesday.
   Although he has no experience in the conventional energy field,
Watkins developed an expertise in nuclear power during a 41-year
Navy career that included training in reactor technology as well as
the command of a nuclear submarine.
   Now he's about to enter battle against one of the Bush
administration's biggest challenges: revitalizing the Energy
Department's nuclear weapons complex and planning a long-range
cleanup operation that may cost $100 billion.
   The Energy Department spends about two-thirds of its budget,
which this year is $14 billion, on developing, building and testing
nuclear weapons for the Pentagon. The remaining one-third is spent
on conventional energy projects, mainly research.
   Key parts of the 12-state weapons complex are shut down because
of safety, technical and managerial concerns, leaving the United
States without the capacity to build nuclear weapons for the first
time since the dawn of the nuclear age.
   ``It's the most daunting management task I think we've ever given
to anybody I've seen in government,'' Sen. J. Bennett Johnston,
D-La., said during Watkins' Feb. 22 hearing.
   Sen. James A. McClure, R-Idaho, said that although the weapons
plant problems were created by past administrations, ``You, Admiral
Watkins, will be the man in the limelight or hotseat charged with
getting the situation effectively under control as quickly as
possible.''
   Watkins told his confirmation hearing the Energy Department's
weapons complex was ``antique, out-of-date, desperately in need of
change.'' He also ripped the department's management structure,
calling it ``a mess'' and vowing to install the core of a new
management team to oversee the plants within six months.
   Watkins is a 1949 graduate of the Naval Academy at Annapolis,
Md., and was hand-picked by the late admiral Hyman G. Rickover,
father of the modern nuclear Navy. He served as a submarine
commander, cruiser and destroyer force commander of the Seventh
Fleet and NATO commander of the Sixth Fleet before capping his
career as chief of naval operations, the service's top position. He
retired in 1986.
   The four-star admiral is not shy about stressing his relationship
with Rickover.
   ``I learned from him that the fulfillment of the mission of our
national defense and the protection of the environment were mutually
compatible objectives,'' Watkins told his confirmation hearing.
   He said one of his top priorities as energy secretary would be to
cultivate in department managers a commitment to safe operations of
the nuclear complex.
   ``All that fancy technology is useless, and perhaps even a threat
to society, unless we properly educate and train those entrusted
with its operation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
