<FIRST>u a PM-Cuomo-Shoreham 1stLd-Writethru a0458 03-01 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuomo-Shoreham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0458,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>State To Pay $1 To Buy Shoreham; Consumers Will Pay Much More To
Shut It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with key legislator saying he likes
the deal; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Jack Kulka ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo signed a new agreement to
buy the $5.4 billion Shoreham nuclear plant for $1 and dismantle it,
and a key lawmaker today said he likes the deal.
   Under the agreement, the Long Island Lighting Co. will let the
state tear down the never-used plant, which has had to wage
licensing battles since its completion in 1985 and nearly bankrupted
the utility with cost overruns and delays.
   ``It is time to end this matter once and for all and turn our
energies to new, productive measures for Long Island and the
state,'' Cuomo said Tuesday.
   Unlike a similar agreement last year, which was killed by state
legislators, Cuomo predicted this deal would succeed because it
largely bypasses the Legislature.
   State Senate Majority Leader Ralph Marino, a Long Island
Republican whose support for the plan is crucial to its success,
said today that he likes the deal. Shoreham is on Long Island, 55
miles from Manhattan.
   ``I think we should get the issue behind us, at least have some
kind of direction and this gives us stability,'' Marino said.
   Other reaction was mixed.
   Long Island business leaders contend the $2.5 billion loss that
Lilco plans to take on the plant during the next three years will be
passed to its customers, who already pay among the nation's highest
electric bills.
   Jack Kulka, of the Association for a Better Long Island, said his
business group was ``very, very skeptical'' because ``Shoreham
continues to rise from the dead.''
   But Suffolk County Executive Patrick Halpin, whose county is
where the plant is located, said: ``I am pleased that Long Island's
longest-running soap opera has finally gotten its cancellation
notice.''
   In December, the state Legislature refused to act on a deal
negotiated in June by Cuomo with the utility that would also have
had the state buy the plant for $1 and dismantle it. In that deal,
Lilco would have been guaranteed 5 percent rate increases for at
least three years, and possibly for a decade.
   At the time, key lawmakers said the deal was too expensive for
Lilco customers. Cuomo said the legislators were simply afraid to
face a politically tough situation.
   Under Tuesday's agreement, Lilco is guaranteed no particular
rates, which are decided by the state Public Service Commission.
Cuomo predicted the rates would be lower than proposed in the
earlier deal, probably less than 4.5 percent.
   ``Nobody is going to be responsible for the rates,'' quipped
Cuomo. ``It's wonderful.''
   Last week, however, the commission approved a temporary 5.4
percent rate increase for the utility.
   Cuomo said he made the new deal because he believed the federal
Nuclear Regulatory Commission was about to grant Lilco a license to
operate the plant at 25 percent of full power.
   The NRC last week announced a proposed rule change aimed at
revitalizing the nation's nuclear power industry by cutting down the
licensing process for plants to six years or less, compared with the
recent average of 13 years.
   Many utilities, swamped by debt from nuclear plant construction,
contend that long delays in obtaining an NRC license are a main
reason why no new plants have been ordered since the mid-1970s.
   The 800-megawatt Shoreham plant, which was proposed in 1966, has
thus far been unable to win anything more than a 5 percent testing
license from federal officials. That's largely due to the refusal of
Cuomo and Long Island officials to cooperate in emergency planning
for the plant.
   Cuomo and the officials long have argued that Shoreham should
never be allowed to open because the area around the plant couldn't
be safely evacuated during a nuclear emergency. Lilco disputed that.
   Tuesday's agreement is subject to approval by Lilco's board of
directors and shareholders, a process that utility spokesman Jim
Lois said would ``take approximately three months.''
   ``While the approvals for this agreement are being obtained, the
company will continue to vigorously pursue a full power operating
license for Shoreham before the Nuclear Regulatory Commission,''
said a Lilco statement.
   However, it said it would operate the plant only if shareholders
veto the agreement, which also requires approval by the Public
Service Commission, the state Power Authority and the Long Island
Power Authority.
   Assemblyman Paul Harenberg of Suffolk called the new agreement
``very unfortunate'' and said Cuomo is ``forcing the public to pay
for the foolishness and imprudence of the investors of Lilco.''
</TEXT>
