<FIRST>r a AM-People-Sajak     03-01 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Sajak,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hopes For `Kinder, Gentler' Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Sajak, host of a CBS-TV late night talk
show, has some complaints about his television neighbors, the
tabloid shows he says are too loud, too rude and too cruel.
   ``This whole trend will pass when someone stretches the limits
and a line will be crossed,'' Sajak said in a recent interview. ``It
might take someone getting killed on television, I don't know.
   ``Then we'll have a `kinder, gentler,' kind of television, to
borrow a phrase,'' said Sajak, who said he finds most disturbing the
shows which re-create crimes.
   ``The Pat Sajak Show'' is seen on about 195 stations, said its
host. He said the 90-minute show is doing well in a competitive
market that, depending on the hours of its broadcast, faces ``The
Tonight Show'' starring Johnny Carson'' and ``Late Night With David
Letterman'' on NBC or Fox Television's Arsenio Hall.
   Sajak said it was unlikely his show would overtake Carson's
top-rated, 27-year run.
   Sajak, who was host of the hit game show ``Wheel of Fortune'' for
seven years before getting his own late-night slot, still does his
game show, taping 10 shows on the weekend. He tapes the CBS show
weeknights.
</TEXT>
