<FIRST>r a AM-JuvenileArrest     03-01 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Juvenile Arrest,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>8-Year-Old Arrested by Base Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nellis Air Force Base officials are rethinking a
policy on dealing with juveniles after an 8-year-old boy was
arrested for hitting a security guard in the face with a pencil.
   Authorities say the boy was arrested by base security police,
charged with battery, read his rights and turned over to local
authorities. He was later released to his parents and the charges
were dropped.
   The arrest occurred after the boy tossed the pencil out the
window of a school bus, striking a sentry guarding the entrance to
the base on the northern edge of Las Vegas.
   The sentry was not hurt.
   Security guards boarded the bus and took the boy into custody
after he admitted tossing the pencil.
   Nellis officials said the boy was arrested under a new policy
designed to crack down on juvenile vandalism. They admit the boy's
actions may not have fallen under the vandalism category and say the
policy may be revised but not dropped.
   ``We could have handled it with more sensitivity,'' Maj. Victor
Andrijauskas, base spokesman, said Tuesday. ``Because of this
situation, the policy is being reviewed.''
   The boy's father, Sgt. Jim Warner, who works on the base,
declined to allow the family to discuss the matter publicly.
</TEXT>
