<FIRST>u a PM-PlaneEmergency 1stLd-Writethru a0502 03-01 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Emergency, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cargo Door Believed Found; Officials Not Sure They'll Retrieve It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf pvs, `We have ...' with details
on how cargo door could be raised.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radar has pinpointed an object believed to be the
cargo door that tore from a United Airlines jumbo jet, but federal
investigators say they aren't sure whether it can be retrieved from
under 16,800 feet of water.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said late Tuesday that
Navy radar tracked a large object 85 miles southwest of Honolulu
about 45 seconds after the pilot of Flight 811 reported an in-flight
emergency.
   Nine passengers were swept to their deaths when a 10-by-20 foot
section of the fuselage, including the cargo door, tore from the
right side of the Boeing 747 at 22,000 feet on Friday. Twenty-seven
others were treated for injuries.
   ``The radar picked up something that could be a large piece of
metal, possibly the cargo door,'' NTSB investigator Lee Dickinson
said Tuesday night.
   ``That information is going back to Washington, D.C., to see if
we can indeed determine ... that was the cargo door, and its exact
location.''
   Dickinson said the door would be ``very helpful to us in our
analysis,'' but added that he did not know whether the object could
be salvaged and the decision to try would be up to the full
five-member NTSB board.
   ``We have the location at the surface of the water,'' he said.
``You're talking about three miles (down), one can only guess where
that is.''
   Paul Wolcott, a technician and research submarine pilot at the
Hawaii Undersea Research Lab at the University of Hawaii, today said
the Navy is about the only agency with equipment capable of
recovering the door.
   Such a search would probably involve use of an underwater sonar
sled and a remote-controlled vehicle equipped with a camera, he
said. The vehicle could probably hook a line to the door so it could
be lifted to the surface, he said. The least likely possibility
because of the tremendous expense _ up to $40,000 a day _ would be
the Navy's Sea Cliff, one of the world's few manned research
submarines capable of reaching that depth, Wolcott said.
   Dickinson said the NTSB's field work was nearly completed and
investigators would leave Hawaii today and tomorrow.
   Earlier Tuesday, investigators reported that the same front right
cargo door had had a recent history of problems, including a seal
that was repaired in January.
   Investigators had not yet determined whether the recent repairs
were connected to the accident, said NTSB spokeswoman Drucella
Anderson.
   ``We just don't know that right now,'' she said.
   United Airlines spokesman Rob Doughty said the faulty door seal
had to be fixed before the plane could fly again, and other
electrical problems did not affect the plane's airworthiness.
   On Dec. 5, the door's electrical door-closing mechanism worked
intermittently, Doughty said. It was repaired, but failed again on
Dec. 13 and Dec. 22, he said. It was fixed in Chicago on Dec. 23 and
no further trouble was reported, he said.
   ``I might add, though, that it is completely proper to close this
door manually, and that's what was done,'' he said.
   Doughty said he did not know the details of the work on the
door's seal, but ``I don't think it was major.''
   Meanwhile Tuesday, United officials said a safety pin had to be
replaced in a rear cargo door of a Boeing 747 that was to fly from
Sydney, Australia. The repair delayed the arrival in Honolulu by 18
hours.
   Many passengers, however, said they did not mind the delay,
including Allen Hochberg of New York.
   ``How can you get aggravated at them for trying to save us?'' he
asked.
</TEXT>
