<FIRST>r a AM-SteroidsSeized     03-01 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steroids Seized,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Seize $500,000 Worth of Illegal Steroids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who picked up parcels the Customs
Service had singled out as suspicious was charged with smuggling
more than $500,000 worth of anabolic steroids into the United States
from Brazil, authorities said.
   About 135,000 doses of the body-building drug in pill and
injection form were seized over the weekend, said Edgar Adamson,
customs agent in charge in Los Angeles.
   ``At one time, at one location, this is the largest shipment ever
confiscated, we believe,'' Adamson said.
   Lowell D. Coble, 49, was charged in federal court on Tuesday with
four counts of smuggling and possessing the drugs for distribution.
The charges are punishable by up to eight years in prison and a
$500,000 fine.
   Coble was freed on $25,000 bond, said Garry Grotewold,
supervisory deputy for the U.S. Marshal's office.
   Authorities said a Customs Service mail technician at Los Angeles
International Airport spotted several suspicious looking parcels
marked for delivery to a Southern California post office box.
   After Coble picked up the parcels and was arrested, authorities
found lists indicated he had customers throughout the United States,
according to a customs affidavit.
   ``Steroid seizures have been increasing rapidly during the past
three years, with about a tenfold increase every year,'' said John
Hensley, assistant regional commissioner for the Customs Service.
``Last year, customs seized over 2 million units of steroids
nationwide.''
   Steroids are used to increase strength and muscle bulk, making
them popular among body builders. They are illegal if bought, sold
or imported without a prescription.
   Health experts say prolonged use of the drug without proper
medical supervision can contribute to heart trouble, sexual and
reproductive disorders, immune deficiencies, liver problems,
psychological disturbances and growth disorders.
</TEXT>
