<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MarineRecruiting     03-01 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marine Recruiting,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recruiters Disciplined In Marine Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps relieved 15 recruiters and
their commander of their duties in Pittsburgh for alleged
violations, including fabricating high school diplomas for recruits,
a newspaper reported today.
   The Pittsburgh Press quoted Marine Maj. Robert W. McLean, a corps
spokesman at Parris Island, S.C., as saying that six of the
recruiters face courts-martial on charges that will be filed within
the next few weeks.
   Punishment for the nine others ranged from forfeiture of pay to
letters of reprimand, he said.
   Investigators found recruiters provided as many as 17 diplomas
for recruits who never graduated from high school, the newspaper
said.
   In addition, the criminal records of some recruits were omitted
from enlistment papers, as were medical problems that could have
disqualified recruits from serving, the Press said.
   The investigation began in January after a suburban Pittsburgh
recruit became ill at boot camp on Parris Island and had to be
hospitalized for a severe ulcer his mother says she reported to the
recruiter, the newspaper said.
   Investigators later identified 82 others who may have been
recruited improperly.
   Thirty of the 83 recruits were discharged because of enlistment
problems, McLean said. The Corps retained 49 and has yet decided
what to do with the others.
   The head of the Pittsburgh recruiting office, Maj. George A.
Eberhart Jr., was relieved Feb. 14 of duties he had held since 1986.
   Maj. Donald Kappel, a corps spokesman in the Philadelphia
district headquarters, today confirmed that an investigation led to
the 15 recruiters being relieved of duty, but he declined to provide
other details.
</TEXT>
