<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Webster-ChemicalWeapons     03-01 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Webster-Chemical Weapons,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Could Easily Share Chemical Weapons: Webster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CIA Director William Webster said Wednesday
Libyan strongman Moammar Gadhafi's chemical weapons plant is so big
that he could easily share its output with other radical nations.
   ``The production capability is far more than Col. Gadhafi could
ever need or use by any stretch of the imagination,'' Webster told
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   ``Is this going to become just another form of currency, ... a
brokering capability?'' he asked.
   Webster also said Libya could have the capacity of targeting such
countries as Israel with chemical weapons if Gadhafi's forces obtain
air-to-air refueling capacity for their bombers.
   ``It moves it (the chemical weapons threat) off the battlefields
and puts it into the cities and strategic areas'' of the whole
Middle East, he said.
   Webster was asked by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., if elements of the
West German armed forces had aided Libyan efforts to obtain
air-to-air refueling capability.
   Webster said he would prefer to discuss the matter in a closed,
non-public session but told Helms, ``You're right on target.''
   Webster later declined to elaborate on his comment.
   Gadhafi has said the plant was built to produce pharmaceuticals,
not chemical weapons. Webster said that even if that were true the
facility could be converted to manufacture weapons within a day's
time.
   The CIA director did say, as he and other U.S. officials have
said before, that West German corporations as well as those from
other European and Asian countries have helped Libya acquire a
chemical weapons production capability, and that it ``would have
been virtually impossible'' for Libya to do that without such help.
   But he said the West German government _ after a period of
hesitation _ has become more willing to address the situation and is
moving to tighten export controls on the chemicals and technologies
needed to produce chemical weapons.
   Webster said that while there was an initial ``slowness'' on the
part of some countries to accept available intelligence information
that a problem of chemical weapons proliferation existed, that is no
longer true.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
