<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MultipleKillings     03-01 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Multiple Killings,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Simmons' Request For Waiver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSSELLVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Wednesday allowed R. Gene
Simmons, convicted of killing 14 relatives and two other people, to
waive his appeal and face possible execution March 16.
   Under a state Supreme Court ruling in an earlier Simmons case,
the waiver of his right to appeal will be reviewed by the high court.
   The execution was scheduled after Simmons was convicted of
capital murder in February for the slaying of 14 relatives whose
bodies were found in and around Simmons' property near Dover at
Christmastime in 1987.
   Last May, Simmons was convicted of capital murder for killing two
people during a 40-minute shooting rampage in Russellville on Dec.
28, 1987. He told the court at that time that he wanted to die and
did not want any appeals.
   Testifying Wednesday, Simmons said he knew about his rights and
wanted the execution to proceed without delay.
   Circuit Court Judge John Patterson granted his waiver request.
</TEXT>
