<FIRST>r a AM-People-Reagan     03-01 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Reagan,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maureen Reagan Publishes Memoirs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maureen Reagan provides some insights into her
father, the former president, and unleashes a number of gossipy
barbs in her new book, ``First Father, First Daughter.''
   She writes that former deputy chief of staff Michael Deaver
``came to my father's administration not because he believed in
Ronald Reagan's conservative movement ... but because Reagan was a
politcal train that happened to be leaving the station, and Mike
Deaver wanted to be on board,'' USA Today reported Wednesday.
   Her opinion of former White House chief of staff Donald Regan is
no higher: ``He seemed to suffer from that rare snobbery of the
greedy rich.''
   She said Regan had his office remodeled to include an outdoor
patio like the president's, and kept referring to him as ``cousin''
until Reagan joked he would be accused of nepotism if Regan didn't
knock it off.
   The official publication date of ``First Father, First Daughter''
is April 3 but copies of the book will be in some stores near the
end of next week, Jennifer Kittredge, a spokeswoman for the
publisher, said Wednesday.
   Ms. Reagan says her father was afraid to fly but overcame his
fear during his first bid for governor of California. She also said
the president joked that would-be assassin John Hinckley ruined a
good suit.
   In her book, Ms. Reagan paints a picture of life in the White
House as a fairy tale come true.
   But writing about her own life, Ms. Reagan says that in her first
marriage, at age 20, she was an abused wife who ``just sat there
receiving his blows, not wanting to believe I'd let myself get into
a situation like this.''
   She said she never told her parents about the beatings.
</TEXT>
