<FIRST>r a AM-TransplantFuror     03-01 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplant Furor,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Relieved That State Will Pay For Son's Bone Marrow Transplant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose 6-year-old son needs a bone
marrow transplant said Wednesday she is glad the state will pay for
the operation but bitter about how the state handled the case.
   ``It's a big relief. I'm just sorry my family had to go through
this. No family should have to go through that,'' Vargas said in an
interview in her apartment as her son, Derek Annese, fidgeted on the
couch beside her.
   After the Boston Sunday Globe quoted New Hampshire officials as
saying the state would not cover most costs associated with the
operation, Derek's plight became the subject of radio talk shows and
led to a public campaign to raise money for the operation, expected
to cost about $150,000.
   On Tuesday, Gov. Judd Gregg held a news conference to assure that
Medicaid would cover most of the cost.
   Derek, who lives with his mother and two brothers on about $800 a
month in public assistance, needs the transplant to give him a
chance to beat a precursor of leukemia. A bone-marrow donor has been
located and doctors at the University of Wisconsin are scheduling
the transplant, Vargas said.
   The boy's mother said Wednesday she has not heard from state
officials, learning the news from a radio newscast when she and
Derek returned to New Hampshire on Tuesday from a trip to Disney
World. The trip was courtesy of the Make-A-Wish program for gravely
ill children.
   Gregg said at the news conference that the newspaper account was
incorrect, resulting from a ``communications breakdown,'' and that
the state's decision to pay for the transplant ``is not a new
policy.''
   However, Globe reporter Bob Hohler stood by his story and was
supported by Derek's lawyer and doctors.
   ``I don't see how it could be a misunderstanding,'' Vargas said.
``They (state officials) told Wisconsin no, they told my
pediatrician no and they told my doctor in Boston (at the
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute) no.''
   ``They weren't going to pay for anything to do with the
transplant,'' she said.
   Derek made it clear he was tired of answering reporters'
questions but said he felt ``great.''
   Vargas said Derek was excited that a path was now clear for the
operation. But she said he may only now be learning of the gravity
of his illness.
   After Derek left the room, Vargas said it was only Tuesday night,
as the family watched news programs that had been videotaped for
them during their absence, that the boy heard one of his doctors say
he would die without the operation.
   ``And me and my sister both just looked right at him at the same
time, because it was the first time that it was loud and clear, and
we just didn't know what he was going to do,'' she said.
   ``But he just sat in the chair quietly and watched the rest of
the (newscast), and he asked me if all those people were helping
him. And I said yes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
