<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-01 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GORMAN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If a guy changing a tire can so fascinate
motorists that freeway traffic is backed up for miles, imagine what
rubberneckers would make of 1,700 giant yellow roadside umbrellas
planted by the artist Christo.
   If all goes as planned, that's just what drivers traveling the
steep, winding section of Interstate 5 known as the Grapevine will
see: miles of octagonal umbrellas, each 28 feet in diameter.
   Christo plans the display as part of a two-nation spectacle for
three weeks in October 1991. He wants to set up 1,300 blue umbrellas
in rural Japan and says he will pay the project's $10 million to $12
million cost.
   ``The umbrella is something extremely familiar to everyone around
the world,'' the Bulgarian artist said. ``It's so enchanting, so
uplifting. It has a fabulous connotation. The umbrella is very much
linked to the greatness of kings.''
   The California Highway Patrol is diplomatically embracing the
project even while worrying about the effect on California's major
north-south highway a little more than an hour's drive north of
downtown Los Angeles.
   ``It will be a traffic nightmare,'' said Capt. Patrick
Harrington, ``but it will be a thing of absolute beauty. ... We're
really excited about it.''
   Christo previously gift-wrapped the Florida islands dotting
Biscayne Bay in hot pink woven polypropylene, drew a giant curtain
across a Colorado valley, and shrouded Paris' oldest bridge in
champagne-colored fabric.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Nebraska celebrated its 122nd birthday
Wednesday, the history-minded recalled an incident that could be
called the Great Seal Steal.
   Before Nebraska became a state on March 1, 1867, Omaha was the
territorial capital, and a lot of people there opposed the decision
to make Lincoln the state capital. So they kept secreted away the
60-pound state seal.
   When the new Capitol was ready for occupancy on Dec. 1, 1868,
according to previously published reports, then-Secretary of State
Tom Kennard declared: ``We'll have to steal the seal! There is no
other way.''
   Kennard hitched up his horses and set out for Omaha on a Sunday.
He entered the territorial Capitol, wrapped up the seal and stashed
it under the seat of his buggy.
   He whipped his horses into action and by nightfall had crossed
the Platte River, the line of demarcation between forces pushing
Omaha or Lincoln as the state capital.
   Early the next morning, he appeared on the steps of the new
Capitol. There, on Dec. 3, 1868, he put the impression of the
insignia from the state seal to a proclamation declaring the capital
of Nebraska as Lincoln, County of Lancaster, Nebraska, and that it
was ``open for business.''
   For 121 years, that same seal has been used almost daily for
hundreds of official governmental transactions. The seal depicts a
steamboat ascending the Missouri river, a smith with hammer and
anvil, a settler's cabin, sheaves of wheat and stalks of growing
corn, and the Rocky Mountains in the background.
</TEXT>
