<FIRST>r a AM-Shoreham     03-01 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Republican In Albany Likes Cuomo's Shoreham Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate majority leader said
Wednesday he supports Gov. Mario Cuomo's plan to buy the Shoreham
nuclear power plant for $1 and dismantle it.
   Republican Ralph Marino, who could kill the Democratic governor's
plan, endorsed it at a Capitol news conference, saying, ``I think we
should get the issue behind us, at least have some kind of
direction, and this gives us stability.''
   Under the agreement announced Tuesday by Cuomo and the Long
Island Lighting Co., the state would buy the $5.4 billion nuclear
plant for $1 and have the state Power Authority dismantle it. The
never-used Long Island plant has waged licensing battles since its
completion in 1985 and nearly bankrupted the utility with cost
overruns and delays.
   As part of the Cuomo-Lilco agreement, approval is needed from the
Power Authority's board of directors. At the moment, Cuomo doesn't
have the three votes he needs from the five-member panel. Marino
could give Cuomo the votes.
   One of the slots on the panel is vacant and a second will be soon
because the current member's term is expiring. Of the remaining
three members, one supports Cuomo's plan, one opposes it and one has
taken no position.
   For months, Cuomo has had two nominees for the board pending
before the state Senate for confirmation. Last year, under the
leadership of then-Senate Majority Leader Warren Anderson, the
nominations stalled as Cuomo and the state Legislature battled over
the Shoreham issue.
   Anderson has since retired and been replaced by Marino. Marino
could free up the nominations, and both votes are expected to be
votes in favor of Cuomo's deal.
</TEXT>
