<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurity     03-01 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commissioner Says Don't Make Social Security Separate Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy
urged a House panel Wednesday to reject legislation that would make
the Social Security Administration a separate agency rather than a
part of the Department of Health and Human Services.
   ``I firmly believe that making SSA an independent agency would
hinder our efforts to continue and improve our record of
high-quality service to the public,'' Ms. Hardy testified.
   ``What independent agency status would do is invite, and expose
SSA to, direct pressure from interest groups, states, and members of
Congress,'' she said.
   If such a measure were to win eventual congressional approval,
she argued, it at least should be changed to provide that the agency
be run by a single administrator rather than a three-member board as
spelled out in the bill under consideration.
   Although not taking a position at the hearing for or against the
basic concept of making Social Security a separate agency, the
General Accounting Office backed Hardy's call for avoiding a system
that could result in management by committee.
   ``As we have testified in the past, we believe a more effective
form of leadership would be a single administrator,'' said Joseph F.
Delfico, director of income security issues in GAO's human resources
division.
   The General Accounting Office is Congress' own watchdog agency,
and Delfico was careful not to offend Rep. Andy Jacobs, D-Ind.,
chairman of the Ways and Means subcommittee on Social Security and
lead author of the legislation.
   Delfico's reference to past testimony illustrated that attempts
to make the Social Security Administration a separate agency are not
new.
   The idea enjoys considerable popularity, particularly among House
members, because of what they say is a widely held public perception
that making the Social Security Administration an independent agency
would separate it from politics.
   Noting that he had been supporting such proposals for years, Rep.
J.J. Pickle, D-Texas, told the panel:
   ``Despite the steady increase in the financial strength of the
system ... too many people still doubt that the system will provide
them with meaningful benefits when it is their time to retire. This
is because, deep down, they do not believe that the `politicans and
bureaucrats' have the will to leave the program alone.''
   Making the Social Security Administration a separate agency would
not exempt it from following the policies laid down by Congress,
which sets both benefit levels and the withholding taxes to pay for
them.
   Pickle introduced a measure to separate the agency in the 98th
Congress and similar bills have been introduced in each Congress
since, including the current 101st. A bill passed the House 401-0 in
1986, but was not taken up in the Senate.
   Pickle noted that the measure has little overt opposition in
Congress but ``for some reason or another it always gets bottled up
before we get it out.''
</TEXT>
