<FIRST>r a AM-Hepatitis-Sewage     03-01 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hepatitis-Sewage,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abandoned Plant May be Source of Disease at Trailer Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCOEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials are offering free
inoculations to try to curb an outbreak of hepatitis believed caused
by sewage flowing into a trailer park from an abandoned plant.
   Fifteen people, mostly children, have gotten the disease at the
Palms Mobile Home Park in this Orlando suburb since November.
   Orange County health officials say the wastewater discharging
from the abandoned plant that once served the park is virtually
untreated and could contain the infectious hepatitis virus.
   Rain causes water to back up from the plant into yards and
streets, where children play in it, said Teresa Madden, whose
6-year-old daughter recently had hepatitis.
   Bob and Gina Segebart said Tuesday that sewage from the plant has
been a problem since they moved into the park of about 125 mobile
homes three years ago.
   ``It makes me mad, really mad,'' said Gina Segebart. ``I think
the entire neighborhood is upset.''
   Bill Toth, health department spokesman, said the shots of gamma
globulin will give residents temporary immunity and lessen symptoms,
which include fever, jaundice, an enlarged liver and intestinal
problems.
   ``Our prime concern right now is there is a very real risk of
transmission through raw sewage,'' Toth said. ``If we can break the
chain of infection anywhere along the way, we can stop this thing in
its tracks.''
   Joe Passiatore, an assistant county attorney, said a loophole in
state law allows a private utility owner to walk away from a
malfunctioning plant. The owner, Brevard County businessman Mike
Minton, said he abandoned the plant early in February after trying
to sell it to Ocoee and to a private utility company.
   He said he tried to buy more land to expand, but the owners would
not sell, and so he gave the county, city and regulatory agencies 90
days notice that he would abandon the utility. Under state law, the
county became responsible for having someone take over its operation.
   County commissioners Monday authorized repairs until a judge can
appoint someone to run the plant. A cleanup began on Tuesday.
   Something would have been done months ago if the mobile home park
was not in a poor section, said resident Doug Walker.
   ``It is like we are not here,'' Walker said.
</TEXT>
