<DOCNO> AP890301-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CellularEavesdropping     03-01 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cellular Eavesdropping,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Legislators Mull Law Banning Cellular Phone Eavesdropping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As you cruise down the freeway and chat on
your cellular telephone with your sweetheart, lawyer, bookie or
broker, bear in mind that somebody _ anybody _ could be listening.
   The fact that conversations on cellular telephones can be easily
pulled from the airwaves with inexpensive radio scanners upsets a
lot of people, including a few state legislators who have proposed a
measure to make eavesdropping illegal. Action on the bill has been
put off for a year while a legislative committee studies it.
   At a hearing Tuesday for the Committee on Energy and Utilities,
one cellular phone user urged action.
   ``If there's no prohibition against listening in, why not just go
to a CB?'' asked lobbyist Steve Duncan. ``The point for me is that
my phone is not like a CB radio. I'm paying more to the phone
company to use my car phone than to use a phone at my home.''
   Duncan is one of scores of Washington residents who use a
cellular phone, for which he pays $150 a month in subscriber charges.
   Attorney Deborah Senn, a legislative researcher, said either
technology must solve the problem or lawmakers must address it. She
said the problem will only grow along with the popularity of
cellular car phones, which now are estimated to number 1 million in
the United States.
   Senn said legislators have heard from lawyers and physicians who
are especially concerned at eavesdropping because some of their
conversations are with clients and considered privileged.
   ``We're talking about a lot of sensitive phone conversations
where people might not even be aware that somebody could be
listening in,'' she said.
   Duncan acknowledged that a state law might not stop
eavesdroppers, especially since a 1986 federal law, which carries a
$500 fine for eavesdropping, seems to have had little effect.
   But he said at least ``bragging rights would stop'' among
eavesdroppers who have been known to tape conversations and play
them on commercial radio stations for entertainment. He said he
heard just such a program recently on a Seattle station.
   Tom McBride, another researcher for the legislative committee,
said radio scanners with a megahertz band of 800 to 900 are capable
of picking up cellular telephone conversations. He said the cellular
phone industry is working on ways to scramble conversations with
relatively affordable technology.
   European systems already are secure against eavesdroppers,
McBride said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
