<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     03-01 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobs, Police Clash in India Over `Satanic Verses'; 35 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grafs 5-8, ``In London ...'' embargoed for release 4 p.m. EST,
time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired shots in the air and lobbed
tear-gas Wednesday at a rampaging mob protesting Salman Rushdie's
novel ``The Satanic Verses'' in the northern city of Srinagar, news
reports said.
   At least 35 people, including 15 policemen, were injured in the
clashes, United News of India said.
   Also on Wednesday, a Swiss newspaper quoted the son of the former
Iranian shah as saying that any harm to Islam from the book is small
compared to that caused by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's death
sentence on Rushdie.
   Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark met with 25 ambassadors from
Islamic countries Wednesday in Ottawa in efforts to help end the
death threat. The ambassadors responded by calling on Canada to ban
the sale of Rushdie's book. No progress was reported.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BEGIN MATERIAL EMBARGOED FOR 4 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In London, about 1,000 of the world's leading writers challenged
Khomeini's death sentence on Rushdie by declaring themselves
involved in the publication of his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``We, the undersigned, insofar as we defend the right to freedom
of opinion and expression as embodied in the Universal Declaration
of Human Rights, declare that we are also involved in the
publication,'' said the statement.
   ``We are involved whether we approve of the contents of the book
or not,'' added the statement, whose signers included America's Saul
Bellow and Arthur Miller, Mexico's Carlos Fuentes, Soviet writer
Anatoly Rybakov, and Nadine Gordimer and Andre Brink of South Africa.
   The statement appeared to be the most high-powered pledge of
solidarity yet by writers with Rushdie and his publishers, and was a
response to Khomeini's Feb. 14 call.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END EMBARGOED MATERIAL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Indian-born Rushdie, a British citizen, has been in hiding for
two weeks since the Iranian spiritual leader sparked an
international furor by ordering him killed.
   On Feb. 12, police in Pakistan killed six anti-Rushdie
demonstrators. A day later, a man in northern India was killed in a
demonstration. The most violent protests took place in the western
Indian city of Bombay Feb. 24, when at least 10 people were killed
in clashes with police.
   In Srinagar on Wednesday, an organization of Moslem youths
demanded that shops and businesses close in Srinagar in protest of
the novel, news agencies said. Most shops, offices and businesses
stayed open, the UNI news agency said.
   Police opened fire after protesters began throwing stones, UNI
said. At least six of the 20 injured demonstrators were
hospitalized, UNI said. Authorities said 15 policemen also were
injured when they were pelted by stone-throwing protesters, UNI said.
   Srinigar is 400 miles north of New Delhi. India, Pakistan, Egypt
and South Africa are among countries that have banned the book.
   In Switzerland, the weekly newspaper Weltwoche quoted Reza
Pahlavi as saying the campaign against Rushdie was a calculated
effort by radical factions in Iran to keep the current leadership in
power and sabotage overtures to the West after the end of the
draining Iran-Iraq war.
   ``As big as the damage to Islam by Rushdie may be, it is small
compared to the damage Khomeini is causing,'' said Pahlevi, 28, who
lives in the Washington area with his wife. He is the son of the
Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who left power for an interim government
that was toppled in the 1979 Iranian revolution.
   In related developments:
   _ French singer Veronique Sanson has withdrawn a pop song titled
``Allah'' from her repertoire following bomb threats to Paris
concert hall where she is performing. Ms. Sanson said her life and
those of her musicians was threatened by callers to the Olympia
music hall after her opening performance Tuesday.
   _ About 200 university students in the Malaysian capital of Kuala
Lumpur rallied Wednesday against the book, carrying banners with the
message ``Kill Salman Rushdie.'' The one-hour demonstration was
peaceful.
   _ The Swedish publisher Bonnier plan to advance the
Swedish-language release date of ``The Satanic Verses'' from autumn
to summer, the national news agency TT reported Wednesday.
</TEXT>
