<FIRST>r w AM-TaxReturns     03-01 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Returns,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Americans Filing Simpler Tax Forms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A growing number of Americans are filing
simpler tax forms, apparently because the new tax law reduced or
eliminated several beneficial deductions.
   The number filing the long Form 1040 is down 4.2 percent this
year, the Internal Revenue Service said Wednesday. The number filing
the ``short'' Form 1040A is up 7.5 percent; 6.8 percent more
taxpayers are filing the simplest form, 1040EZ, than at this time
last year.
   ``These figures suggest that many taxpayers who filed Form 1040
in the past may be switching to the simpler, shorter forms,'' the
IRS said.
   The 1986 tax overhaul eliminated deductions for state and local
sales taxes and two-earner couples, and began phasing out the
deduction for consumer interest. It also reduced writeoffs for
medical expenses, and for millions of workers it cut or eliminated
deductions for Individual Retirement Accounts.
   Through Feb. 24, halfway through the filing season, the IRS had
received 30.8 million returns _ only about 28 percent of the 109
million expected to file this year. That is up 2 percent from the
30.2 million at this time last year. This year's receipts included
13.1 million Forms 1040, 8.5 million 1040A and 9.1 million 1040EZ.
   The IRS had processed almost half the returns and had approved
refund checks for almost 8.3 million taxpayers, up 9in the Black
Hills of South Dakota.
   Partly cloudy skies and mild temperatures prevailed in the
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 11 below
zero at Warroad, Minn., to 85 degrees at Avon Park, Fla. The morning
low for the nation was minus 33 at Warroad.
   Thursday's forecast called for widespread rain from Oklahoma and
southeast Kansas across the lower half of the Mississippi, Ohio and
Tennessee valleys to the South Atlantic Coast states, with
thunderstorms heaviest over Georgia and Florida. Rain also was
expected from western Oregon across much of California and Nevada,
with snow from Washington and eastern Oregon across the northern
Rockies, parts of the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi
Valley, the Great Lakes and Pennsylvania, New York and Vermont.
   Highs should be in the single digits and teens from Montana
across the northern Plains to northern Michigan, with temperatures
in the 20s and 30s across Wyoming, Nebraska, Iowa, much of the Great
Lakes and Pennsylvania to New England. Highs should be in the 60s
and 70s over much of California, Arizona, New Mexico, Texas, the
central Gulf Coast states and northern Florida, warming into the 80s
over southern Florida. Elsewhere, highs in the 50s and 60s should be
the rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
