<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Iberia     03-01 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Iberia,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iberia Puts Losses Due to Mechanics Strike at $50 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iberia Airlines has lost $50 million in
business since Jan. 1 due to a three-month strike by jet mechanics
over training, pay and work benefits, the airline's president said
Wednesday.
   Iberia President Narcis Andreu also told Parliament's industry
committee the recent discovery of nine cases of sabotage of jets had
forced extra inspections and the cancellation of at least 10
transoceanic flights, costing $4.3 million.
   Andreu took pains, however, to avoid blaming the sabotage on the
1,600 members of the the Spanish Association of Aircraft Maintenance
Technicians who have carried out many one-day strikes since Dec. 23.
   Andreu also said it had 7.3 percent fewer passengers between Jan.
1 and Feb. 27, compared with the same period last year. He
attributed the drop to the 25 percent reduction in its 350 to 450
daily flights since January caused by the mechanics' strike.
   The union has pressured Iberia for a separate agreement to
guarantee training to meet international specifications out of fear
its members could lose their jobs in 1993 when the European Economic
Community creates a unified labor pool and establishes common labor
standards.
   The jet mechanics form part of a contract that includes the
company's 21,000 ground employees.
   Andreu said he would not agree to the mechanics' union demands
for a separate agreement because it would lead to calls by other
groups within the ground employees for separate agreements,
``increasing conflicts in negotiations and eventually reducing the
company's competitivity.''
   He said 100 of the unions' mechanics had been fired for failing
to meet minimum services decreed by the Transport Ministry on strike
days. Another 353 mechanics had been sanctioned for disciplinary
reasons, he said.
</TEXT>
