<DOCNO> AP890301-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Food     03-01 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Food,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Criticized for Food-Poisoning Scare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parliamentary committee criticized the government
Wednesday for its handling of a salmonella-in-eggs crisis triggered
by a junior minister's remark that most British egg production was
infected.
   The Agriculture Select Committee said ``the likelihood of an egg
being infected with salmonella is very small'' but cautioned that a
sharp rise in salmonella poisoning cases from 10,000 in 1981 to
23,000 in the first 10 months of 1988 was ``cause for concern.''
   Egg sales fell 60 percent after the junior health minister,
Edwina Currie, said Dec. 3 that most egg production was infected
with salmonella. Confronted by lawsuits from farmers, Mrs. Currie
resigned, but the affair prompted a major public debate about food
hygiene.
   The committee said the government, and not just Mrs. Currie, was
to blame from failing to correct her ``wrong'' remark.
   Critics have accused the government of siding with food
producers, neglecting the interests of consumers and issuing
conflicting statements that confused the public.
   Last month, the government ordered an inquiry into food safety
after warning pregnant women against eating soft cheeses and
ordering farmers to slaughter salmonella-infected chickens.
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke said Wednesday the government had
issued health warnings ``that were very clear.''
   ``I accept that we have got to do more to tell people about the
safe handling of food,'' he told the BBC.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher ``shares the concern of the rest
of the government that the health of the public is properly
protected and British farming produces high quality food and also
that ... we keep things in proportion,'' Clarke said.
   The committee said ``more should have been done sooner'' by the
government to prevent eggs entering the food chain from farms
responsible for poisoning outbreaks.
   It urged the government to spend more on research to counter food
poisoning, bring in better procedures for tracing outbreaks to their
source and reduce contamination in animal foodstuffs.
   The government's chief medical officer, Sir Donald Acheson, said
in January that salmonella in eggs is a serious health problem but
``only a very few eggs are infected.''
</TEXT>
