<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Heroes     03-01 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heroes,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carnegie Hero Medals Awarded To 19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Sullivan and two buddies in a fishing
boat outraced thundering, 15-foot Pacific Ocean breakers to rescue
two people clinging to the hull of a capsized skiff.
   ``None of us was scared until we got back to the dock, and then
we just started shaking all over,'' the retired welder said
Wednesday after he and 18 others from 11 states and two Canadian
provinces were recognized as heroes by the Carnegie Hero Fund
Commission.
   Sullivan, 60, of Rockaway Beach, Ore., said the incident on
Nehalem Bay on Aug. 8, 1987, was the most dramatic of several
rescues he has performed in his life.
   ``We don't have to do it. It's just one of those things. You take
a chance,'' he said in a telephone interview from a dockside bait
shop. ``I don't know what it is. When you hear about someone
floating around and you have a chance to get them, you do it. To
save someone's life makes you feel good.''
   Sullivan, David Morrow, 41, and Lloyd Komlofske, Sr., 38, both of
Clackamas, Ore., were crabbing from their 21-foot boat when a
distress call came over their CB radio.
   ``We just dropped everything and said, `Let's go!' '' Sullivan
said.
   The skiff with five people aboard overturned in 15- to 20-foot
breakers two miles from shore. The rescuers, struggling to hold
their craft and maneuver in the breakers, managed to pull aboard
Stephanie Dennis, 43, and John Gochenour, 29, both of Portland.
   ``We went through a breaker about that time,'' said Morrow, the
skipper. ``It went right over top of us, and then I couldn't find
the people anymore. I was scared I was going to run over the people
who were still out in the water.''
   Morrow piloted the boat beyond the breakers, turned around and
was attempting a second pass at the skiff when a Coast Guard cutter
arrived for the other survivors. Morrow headed for shore.
   ``We had a big breaker coming up behind us, and you have to stay
ahead of them,'' Sullivan said. ``We had to outrun the last one.''
   The Coast Guard saved two people. The fifth drowned.
   The awards Wednesday bring to 7,313 the number of people honored
since industrialist Andrew Carnegie established the fund 85 years
ago. The latest recipients or their survivors shared grants totaling
$47,500.
   They are:
   _Francis Theodore Waldo, 45, of Jamestown, Pa., who died trying
to save his teen-age daughter and a 16-year-old boy from drowning in
Pymatuning Reservoir on June 19, 1988. Only the girl lived.
   _James Edward Fell, 34, of Los Angeles, who saved a 29-year-old
man from a knife attack in Los Angeles on Dec. 15, 1986.
   _Giancarlo Mangialaio, 39, of Trail, British Columbia, who saved
a man and a woman from a burning car on Oct. 16, 1987.
   _Daniel G. Shannon, 37, of Madeira Beach, Fla., who helped to
save two young girls from drowning in the Gulf of Mexico on Aug. 7,
1988.
   _Randolph W. Macyauski, 30, of Greensburg, Ind., who saved a
6-year-old girl from drowning when her car was swept from a bridge
and carried downstream in Salt Creek in Oldenburg, Ind., on Aug. 19,
1988.
   _Robert John Jameson, 35, of Roebling, N.J., who rescued a
31-year-old woman from a knife assault aboard a bus in Bordentown,
N.J., on April 15, 1988.
   _Brian Michael Rebus, 32, of Drumheller, Alberta, who helped save
a 27-year-old man who was overcome by carbon monoxide in a sewer and
collapsed face down in the water in East Coulee, Alberta, on June
25, 1987.
   _Kemrey Magnant, 27, of Shelburne, Vt., who saved a 20-year-old
woman from a burning car in Williston, Vt., on July 16, 1988.
   _Rodney Jay Myers, 36, and Dennis Hall, 40, both of Hyattsville,
Md., who helped save an 11-year-old boy from burning in his home in
Hyattsville on April 26, 1988.
   _Robert Ladau, 48, of Patterson, N.Y., and Joseph Vandenhouten,
45, of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., who saved a 20-year-old man caught in
a rip current in the Atlantic Ocean off Fort Lauderdale on March 24,
1988.
   _Michael Clay Mitchell, 34, of Chicago, who saved a 2-year-old
boy and 4-month-old infant from a fire in their Chicago home April
19, 1988. In the same incident, Keith Benson, 21, of Lincoln, Ill.,
rescued a 15-month-old boy.
   _Karl Schreinber, 75, of Indianapolis, who rescued a 6-year-old
boy from an attack by two pit bull terriers in Indianapolis on Oct.
3, 1988.
   _Jackie Mason, 46, of Irving, Texas, who helped saved a
73-year-old woman from drowning after her car was swept into an
8-foot-deep irrigation canal in Gila Bend, Ariz., on March 19, 1988.
</TEXT>
