<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0686 03-01 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Looking for `Concrete Steps' from PLO; Shamir Critical</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with official saying PLO supplied counterterrorism information,
inserting new grafs 7-9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday it would
keep talking to the Palestine Liberation Organization and look for
``concrete steps'' toward peace in the Middle East.
   The five U.S.-PLO meetings since December have been described by
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir as useless. And in an
interview with The Washington Times, he said Chairman Yasser Arafat
and Adolf Hitler ``belong to the same family of demagogues and
totalitarians.''
   The State Department spokesman, Charles E. Redman, declined to
respond directly to Shamir's statement about the U.S. dialogue with
the PLO. However, Redman said it was the ``basic approach and
objective (to) hopefully produce concrete steps that contribute to
peace in the Middle East.''
   At the last session, on Tuesday in Tunisia, U.S. Ambassador
Robert Pelletreau criticized a raid by three PLO guerrillas in
southern Lebanon, about a mile from Israel's border.
   However, Redman made it clear that the talks would be continued.
   ``This dialogue is not an end in itself,'' he said. And when
asked to assess the results so far, Redman said, ``This is still
early going in the process.''
   Meanwhile, Edward S. Walker, a deputy assistant secretary of
state, indicated to a House subcommittee Wednesday that the PLO had
provided useful information regarding counterterrorism.
   Asked by Rep. Larry Smith, D-Fla., about a statement two weeks
ago by the State Department's top counterterrorism official that the
PLO had not furnished information on the Pan American jetliner that
crashed after exploding over Scotland in December, Walker replied:
``I couldn't make that same statement today.''
   However, other U.S. officials, speaking on condition they not be
named, said the PLO had not provided information on that flight. One
said Walker did not mean to indicate the information concerned the
PLO flight.
   Shamir said in The Times interview published Wednesday that if
Arafat flew to Israel as the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat did
on a 1977 peace mission, ``we'd put him in prison.''
   Interviewed in Jerusalem by Arnaud de Borchgrave, the newspaper's
editor-in-chief, the Israeli leader called King Hussein of Jordan,
with whom he has offered to negotiate terms for an Arab-Israeli
settlement, an ``element of stability'' in the region.
   But, Shamir said, if a Palestinian state is to be established it
should be located on the East Bank of the Jordan River, where
Hussein's kingdom stands.
   ``If the Jordanian population one day decides to have a
Palestinian state there, it's up to them,'' he said.
   Although Jordan does not provide precise population figures it is
believed to be at least 70 percent Palestinian.
   The West Bank, meanwhile, which Jordan ruled from 1947 until the
territory was captured by Israel in the 1967 war, has nearly 1
million Palestinians and about 60,000 Jews.
   Shamir took a tough stand on these issues as the Bush
administration pondered its policy toward the Middle East. Israeli
Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, who is also a hard-liner, is due here
for talks in two weeks with Secretary of State James A. Baker III
and Vice President Dan Quayle.
   Arens also may see President Bush.
   Ending a 13-year ban, the United States opened a dialogue with
the PLO last December, over Israel's objections. There have been
five meetings so far in Tunisia, where the PLO maintains its
headquarters.
   Asked if the dialogue is a bad idea, Shamir said: ``I think it's
useless. Not healthy because it gives the PLO more prestige and
importance, and in such a way that it discourages moderate elements
who would like to find a path to real peace with Israel.''
   Shamir said there were many moderate elements among the
Palestinians. ``But when they see the Americans talking to the PLO,
they cannot muster the courage to do anything else,'' he said.
   The U.S. talks with the PLO were based on a judgment by the
Reagan administration that Arafat had renounced terrorism, accepted
Israel's right to exist and subscribed to U.N. Security Council
resolutions upholding the right of all states in the area to live
within secure borders.
   But Shamir did not detect any change in Arafat's attitude.
   ``History is replete with such phenomena who, after a while,
disappear when they have outlived their usefulness,'' he said.
``Take Hitler. There was a time in the 1930s when Hitler was
celebrated the world over as some kind of savior. The end we know.
But the price was a very heavy one.''
   Asked if he were drawing a parallel between Hitler and Arafat,
the Israeli leader replied: ``They belong to the same family of
demagogues and totalitarians, enemies of the Jewish people, men who
think nothing of killing millions to achieve their objectives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
