<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Brazil-Crime     03-01 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Brazil-Crime,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted in Burning of Girlfriend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who set his girlfriend on
fire when she told him their relationship was over was convicted of
attempted murder and sentenced to 13 years and 10 months in prison,
lawyers said Wednesday.
   Uilson Miyashiro was convicted Tuesday of attempted murder for
dousing Cristina Lopes Afonso with alcohol and setting a match to
her, defense lawyer Fabiana Jacobs said by telephone from Curitiba,
520 miles southwest of Rio.
   Miss Afonso, 24, who suffered burns over two-thirds of her body
and has extensive scars on her face and arms, testified that
Miyashiro, a 42-year-old opthamologist, went berserk when she told
him in 1986 their relationship was over, Jacobs said.
   Miyashiro broke furnishings in their apartment and poured alcohol
over Miss Afonso and asked her to reconsider, the lawyer said. When
she refused, he struck a match and set her afire.
   Miss Afonso spent four months in the hospital. She has had 24
plastic surgery operations and is still in physical therapy.
   Cheers broke out in court when the sentence was announced. Miss
Afonso's supporters had been worried that Miyashiro would receive a
light sentence.
</TEXT>
