<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Tobacco-SKorea     03-01 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tobacco-SKorea,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tobacco Exports, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Good News for U.S. Makers in Korean Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year's settlement of a trade dispute with
South Korea cleared the way for rapid growth in U.S. sales of
cigarettes and leaf tobacco to that thriving Asian market, according
to an Agriculture Department report.
   ``Cigarette manufacturers have clearly won by gaining access to
this market, which earned them $56.4 million in 1988 and holds
promise for even greater annual earnings in the future,'' the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service said.
   Shipments of ``unmanufactured'' leaf tobacco to South Korea last
year were valued at less than $10 million, but that was the most
since U.S. leaf exports were about $40 million in 1981. The $56.4
million in cigarette shipments was the most ever.
   ``U.S. cigarettes have historically faced stringent trade
restrictions in this market,'' the report said. ``Prior to 1986, it
was illegal for Korean citizens even to possess foreign cigarettes.
This prohibition was lifted in 1986, but U.S. cigarettes continued
to face tought trade restrictions.''
   The restrictions led the U.S. Cigarette Export Association to
file a complaint with the U.S. trade representative on Jan. 1, 1988,
charging that South Korea had violated the U.S. Trade Act.
   Under the 1974 law, the president can take action, including
retaliation, to obtain the removal of any foreign barrier found to
be in violation of international agreement or discriminatory.
   Negotiations produced a ``record of understanding'' signed with
South Korea on May 27, 1988, which eased restrictions on U.S.
cigarettes carried out by the Korean Monopoly Corp., or KOMOCO.
   ``Now, U.S. cigarettes are not subject to an import quota,'' the
report said. ``Import and domestic taxes have been reduced further;
restrictions on advertising and promotion have been reduced; price
restrictions have been removed; and cigarettes can be distributed
independent of KOMOCO.''
   The report added, ``Soon after the agreement was signed, U.S.
manufacturers began to sign sales agreements with Korean firms, and
U.S. cigarette exports began to explode.''
   In June 1988, U.S. cigarette shipments to South Korea increased
30-fold from May. For the entire year, sales totaled 2.4 billion
cigarettes, or ``pieces,'' a 670 percent increase from 312 million
pieces in 1987.
   ``In recent years, (South Korean) cigarette consumption has
increased an average of 5 percent annually,'' the report said.
``Increased consumption is attributable to the tremendous growth in
personal income and increased consumption by women and students.''
   The report also credits KOMOCO with ``an aggressive promotion
campaign'' to help boost sales of domestic brands, many of which are
using greater amounts of U.S. tobacco leaf.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
