<SECOND>AM-Rapist-Release,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Calls Releasing Rapist `Bad Decision'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the state's parole program
conceded that it was a mistake to release a twice-convicted child
molester who was arrested again this week on charges of abducting
and raping a young girl.
   ``We made a bad decision on this case, no question about it,''
Guy Revell, chairman of the Florida Parole and Probation Commission,
said Tuesday.
   Frank Potter, 43, was paroled by officials both in Florida and
New Jersey in 1987. He was arrested in Tampa on Monday and charged
with abducting and sexually assaulting a 7-year-old girl as she was
on her way to school three weeks earlier.
   Twice before, Potter was paroled after serving time for sexual
assaults on children in Palmetto, Fla., in 1968, and in Lakewood,
N.J., in 1976.
   In all, Potter had been sentenced to 55 years in prison in both
states and served fewer than 20 years.
   Revell said a probation officer recommended in a memo in July
that ``Potter needs to be in a more structured situation than
regular parole,'' and recommended community control with an
electronic monitoring device.
   Revell said it was only a matter of time before Potter's sentence
was to end. So the commission gave him parole on condition he attend
a treatment program.
   ``And it didn't work out,'' Revell said. ``We tried and the man
violated. We tried to protect the community as best we could through
some sort of formal treatment program.''
