<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaker Says Report of Threats `Preposterous'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright condemned Wednesday as
``preposterous'' a published report that he had threatened to blow
the whistle on a Texas federal savings and loan regulator said to be
homosexual.
   The report in Wednesday's Washington Times said that Wright,
D-Texas, made the threat in an effort to get better treatment for
Texas savings and loan institutions whose officials had complained
to him, and that the issue had figured in the report of a special
outside counsel investigating charges against Wright for the House
ethics committee.
   ``The story ... is preposterous,'' Wright said in a statement
read to reporters at his daily news conference. ``This entire report
is antithetical to my personality. I don't threaten people.''
   The allegation that Wright improperly sought to influence S&amp;L
regulators is one of six allegations against the speaker that are
the subjects of a nine-month ethics probe. The ethics panel is
expected to announce some action in the case the week of March 13.
   Wright acknowledged expressing concerns in 1986 and 1987 about
regulatory conduct in Texas to Edwin Gray, then chairman of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which oversees savings and loan
institutions. But he said the exchange was ``consistent with the
work done by members of Congress all the time.''
   Wright said he had submitted to the ethics committee an affidavit
and a letter from two people present at meetings with Gray and other
S&amp;L regulators in 1986 and 1987 who contend he made no improper
requests of the officials.
   Wright did not respond directly when asked whether he had raised
with Gray the allegations of homosexuality, saying only that he
would not ``indulge in rumors.''
   Published reports and sources close to Wright say the speaker
expressed concerns at the time that a top FHLBB official in Texas
was pressuring state S&amp;L executives to hire the regulator's
homosexual associates as consultants and attorneys.
</TEXT>
