<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     03-01 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Warns Opposition Against Venezuela-Style Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MGA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega on Wednesday
warned critics of his austerity plan not to instigate protests
similiar to the unrest in Venezuela.
   Ortega said the opposition and the ``Yankee empire'' would be the
first victims of such an uprising.
   His speech came the day after the Sandinista government devalued
its currency and raised fuel prices for the sixth time this year. It
also followed days of front-page stories in Nicaraguan newspapers
about violent protests sparked by similar austerity measures.
   ``If a situation develops here like that of Venezuela, if workers
lose their heads and fall into the trap laid by right-wingers, if
they lose faith in the revolution, they will rob and raid the
establishments of right-wing businessmen,'' Ortega said.
   The leftist Sandinistas took power in a 1979 revolution that
ended decades of the pro-U.S. Somoza family dictatorship.
   ``If there is someone trying to sow uncertainty and instability
in this country it is the Yankee empire through its spokesmen,
(political) parties, radio stations, businessmen and newspapers, who
clumsily launch that campaign without realizing they would be the
first victims of the wave they're trying to stimulate,'' Ortega said
in a speech opening the new semester at a local high school.
   The president blamed the United States and other industrialized
nations for the economic crises in Nicaragua and Venezuela.
   He said: ``In Nicaragua, right-wing groups, politicians and radio
stations speak against the economic measures, of the disaster of the
Nicaraguan situation,'' Ortega said.
   He called it the tolling of ``a bell calling the people to
insurrection.''
   ``They fail to understand that with these attitudes they are
playing with fire, which could end up burning them,'' he said.
   The riots in Venezuela came after the month-old government of
Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez announced a sweeping
economic reform package under pressure from internatonal creditors.
   Although Nicaragua does not face the same pressure from
creditors, it is suffering from inflation that hit 20,000 percent
last year and Ortega's harsh austerity program resembles Venezuela's
in many ways.
   The Sandinista program, announced Jan. 30, includes devaluations,
cuts in public spending, higher fuel prices, massive layoffs of
public employees, restricting credit and slashing capital investment.
   ``Our country demands effort, sacrifice and productivity from all
Nicaraguans,'' Ortega said Wednesday.
   He said his economic program is working and that inflation, which
hit 97 percent in January alone was ``only 40 or 41 percent'' in
February.
   ``We were expecting a much higher inflation rate, but our
measures are showing results, thanks to the efforts of the popular
sectors and of responsible businessmen,'' he said.
   Nicaragua's currency, the cordoba, has been devalued six times so
far this year. Each time the cost of food and fuel has risen, in
part because food has to be trucked into the city from the
countryside.
   The latest devaluation was announced Wednesday, with the official
exchange rate now 4,200 cordobas to the U.S. dollar, up from 3,800
cordobas.
   Fuel prices also rose 1,000 cordobas, with a gallon of gasoline
now selling for 8,900 cordobas. Ortega said that fuel prices will
rise in the future but not by as much as over the last two months.
</TEXT>
