<HEAD>Review Ordered of Management Practices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday directed a Pentagon
review of ``management practices throughout the department.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the review would
build on 1986 recommendations of a commission on defense management
appointed by former President Reagan.
   That commission, headed by industrialist David Packard, called
for a major overhaul of the military procurement system, claiming
weapons systems take too long to bring on-line, cost too much and
often do not perform as promised.
   ``The focus now is to identify specific actions to address
problems already clearly identified,'' Fitzwater said in a statement.
   It was not immediately clear from the White House's announcement
what Bush expected from the new review. Last Dec. 13, in a status
report provided to journalists, Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said
34 of the commission's 37 recommendations ``have already been
implemented or are now in the process of being implemented.''
