<FIRST>r w AM-BaseClosings 530   03-01 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings, 530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Members Defend Base Closing Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a presidential panel Wednesday
defended their plan to close U.S. military bases, telling lawmakers
the decisions were based on ``military value.''
   The commission's co-chairs, former Sen. Abraham Ribicoff,
D-Conn., and former Rep. Jack Edwards, R-Ala., also disputed
lawmakers' claims that the decisions were based on faulty data or
conclusions.
   Ribicoff and Edwards, testifying before the House Subcommittee on
Military Installations and Facilities, defended the Dec. 30 report
of the Commission on Base Realignment and Closure.
   ``We did not just pluck these recommendations out of midair,''
Ribicoff said.
   Disputing charges that the commission played politics, Edwards
added, ``Military value is really the touchstone of the process.''
   Ribicoff and Edwards were supported by a top congressional
investigator, who said he has yet to find ``glaring errors'' in the
commission's data.
   Edwards and Ribicoff were on Capitol Hill to fend off criticism
of their report, which was proposed by Congress in an attempt to
solve the politically difficult problem of closing military bases.
   The base-closing panel, planning to close some 86 installations
and partially shut five others, expects its recommendations to save
$5.6 billion over 20 years.
   Congress is scheduled to vote within weeks on the
recommendations, which must be either endorsed in whole or refused
in whole.
   Most criticism has come from lawmakers facing base closings in
their areas. Some lawmakers say the decisions are based on bad
conclusions, and that transfer of some doomed bases' functions will
cost as much or more money than they will save.
   Rep. Larry Hopkins, R-Ky., said he orginally supported the
legislation calling for the commission's report. But Hopkins said he
has been concerned by calculations that show the closures might not
save money.
   ``If we're not, I'm not going to support it,'' he said.
   For example, the commission estimates reductions at Fort Dix,
N.J., will save $84.5 million a year. A report by the Secretary of
Defense's office predicts the change will cost $190 million in new
military construction, and $182 million in other ``implementation''
costs.
   Deputy Assistant Defense Secretary Robert Stone, who provided the
cost estimates, defended them.
   ``There is an old adage that it takes money to make money. For
base closures, it takes money to save money,'' Stone told the
subcommittee.
   Ribicoff said the commission made its recommendations ``after
serious consideration.'' Criticism was expected, he said. ``Change
is not always welcomed. In fact, it can be threatening.''
   ``We were heartened by the substantial evidence showing that
communities do recover from the temporary dislocations that result
from a base closing. Many end up much better off,'' Ribicoff said.
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., the subcommittee chairwoman,
asked Edwards about speculation some of the decisions may have been
motivated by politics.
   ``We were not only bipartisan. We were non-partisan,'' Edwards
replied.
   Frank Conahan, a ranking official of Congress' General Accounting
Office, said his agency has yet to find fault with the commission's
overall recommendations.
   ``We have not found any glaring errors,'' said Conahan, adding
the GAO's review will continue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
