<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Pinochet     03-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Pinochet,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Formed To Promote Pinochet's Re-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA VERGARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians and right-wing activists have
formed an organization promoting the re-election of military
President Augusto Pinochet, who was lost a referendum last year on
whether he should remain in office.
   Claudio Morales, a former councilman in Valparaiso, said the
group is made up of social leaders, independent politicians and
members of various right-wing parties who are ``convinced that the
best candidate we may have'' is Pinochet.
   The group was organized Tuesday night in Valparaiso, 75 miles
north west of Santiago.
   Several right-wing politicians and parties have also indicated
they would like Pinochet to run, but the Valparaiso group is the
first one especially organized to promote his candidacy.
   The 1980 constitution bars Pinochet from seeking re-election, but
in recent weeks the growing divisions among right-wing forces
prompted calls to find a way for him to run in the Dec. 14 election.
   The election was made mandatory by an Oct. 5 referendum, in which
voters overwhelmingly rejected a military proposal to extend
Pinochet's term until 1997.
   Supporters of a Pinochet candidacy say the constitution may be
changed to allow him to run, and the general's wife, Lucia Hiriart,
publicly supported such a constitutional amendment.
   Others say the constitutional restriction on re-election does not
apply to the 73-year-old president and army commander because he was
not elected in the first place. Pinochet seized power in a bloody
1973 coup.
   The government announced last week that it is considering a
plebiscite as early as June to approve unspecified constitutional
changes. There has been no indication, however, that the changes
would include one to allow Pinochet to run in December.
   Pablo Rodriguez, one of two right-wing politicians who have
formally announced their presidential candidacies, says he would
only withdraw from the race if Pinochet can run.
   Pinochet has admitted he cannot be a candidate under the present
constitutional terms. He told his supporters, however, that he will
tell them who to support in the presidential race.
</TEXT>
