<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Soviets     03-01 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Soviets,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young West Germans Unworried By Soviet Military Threat, Poll Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 90 percent of young West
Germans believe the Soviet bloc is not a military threat and most
want their country to cut defense spending, according to a poll
released Wednesday.
   The survey, commissioned by ZDF television, appeared to be yet
another sign of the positive attitude many Germans are developing
toward the Kremlin, especially toward Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his promise to withdraw troops from Europe.
   ZDF said the independent Forschungsgruppe Wahlen research company
surveyed 825 West Germans between 16 and 29 years old. The network
did not provide a margin of error for the poll, which was conducted
from Feb. 17 to Feb. 23.
   The poll said 87 percent do not feel militarily threatened by the
Warsaw Pact and 78 percent believe their nation should cut defense
spending, which has an annual level of about $30 billion.
   The results of the poll were described during a ZDF program
Wednesday night on the armed forces and provided in advance to The
Associated Press.
   Public opinion polls last year repeatedly said Gorbachev's
popularity far outstripped that of then-President Reagan.
   Many West Germans have come to regard the Cold War as being
nearly over, recent polls indicate. In addition, many appear smitten
with the ``Gorbymania'' orchestrated by the increasingly
image-conscious Kremlin.
   They also responded positively to Gorbachev's pledge earlier this
year to unilaterally cut armed forces by 500,000 troops in two
years, including a reduction of 240,000 soldiers in the European
theater.
   Gorbachev also said the production of arms and military supplies
would be slashed by 19.5 percent and 10,000 tanks would be
eliminated in Europe.
   The perception that the Soviet threat is diminishing has led to
growing questions about the need for U.S. military training flights
in West Germany and the routine maneuvers that chew up farmers'
fields and disrupt daily life.
   A key issue for the federal government in Bonn is whether to
replace the approximately 600 aging Lance nuclear missiles stationed
in West Germany.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government wants the decision delayed
until 1991 or 1992, to keep it from becoming an issue in next year's
general elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
