<FIRST>r w AM-DiplomatsResign 300   03-01 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomats Resign, 300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Terrorist Chief, Assistant Secretary of State Quit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Paul Bremer, the State Department's senior
terrorism expert, has resigned, sources said Wednesday.
   In addition, Rozanne L. Ridgway, assistant secretary of state for
European affairs, has also quit, said the sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Bremer, a 48-year-old career ambassador, will remain temporarily
to conduct a personnel study, the sources said.
   Bremer is a former U.S. envoy to The Netherlands and in a 22-year
diplomatic career he served as chief assistant to three secretaries
of state _ William P. Rogers, Henry A. Kissinger and Alexander M.
Haig Jr.
   There was speculation that Bremer would take a job with
Kissinger's private consulting firm.
   Ms. Ridgway, retiring after 31 years in the foreign service,
asked Secretary of State James A. Baker III to take her name out of
contention for the post of U.S. ambassador to the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization or for any other overseas job.
   A former ambassador to East Germany and Finland, she informed
Baker she wants to remain in the area with her husband, Coast Guard
Capt. Theodore Dening.
   Ms. Ridgway attended all five summit meetings former President
Reagan held with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and was
considered a senior expert on Soviet affairs.
   During the transition to the Bush administration, Ms. Ridgway was
understood to be in contention for a top State Department job, but
wasn't picked. No successor has been named to head the European
bureau, a post she has held since mid-1985.
   Bremer headed the Office to Counter Terrorism for 2 1@2 years.
His strong stand against terrorism, and criticism of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, complemented the views of George P. Shultz,
who was the Secretary of State during the period.
