<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan-Watkins     03-01 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-Watkins,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Nominee Confirmed, 98-1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-Confirmation Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan took his place at the helm
of the largest federal department Wednesday after the Senate
approved his nomination 98-1. One senator called the new health and
human services secretary a ``compassionate professional.''
   The lone vote against Sullivan was cast by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., who criticized the Atlanta doctor for declining to take a
position on several abortion-related issues, including research on
fetal tissue.
   In other confirmation action Wednesday:
   _The Senate voted 99-0 to approve retired Adm. James D. Watkins,
as the first career military man to head the Department of Energy,
which devotes two-thirds of its budget to developing, building and
testing the nation's nuclear arsenal at a network of 15 major plants
in a dozen states.
   Watkins, 61, who retired in 1986 after 41 years in the Navy,
encountered no opposition during the confirmation process and was
widely praised on Capitol Hill as a fit choice for guiding the
Energy Department at a time of growing controversy over the
condition of its nuclear weapons complex.
   _Edward J. Derwinski, nominated to head the new Veterans
Department, told his confirmation hearing he still doesn't believe
he endangered anyone 12 years ago with an unthinking warning to the
Korean embassy that one of their agents was about to defect to the
United States.
   In initial questioning by the Veterans Affairs Committee, no
senator criticized his action in the Korean matter, but Chairman
Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said, ``I do not intend to take a position
until the vote tomorrow.''
   _William J. Bennett, nominated to lead the fight against drug
abuse, told his confirmation hearing that a well-fashioned strategy
can ease the problem but that it ``will not disappear overnight.''
   Bennett appeared a virtual shoo-in for endorsement by the
Judiciary Committee, with his sharpest critic, Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., saying he was considering voting against the nomination but
that he hadn't made up his mind.
   Sullivan, a 55-year-old blood specialist, was roundly praised by
Democrats and Republicans alike for his commitment to the
health-care needs of the poor, demonstrated by his founding of the
Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta to train physicians to work
in medically underserved areas.
   ``I'm confident that Dr. Sullivan is going to be a caring
advocate for these millions of Americans,'' said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said the task of administering a
department with a nearly $400 billion budget and 114,000 employees
``must fall on the shoulders of a compassionate professional. I
believe that Dr. Sullivan is such a person.''
   The issue of abortion has been the most controversial for
Sullivan since his remarks in the Atlanta Journal Constitution that
he supported abortion and to Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., that he
favored retaining the Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade decision
legalizing the procedure.
   At his confirmation hearing before the Senate Finance Committee,
Sullivan apologized to Packwood for having ``misspoken'' his
position and said he holds the same views on the subject as the
president: He is opposed to abortion except in cases of rape, incest
or danger to the mother's life; he opposes federal financing of
abortions except when the mother's life is threatened, and he favors
reversal of Roe vs. Wade.
   Packwood, who is strongly pro-choice, said he disagreed with
Sullivan's stand on abortion, but he said the issue has gotten undue
attention considering that the Department of Health and Human
Services has few abortion-related activities.
   ``In every sense this man is qualified to do a first rate job.
The issue of abortion ought to be irrelevant,'' Packwood said.
   Several senators said that while they admired Sullivan's attempt
to avoid any conflicts of interest by forfeiting nearly $300,000 in
severance pay from his job as president of Morehouse, the sacrifice
wasn't necessary and could discourage others from taking government
jobs.
</TEXT>
