<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     03-01 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Assembly Approves Namibia Independence Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly on Wednesday approved
$416 million for the U.N. peacekeeping mission that will oversee
Namibia's passage to freedom after 74 years of South African rule.
   ``The show is on the road,'' declared Marrack Goulding, the
ndersecretary-general in charge of all U.N. peacekeeping operations.
   The one-year U.N. plan for Namibia's independence begins April 1.
   The 159-member assembly adopted by consensus a funding resolution
for a Namibia force that will consist of 4,650 peacekeepers, 500
police, and about 2,200 civilian staff and election monitors.
   The mission will oversee elections for a constituent assembly in
November that will organize a black majority-ruled government _
creating the world's newest independent nation and in the process
settling the last major colonial problem in Africa.
   U.N. officials confirmed publicly that South Africa will receive
a generous share of the U.N. funds as the force makes purchases in
the region, including $10.2 million in gasoline and aviation fuel.
   Some black African nations, led by Zambia and Zimbabwe, fought to
make the world body heed its own calls for trade embargoes on South
African products.
   ``We don't have any oil distribution in Namibia, so we have to
use the oil that is there,'' said Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N.
undersecretary-general in charge of the civilian phase of the
Namibia transition plan.
   ``For the military component, the maximum tasks come in the first
few weeks of the transition period,'' said Goulding.
   He said the military ``has to ensure that the South African
forces are confined to barracks; ... to start supervising the
withdrawal of South African forces down to 1,500; ... to start the
process of dismantling the command structures and taking into
custody the arms of the various local forces that South Africa has
set up in Namibia.''
   White-dominated South Africa has ruled Namibia since it captured
the colony from Germany during World War I.
   In December, South Africa signed accords with Angola and Cuba
agreeing to free Namibia if 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola
are sent home by mid-1991.
   Marxist Angola adjoins Namibia.
   Namibia is one of the world's most sparsely populated areas, with
an estimated 1.3 million people occupying territory as large as
France and West Germany combined. The Ovambo people inhabit the
relatively fertile northern region and make up about half the
population. There are 75,000 white residents.
   The economy is dominated by mining, with diamonds, uranium and
copper the principal minerals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Aflatoxin     03-01 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aflatoxin,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Amount of Aflatoxin in Food Supply Unlikely to Hurt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said
Wednesday that cancer-causing aflatoxin is unlikely to get into the
food supply in amounts great enough to hurt anyone.
   ``Anytime we have a drought, we are going to see more aflatoxin
problems,'' Yeutter told the House Appropriations subcommittee on
rural development, agriculture and related agencies. ``That doesn't
mean we're going to have more in the food supply ... or any that
slips in is going to hurt anyone.''
   Yeutter criticized a recent article in The Wall Street Journal
that said aflatoxin-tainted corn is moving through the nation's food
chain because of inadequate sampling and unreliable testing.
   He said the article implied that people are being cavalier about
the existence of the toxin.
   ``Everyone is going to do their best to minimize the risk of
letting aflatoxin into the food supply,'' he said. ``Nobody in the
food chain wants it.''
   Last year's heat and drought were ideal for development of the
fungus that produces aflatoxin, which researchers have linked to the
development of liver cancer in laboratory rats.
   The level of aflatoxin allowed in corn is 20 parts per billion.
   On Tuesday, the Food and Drug Administration said about 6 percent
_ 95 samples out of 1,650 _ of the field corn tested in recent
months had higher levels.
   That corn cannot be used for human consumption, but can be
diverted to feed non-dairy cattle, the FDA said.
   FDA tested about 263 samples of corn flour and corn meal and
found 2 percent, or six samples, to have more than 20 parts of
aflatoxin per billion. FDA policy requires that these products be
removed from the market.
   In answer to another question from the subcommittee, Yeutter said
he considers the chance of international trade reform to be better
than it has been in a decade.
   He said that there are some hurdles the United States and the
European Community must work out before talks in the Uruguay Round
resume next month in Geneva.
   ``I'm cautiously optimistic we'll get that worked out between now
and April,'' he told the committee.
   ``What happens in the Uruguay Round will determine what we should
have in farm legislation,'' Yeutter said.
   He said he doesn't anticipate any significant changes from the
1985 farm bill that is due to expire in 1990. He said Congress could
extend the 1985 law until the Uruguay talks are complete, or pass a
new bill and amend it as necessary after the negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
