<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More Arrested In Death Linked To Winnie Mandela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Wednesday that
three more people were arrested in the death of 14-year-old activist
Stompie Seipei, who purportedly was killed by Winnie Mandela's
bodyguards.
   Police Lt. Col. J.H. Labuscagne said the two men and one woman
will be formally charged in a Johannesburg court on Thursday. He did
not release their names but said the two men had links to Mrs.
Mandela's group of bodyguards, known as the Mandela United soccer
club.
   Three men who were part of Mandela United were charged earlier
with Seipei's murder.
   Mrs. Mandela is the wife of jailed African National Congress
leader Nelson Mandela.
   Seipei was allegedly beaten in December by the bodyguards at her
home in Soweto, outside Johannesburg. His decomposed body was found
in a field in January, police said.
   Mrs. Mandela denied any wrongdoing on her part, but refused to
give a full account of her role in the controversy involving the
soccer club, which she established in 1986.
