<FIRST>r w AM-US-Guatemala     03-01 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Guatemala,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Meets Guatemalan President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo, meeting
Wednesday with Vice President Dan Quayle, said leftist-ruled
Nicaragua should start democratic reforms before a final agreement
to disband the Contra rebels.
   Cerezo told reporters after his half-hour session with Quayle
that the U.S. officials ``still have reservations'' about the peace
agreement reached two weeks ago by the five Central American
presidents.
   Cerezo's session with Quayle and a similar meeting scheduled
Thursday with President Bush offered an opportunity to voice U.S.
concerns about Nicaragua's intentions in the agreement, U.S.
officials said.
   A chief complaint expressed by Bush administration officials is
lack of an enforcement mechanism to ensure the ruling Sandinistas in
Nicaragua live up to promised reforms.
   Quayle emphasized that concern Wednesday, and Bush is expected to
make the same point, administration officials said.
   Previous U.S. policy held that the U.S.-backed Contras provided
the goad which could push the Sandinistas into democratization.
   One major roadblock to a Nicaraguan peace plan has been an
inability to agree on whether disarmament of the Contras of internal
reforms in Nicaragua should come first.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega pledged in the agreement last
month to free political prisoners, hold early elections, allow
opposition parties access to the media and repatriate the Contras.
   But there was no timetable for those reforms and the five
presidents said they would agree on those details within 90 days.
   Cerezo, asked Wednesday when the Sandinistas should implement
reforms, said, ``They have to make the things before and at the same
time when we affirm the plans for the contras demobilization.''
   Cerezo said he assured Quayle the Contras would disarm ``in an
orderly manner.''
   Quayle encouraged continued meetings between the Central American
presidents and with U.S. representatives to further the peace
process, said an administration official who declined to be
identified.
   Cerezo said the Sandinistas need help from Europe and the United
States to rebuild their economy after almost a decade of internal
war and they know that assistance only will be offered if there is
peace throughout Central America.
   The vice president also brought up Guatemalan human rights with
Cerezo, said an official, speaking on condition of anonymity, but
the official offered no details.
   Administration officials wanted to discuss U.S. concerns over
continuing human rights abuses in Guatemala, State Department
sources said.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they are
convinced human rights violations are not a matter of government
policy but that those guilty of politically-motivated crimes must be
brought to justice.
   Americas Watch, a private rights group, has said Guatemala's
record on the rights issue is far worse than the administration is
willing to concede.
   Juan Mendez, the executive director of Americas Watch, told
Congress last month that Guatemala ``continues to have one of the
worst human rights records in the Western Hemisphere'' despite more
than three years of civilian government.
   Mendez said the number of violent abuses in Guatemala rose last
year and rural areas continue to live under de facto military
dictatorship.
</TEXT>
