<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CapitalGains     03-01 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Capital Gains,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pitches For Tax Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush drew on his recent Asian trip to
make a new pitch for lower capital gains taxes Wednesday, claiming
western Pacific businesses enjoy a competitive tax advantage over
U.S. companies.
   ``The `four dragons' of Hong Kong, Singapore, Taiwan and South
Korea all exempt long-term capital gains from tax, total exemption.
Japan also had no tax on capital gains during its meteoric rise to
economic power,'' Bush told a business group at the White House.
   In his 1989 budget, Bush proposed that the tax on capital gains
be lowered to a maximum of 15 percent from its current rate of 28
percent or, in some cases, 33 percent.
   ``While I was in Asia, this recent trip, I had a chance to think
seriously about what sets our trading partners apart from us, and I
realized that we may have erected a barrier to our own success and
deprived ourselves of vital long-term investment that our
competitors have always enjoyed,'' Bush said.
   He returned Monday from a five-day trip to Japan, China and South
Korea.
   Speaking to about 250 members of the Small Business Legislative
Council in the East Room, Bush said, ``By taxing capital gains, we
impede our own progress and we turn the playing field into an uphill
climb.''
   Bush claims that lowering the tax on capital gains _ profits from
the sale of stock, real estate, works of art or other assets _ will
spur business investment, reaping for the Treasury more than it
costs.
   However, the idea has generated fierce opposition in the
Democratic-controlled Congress, where leaders have sought to portray
it as a new tax break for the rich.
   Bush on Wednesday insisted the tax break will increase revenues
$4.8 billion annually.
   Private economists are divided on whether lowering capital gains
taxes would increase or decrease revenues.
   While in Seoul, Bush cautioned the South Korean National Assembly
to do more in opening markets and avoiding protectionism.
   He made reference to that in Wednesday's address, claiming he had
stressed to Asian trading partners ``at every stop...the need for
keeping these markets open.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
