<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SleepThieves     03-01 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sleep Thieves,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Begin Search for Robbers With Knock-Out Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Wednesday they are hunting for a couple
who allegedly lured their victims to hotel rooms, slipped
sleep-inducing drugs into their drinks and robbed them.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
investigators identified the suspects as Yousef Mahmoud Salim Abudl
Hawa, 48, of Jordan and Eilien Konga, 28, of Thailand.
   He said investigators had given photos of the pair to newspapers.
   The robberies using the sleep-inducing drugs have occurred in
metropolitan Tokyo since 1986, the official said.
   The Asahi Shimbun and other nationally circulated Japanese
newspapers said the equivalent of about $78,000 has been stolen in
26 ``dead sleep'' robberies.
   The Asahi said that in one case, a 58-year-old businessman
invited Konga into his hotel room in July 1987, only to have his
beer drugged and about $30,000 stolen from his wallet.
