<FIRST>r w AM-Homeless-WhiteHouse     03-01 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless-White House,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gore Seeks White House Conference on Homelessness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush should convene a conference on
homelessness because a coherent national strategy to deal with the
problem is urgently needed, said Sen. Albert Gore, who introduced
legislation Wednesday to authorize such a meeting.
   ``Now is the time for President Bush to show the leadership this
issue demands,'' said the Tennessee Democrat.
   Citing studies predicting 18 million Americans will be homeless
by the turn of the century if current policies continue, Gore said
``a coherent, long-range strategy is urgently needed.''
   ``This isn't the only answer, but it is an essential ingredient
to the comprehensive, effective policy we need,'' he added.
   Gore, an author of the Stewart B. McKinney Homeless Assistance
Act, said he welcomed recent trips to shelters for the homeless b
Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp. Bush has pledged
to provide the $682.8 million authorized by Congress in that
legislation.
   ``The White House conference we are proposing today can provide
substantive direction for their good intentions,'' Gore said.
   Gore's proposal for a White House conference would authorize
meetings and require a report to include specific recommendations
for executive and legislative action on homelessness within six
months after the sessions.
   Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn, who accompanied Gore at a news
conference to announce the proposal, said the conference would be
``welcome news'' to local and state officials who have been
providing shelter for the homeless after cuts in the federal housing
budget during the Reagan administration.
   Flynn had testified earlier as head of the U.S. Conference of
Mayors Task Force on Hunger and Homelessness at a House
subcommitteee on housing and community development hearing which
focused on the need for permanent affordable housing for low- and
moderate-income people.
   Flynn told the panel he had proposed a White House conference to
Bush.
   ``If we are ever to turn around these national figures of growing
homelessness, we need national leadership that cares about these
festering problems,'' said Flynn in a written statement.
</TEXT>
