<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-SpaceCouncil     03-01 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Space Council,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Names National Space Council Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday formally notified
Congress of the composition of the National Space Council
established in the White House to oversee and coordinate space
policy.
   As Bush had revealed in his Feb. 9 budget message and speech to
Congress, the 10-member council will be headed by Vice President Dan
Quayle.
   Other members of the council will include Secretary of State
James A. Baker III, Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher and the secretary of defense.
   Bush still is fighting to get John Tower confirmed by the Senate
for the Pentagon post.
   Bush said the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the
president's assistant for science and technology will participate in
council meetings ``as appropriate.''
   The council, among other things, will review and recommend
modifications of national space policy.
   In his budget message to Congress, Bush said that is
administration ``is committed to an aggressive program to maintain
and press ahead with `the American edge' _ U.S. leadership in key
areas of space activity.''
   In that message, Bush proposed to increase funding in fiscal 1990
for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration by $2.4
billion, or 22 percent over the figure for 1989.
