<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlightAttendant     03-01 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight Attendant,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crew Member Recalls Horror and Heroism Of Flight 811</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heroism by both passengers and crew saved
countless lives during the ``unbelievable horror'' when a United
Airlines jet ripped open over the Pacific, spilling nine passengers
to their deaths, a crew member said.
   ``I felt like Dorothy in the Wizard of Oz when her house gets
picked up and everything gets blown away,'' purser Sarah Shanahan
said in an interview in Wednesday's editions of the Honolulu
Star-Bulletin.
   ``We had some flight attendants who had to hang on to the first
class stairwell when it actually happened. And, by golly, it held.
It helped to protect the lives of at least three people that I know
of,'' said Shanahan, 42, who has worked for United for 21 years.
   Federal investigators suspect the forward cargo door on the
Boeing 747 jet, United's Flight 811 bound for Auckland, New Zealand,
popped open during the flight Friday, tearing a 10-by-20-foot hole
in the plane's fuselage. The plane carried 354 people, including 18
crew members.
   ``I instantly knew that we had a hole in the airplane,'' said
Shanahan. She said her first reaction was to find oxygen to keep
from passing out.
   Because of the damage, the plane's emergency oxygen system did
not activate, investigators said. Shanahan said she searched
desperately for an oxygen bottle, finally finding one and taking ``a
few real strong inhalations'' to regain her strength.
   ``Then I stopped and I collected my thoughts for just a second. I
realized that the plane was flying. It was not in an uncontrolled
rapid descent.''
   Capt. David M. Cronin flew the crippled jet 100 miles on two of
four engines, landing safely at Honolulu International Airport 25
minutes later. Twenty-seven people were injured, with only two still
hospitalized Wednesday.
   Shanahan said it was ``truly a miracle that there were not more
injuries to people from things flying around in the cabin. There
were ice buckets, racks of glasses, cartons of juice and bins of
things around.''
   The decompression of the plane took only a few seconds, and
during that time ``anything that wasn't nailed down moved,'' she
said.
   Shanahan said she inched her way forward and saw ``an incredible
amount of structural damage'' and that two or three crew members
were helping passengers.
   ``They were reassuring people. I could see them physically
touching arms. I don't know what they were saying because the noise
was so incredible you couldn't hear yourself think,'' Sanahan said.
   She started walking back through the cabin, telling passengers to
put on life vests and inflate one chamber. She said she tried using
the public address system but it was too noisy for it to be heard,
so she found a megaphone.
   Shanahan said she instructed the passengers to tighten their seat
belts, grab their ankles and ``stay down until you know we're back
on earth and we've stopped.''
   She said she found three young men and assigned them to help with
the evacuation upon landing, instructing them on how to open the
emergency exit and deploy the inflatable slide, making them repeat
the instructions back to her.
   She said she told them, ``This is a critical job. They will pile
up at the bottom of the slide. They will get badly injured. It is
vital that you stay there.''
   ``And they did. God bless them. They did,'' Shanahan said.
   When the captain announced that the plane was two minutes from
the end of the runway, ``people kept unfastening their seat belts
and standing up to look out the windows,'' she said. ``I'm sure that
they wanted the reassurance. They wanted to see those Honolulu city
lights.
   ``That's why I'm hoarse. I screamed for two minutes: `Grab your
ankles. Stay down, stay down, stay down,''' Shanahan said.
   ``It was the best landing. It was just perfect. It was smooth. It
was wonderful,'' she said.
   Once the plane stopped, Shanhan said she whipped open the door
and began ordering the passengers to form double lines and leap onto
the slide.
   Shanahan said she didn't know until she was off the plane that
passengers had been lost. It was only then that she saw the size of
the hole.
</TEXT>
