<FIRST>r w AM-Thornburgh-Rushdie     03-01 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Rushdie,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishers, Booksellers Now Satisfied With Response To Book Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of publishers and booksellers
met with the attorney general and FBI director Wednesday and said
they are now satisfied with the federal response to threats of
violence related to Salman Rushdie's book, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Thirteen publishing and bookselling executives met privately for
an hour at the Justice Department with Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh and FBI Director William Sessions.
   Afterward, Lawrence Hughes, chairman of Hearst Trade Books Group
and the Association of American Publishers, said, ``I'm satisfied
they're fully committed to put whatever resources they can into
combating this terrorist threat.''
   Hughes, whose group represents 250 publishers who put out 75
percent of the nation's books, added that the executives had called
for the meeting because ``the response from the government had been
slow up to now. There was no immediate response to Ayatollah
Khomeini's death threat. It was quite a few days before anybody in
the government said anything.''
   On Tuesday, bombs exploded in two Berkeley, Calif., bookstores
and the offices of a weekly newspaper in New York. Afterward,
President Bush ordered the Justice Department to get involved.
   Justice spokesman Loye Miller said the FBI has opened a criminal
investigation of the three blasts.
   After the meeting, Thornburgh said, ``Every resource available
will be committed to ensure individuals and organizations in this
country will be protected in the exercise of their First Amendment
rights.''
   He said the group discussed how the FBI can gather intelligence
and how people outside government can help.
   Bernie Rath, executive director of the American Booksellers
Association, which represents owners of 7,000 bookstores, said
100,000 copies of the book will be shipped this weekend and ``only a
quarter-inch of plate glass will stand between the booksellers'
ideals and what's happening on the streets.''
   He predicted virtually all bookstores will sell the novel.
   Rath said he was satisfied with the federal response, which he
said included setting up a hotline for businesses to report threats.
``Maybe they can see patterns in the threats to help with the
intelligence effort,'' Rath said.
   He said threats numbered in the hundreds now, against people
involved in selling the book.
   Bush had previously spoken out against Khomeini's death threat
against Rushdie, who is British.
</TEXT>
