<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Moslems 1stLd-Writethru a0780 03-01 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Moslems, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Fundamentalists Celebrate Victories In Municipal Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th pvs, ``It also..., to ADD analysts
saying Moslem triumph was over local issues; picks up 5th pvs, ``In Umm...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic flags flew over Israeli Arab cities
Wednesday as Moslem fundamentalists celebrated their victories in
municipal elections, the results of which have frightened many Jews.
   The Islamic Movement, competing for the first time in Tuesday's
balloting, emerged as a growing influence among the 400,000 eligible
Arab voters in Israel.
   The movement challenged the Communist Party, the traditional
dominant force in Arab municipalities, and scored a landslide
victory in Umm El Fahem, the second-largest Arab town.
   It also took over the three smaller cities of Kafr Kassim, Kafr
Bara and Kafr Kana, and won seats in four other city councils _
including six seats of the 19-member council in the town of
Nazareth, often called ``red Nazareth'' because of its Communist
affiliation.
   Although Jewish leaders expressed fears that the results
indicated growing extremism in the Arab sector, Arab analysts said
the Islamic movement had won because it provided badly needed
municipal services.
   Lutfy Mashour, editor of the Arabic-language Sinara newspaper in
Nazareth, said the Islamic victory was not ``a matter of religion,
it's a matter of services.''
   In Umm El Fahem, Sheikh Raed Salah Mahajneh, a bearded,
30-year-old preacher, won more than 72 percent of the vote, or 11 of
15 seats on the city council, defeating the town's Communist mayor.
   ``Islam will sweep the world,'' a triumphant aide at Mahajneh's
office said. ``We in Umm el Fahem take the best from the Communists
and the best from the capitalists. This is Islam.''
   Flags of Islam, traditionally green, flew over the Galilee city
of over 20,000 and jubilant residents circled through town in their
cars plastered with green party stickers, creating a huge traffic
jam.
   The fundamentalist victories alarmed Israeli Jewish leaders of
virtually all parties.
   ``The Islamic Movement's aim is to gain leadership in (Israel's)
Arab sector. It's a very worrisome sign,'' said Interior Minister
Arye Deri of the ultra-Orthodox Shas party.
   Uzi Baram of the left-leaning Labor party said he preferred the
Communist Party, which ``at least grants legitimacy to the state of
Israel and sees itself as part of it.
   ``The Islamic Movement is a dangerous movement,'' he said on
Israel television.
   The Islamic Movement's leader, Sheikh Abdallah Nimer Darwish,
said his party would abide by the law and would not harm the state
of Israel ``by word or by deed.''
   Arab analysts said the movement gained its power by providing
services to the population.
   ``It's a local issue,'' said Hashem Abdel Rachman, a spokesman
for the Islamic movement. ``People saw that the Islamic Movement
gave them good services and voted according to what they saw.''
   Analysts said it took the movement about five years of building
schools and running volunteer camps to win over Umm El Fahem, which
an Arab reporter described as ``easily the worst slum in Israel.''
Many roads in the city are not paved and there are serious sewage
problems.
</TEXT>
