<DOCNO> AP890301-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0671 03-01 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Gather Outside Parliament to Protest Ethnic Albanians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with 50,000 Slavs fleeing Kosovo, employees
ordered back to work, background on population and nationalities; no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEL5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people demonstrating
against ethnic Albanians massed outside Parliament on Wednesday
while a senior official inside told lawmakers ethnic violence
threatens to tear Yugoslavia apart.
   Lazar Mojsov, a member of the ruling 12-man state presidency,
also charged that an illegal group of ethnic Albanians has detailed
plans to disrupt southern Kosovo province, the state-run news agency
Tanjug said.
   ``The integrity of Yugoslavia is jeopardized to the extreme
degree,'' Mojsov said in comments carried on Belgrade radio.
   The government indefinitely extended a ban on all public
gatherings in Kosovo, Tanjug said, following more than a week of
widespread unrest in the province.
   Outside Parliament, about 4,000 members of the Serb and
Montenegrin minority from Kosovo blocked streets and chanted songs
to protest alleged persecution in the province by Albanians, who
make up 90 percent of Kosovo's estimated 2 million people.
   Mojsov told the assembly 50,000 Slavs emigrated from Kosovo since
1981 because of harassment.
   The flag-carrying protesters were joined by at least 10,000
Belgrade sympathizers. On Tuesday, a Belgrade rally led by Serbian
Communist Party boss Slobodan Milosevic drew an estimated 500,000
people.
   Taxi drivers, carrying large portraits of Milosevic on their
cars, provided free transportation for the elderly.
   The mainly Christian Serbs believe the predominantly Moslem
Albanians in Kosovo, which was ancient Serbia's heartland, want to
unite the province with neighboring Albania. The ethnic Albanians
have demanded that Kosovo's autonomy not be restricted.
   Growing ethnic nationalism and an economic crisis have created
the greatest threat to Yugoslav unity since the 1980 death of
President Tito, whose leadership held the loose confederation of six
republics and two provinces together. The country's 23 million
citizens belong to a number of different nationalities and religions.
   Mojsov said the presidency has retrieved a document signed by
members of ``an illegal Kosovo group,'' detailing plans for
destabilizing the province, according to Tanjug.
   The plan's initial stage reportedly called for ``passive strikes
in factories, firms, schools and universities'' and other actions,
which Mojsov said were ``carried out in full'' last week.
   The Parliament met to discuss the deteriorating security in the
country following the Kosovo protests and counterdemonstrations by
angry Serbs in Belgrade and other parts of Serbia.
   Frontier controls have been tightened to ``prevent the bringing
in of explosives, arms, ammunition, hostile propaganda material and
illegal crossings of the country's borders,'' Vice Premier Janez
Zemljaric told Parliament.
   A ban on gatherings in Kosovo was introduced in November when up
to 100,000 ethnic Albanians demonstrated in Kosovo's capital
Pristina against the forced resignations of some top ethnic Albanian
provincial leaders as demanded by Serbia.
   The ban, as extended Wednesday, also prohibits massive arrivals
in the province. This was apparently designed to prevent Serbs from
converging on Kosovo.
   The protesting Serbs and Montenegrins walked from the railroad
station to Parliament, jamming streets and interrupting traffic as
Belgrade residents cheered them.
   At the station they were greeted by the Belgrade theological
seminary students choir, which sang Serbian Orthodox songs, banned
until recently but now freely performed.
   Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, was peaceful Wednesday. More
police, military personnel and army vehicles were seen in the area.
   Zemljaric said that 23,500 people in essential services in the
provinces were ordered back to work.
   About 500 ethnic Albanians in the Trepca lead-zinc mine in Kosovo
continued their strike to protest Serbian plans to change
constitutional provisions in a bid to win greater control over the
province.
   On Monday, about 1,300 ethnic Albanian miners at Trepca left the
pits after their eight-day sit-in forced the resignation of three
Kosovo party leaders whom they consider pro-Serbian.
   Both Croatia and Slovenia, Yugoslavia's most
economically-advanced republics, support the ethnic Albanian's
demands for guarantees that autonomy of their province will not be
limited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
