<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AgentKilled     03-01 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Killed,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search For DEA Agent Killer Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unarmed federal drug agent shot to death in an
undercover operation was wearing a radio transmitter and had five
backup men, but they lost contact as he drove off with the man
suspected of killing him, officials said Wednesday.
   The murder of undercover Special Agent Everette Hatcher on
Tuesday was the first killing of a Drug Enforcement Administration
officer in the New York area since 1972, said DEA spokesman Robert
Strang.
   The DEA, FBI and police issued an all-points bulletin for
Constible ``Gus'' Farace, 28, of Staten Island.
   Farace was released from the Elmira Correction Facility in June
1988 after serving eight years for the 1979 kidnapping and murder of
a New Jersey teen-ager, said police sources who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney said he would seek the death penalty
under the new federal drug bill when Hatcher's killer is caught.
   Investigators do not believe Hatcher's ``cover was blown or that
he was known to be a law enforcement officer,'' said William Y.
Doran, special agent in charge of the FBI's Criminal Division.
   ``This was not a `buy and bust' situation. There were no drugs
present. There was no money present,'' Doran said. ``The killing was
out of cold-bloodedness as far as we can determine.''
   He said Hatcher's wire had not been disturbed.
   Hatcher was found slumped over the wheel of an unmarked car on a
dead-end street on Staten Island at 10:15 p.m. Tuesday, shot four
times in the head and upper body, apparently from outside the car,
authorities said.
   Shortly after 9 p.m., Hatcher notified his back-up team that he
and Farace were going to drive their cars to a diner, said Robert
Stutman, special agent in charge of the DEA's New York City bureau.
   ``Shortly after that they (the agents) lost contact with the
transmitter,'' Stutman said. He said they had dropped back so as not
to be spotted and there was considerable traffic.
   The back-up team lost sight of Hatcher and began looking for the
agent, without success, at various diners on the boulevard until
returning to the original meeting area and finding Hatcher's car.
   Hatcher, 46, had worked at the New York office since joining the
DEA in 1972. At the time of his death, the agent was part of a joint
DEA-FBI Task Force engaged in a long-term drug investigation,
officials said.
   Two other DEA agents have been shot and wounded in New York City
in the last six months, but none has been killed in the New York
area since October 12, 1972, when Special Agent Frank Tummillo was
shot in a midtown hotel.
   Tummillo's partner, Supervisory Agent Thomas J. Devine, died
Sept. 25, 1982, of wounds he suffered during the 1972 shooting,
Strang said.
</TEXT>
