<FIRST>u a AM-SmokingPolicy     03-01 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoking Policy,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Heat As Smoking Policy Takes Effect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It isn't easy adopting smoking
restrictions in the heart of tobacco country, as the University of
Louisville discovered when it tried to put a stringent smoking
policy into effect last fall.
   But it is possible, and new regulations went into effect
Wednesday that try to give campus smokers and non-smokers equal
rights to puff and not be puffed upon.
   ``I hope that this is an issue that we can put behind us,'' said
Dan Hall, a university official who met twice with the Kentucky
General Assembly's Tobacco Task Force to iron out details that
didn't set well with lawmakers representing Kentucky burley
producers.
   ``It's a hard issue for anybody who lives in a tobacco state,''
said Justine Speer, dean of the university's School of Nursing.
   The revised regulations, approved by University President Donald
Swain last month, did away with an especially controversial
provision in the original regulations that would have favored
non-smokers in disputes with smokers.
   After the first draft drew fire last November, some lawmakers
threatened to cut the university's budget.
   But in December, the university agreed to rewrite portions of the
policy to make sure smokers and non-smokers would be treated
evenhandedly.
   Under the revision, department heads will discuss and settle
conflicts over smoking with employees and their supervisors.
   ``The university feels that it's been responsive to the concerns
of many of the legislators in those two meetings, and my hope is
that it will be received as such,'' Hall said.
   The new policy bans smoking in classrooms and elevators, as did
the early proposal, but calls for more modest restrictions in
hallways, lounges and other public areas, where smoking will be
allowed in designated areas.
   Hall said the rules would be introduced gradually as signs are
printed and posted designating the smoking and non-smoking areas.
   Ms. Speer said nursing students and faculty worked out their own
smoking policy several months ago, before the issue surfaced
campus-wide.
   Nursing faculty members _ none of whom smoke _ and students voted
not to smoke in halls outside classrooms, Ms. Speer said. Smoking is
also prohibited inside classrooms.
   The nursing students' lounge is divided for smokers and
non-smokers, and staff members have separate lounges, she said.
   Although the school is sensitive to the issues of tobacco
farmers, it also wants to provide a ``healthful environment'' to
non-smokers, she said.
   ``There are very few people in our area who smoke anymore,'' she
said. ``It's just like people have learned.''
</TEXT>
