<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with statement by Kerry, D-Mass., that he
will oppose Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower has 36 firm Republican votes in
favor of confirming him as defense secretary with 36 Democrats
committed in opposition and 27 senators describing themselves as
uncommitted, according to an Associated Press survey.
   The uncommitted senators include 19 Democrats and eight
Republicans.
   When the tally is altered to reflect senators who are leaning
either for or against the nomination, but not firmly committed, the
result is 42-39 against Tower.
   That count includes Republican Larry Pressler of South Dakota
against Tower, the only Republican counted as a possible vote
against confirmation. No Democrats are considered leaning in favor
of a ``yes'' vote.
   One senator, Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, refused to reply to the
survey even though a spokesman said he has made up his mind.
   Confirmation requires a simple majority. Democrats hold a 55-45
majority in the Senate, so Tower would need to hold all Republicans
and gain five Democrats to give Vice President Dan Quayle a chance
to cast the tie-breaking vote for his confirmation.
   Here, in alphabetical order, is the vote count as of Wednesday on
the Tower nomination.
