<FIRST>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0621 03-01 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede: SEOUL</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Korea, North Korea Resume Political Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with talks resuming; picks up 2nd
graf `Last month's...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of South Korea and North Korea
met at the border on Thursday and resumed talks on a possible
meeting between their prime ministers.
   Delegates from the two sides exchanged greetings at the Panmunjom
truce site and chatted for about 10 minutes before beginning formal
deliberations.
   Last month's talks bogged down after North Korea demanded a halt
to joint U.S.-South Korean military exercises. The Pyongyang
government repeated that demand Wednesday.
   North Korea has said the talks cannot progress unless the ``Team
Spirit'' exercises, an annual event since 1976, are canceled.
   ``The South Koran authorities should, first of all, have a
corrrect fundamental stand and attitude toward the dialogue and take
a determined stand of discontinuing the `Team Spirit' joint military
exercises at once,'' North Korea's official Central News Agency said
in a report monitored in Tokyo.
   Another factor that may affect the dialogue would be Seoul's
blocking of dissidents from meeting with North Korean officials on
national unification Wednesday.
   South Korean dissidents, defying a government ban, scheduled the
meeting at the truce village of Panmunjom, but police overpowered
and arrested 28 dissidents heading to the site.
   Before the Feb. 8 meeting at the border village of Panmunjom,
hopes were high the countries would be able to agree on terms for
the prime ministers' meeting. It would be the highest-ranking
meeting ever between communist North Korea and capitalist South
Korea.
   Despite the North Korean demand, military officials of the United
States and South Korea have made it clear they will not halt this
year's exercises.
   Seoul observers believe the hardened North Korean stand also is
expected to affect a scheduled meeting March 9 between sports
officials of the two nations to form a single delegation to the 1990
Asian Games in Beijing.
   It's also believed North Korea may be displeased with President
Bush's recent visit to Seoul and last week's defection to Seoul of
two North Korean students.
   While in Seoul, Bush reaffirmed Washington's security commitment
to South Korea and said the United States would continue its
military presence. About 42,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South
Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
