<DOCNO> AP890301-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru a0771 03-01 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0771,0893</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Appeals to Pilots To Defy Machinists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with details of Lorenzo's offer
to pilots; picks up 13th graf pvs, `More talks...; a version moved on financial
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines struggled Wednesday to avert a
weekend Machinists strike, offering pilots sweeter pay, job security
and other promises if they sign a new contract and defy a walkout by
fellow workers.
   ``If the pilots and other employees support the picket line and
don't show up for work, Eastern cannot survive,'' Frank Lorenzo,
chairman of Eastern's parent company Texas Air Corp., said in a
videotaped message sent to pilots of the unprofitable airline.
   The pilots' participation is considered pivotal to the success of
the Machinists' strike, which is to begin at 12:01 a.m. Saturday
unless there is a breakthrough in the union's 17-month-old contract
negotiations.
   Leaders of the pilots' union have urged their 3,500 members to
honor Machinists picket lines but indicated last week they would
reconsider if management made contract concessions to them.
   Lorenzo's message marked the most dramatic appeal yet by
management to quell the latest in a series of labor crises that have
afflicted Eastern for years and have have helped bring it close to
bankruptcy.
   He promised a five-year pilots pact with pledges of no furloughs
and offered other protections in the event Eastern sought bankruptcy
court protection or was merged into sister Texas Air carrier
Continental Airlines. The pact also offers 3 percent pay increases
for 1992 and 1993.
   The pilots union reacted skeptically and said close inspection
showed little substance to Lorenzo's words.
   ``In his videotape, Lorenzo made a fine theatrical performance,''
the pilots executive council said in a statement to members. ``Don't
be misled. Much work still needs to be done.''
   The council said the offer doesn't pledge job security and
actually contains $64 million in concessions, plus a demand that
pilots drop longstanding grievances it said were worth an additional
$250 million.
   ``The company has gone outside the normal bargaining process and
directly to the pilots,'' said Ron Cole, spokesman for the Eastern
local of the pilots' union. ``We think this is just part of a
continuing disinformation campaign designed to divide the pilots'
group.''
   The pilots' master executive council went into special session
Wednesday afternoon in Washington, Cole said.
   In other developments Wednesday:
   _ A federal judge took under consideration Eastern's request to
hire outside contractors to service 26 aircraft on the ground but
did not say whether he would rule before the strike deadline.
   _ Attorneys for the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers said they were seeking a federal court order
allowing Machinists to picket other airlines with which the
international union has contracts.
   _ Eastern employees reported receiving formal notification of
possible layoffs and plant closings, under the new federal 60-day
plant closing notification law.
   Eastern, which says it has lost more than $1 billion in the past
decade and is losing more than $1 million a day, wants $150 million
in wage concessions from the Machinists, who represent 8,500
mechanics, baggage handlers and other ground services workers.
   More talks were expected with the company on a contract
addressing pilots' demands for job security, a long-term financial
commitment to Eastern, and an agreement to keep Eastern routes from
being transferred to Continental, Texas Air's predominantly
non-union carrier.
   ``We would hope the pilots would remember that Lorenzo's made
agreements before and contracts mean nothing to him. He's not to be
trusted,'' said Frank Ortis, vice president of Machinists Local 702.
   Lorenzo earned a union-busting reputation when, faced with labor
strife at Continental in 1983, he filed for federal bankruptcy
reorganization and got Continental labor contracts abrogated.
   Eastern apparently would have to use management pilots and
possibly recently hired pilots to fly if the pilots' union honored
the machinists' picket lines. The flight attendants' union
leadership has urged its 5,900 Eastern members to honor Eastern
picket lines.
   In Wednesday's court hearing, U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins
took under consideration Eastern's request for permission to hire
outside contractors to service its aircraft.
   Eastern attorneys said 26 of its approximately 250 planes are on
the ground awaiting service because of a Machinists slowdown. The
company also reported incidents of vandalism.
   Los Angeles television station KTTV reported that Eastern has
contracted with outside companies, including concerns based in Hong
Kong, Costa Rica and Europe, to service its planes during a strike.
Elsinore Aerospace Companies of Downey, Calif., is among companies
hired, the station said.
   Eastern spokesman Matell said the company wouldn't discuss strike
contingency plans.
   In Washington, attorney Joseph Guerrieri Jr. said the machinists
were seeking an emergency declaration with the federal court to
allow the union's members to picket other airlines that have
contracts with the union.
   They are Northwest Airlines, USAir, Trans World Airlines, United
Airlines and Piedmont Airlines. A favorable court ruling could
result in Machinists honoring picket lines at those carriers, he
said.
   AFL-CIO officials have said they want their 14 million members to
boycott Eastern and Continental and help the Machinists in a strike.
The Machinists said they will picket other airlines, ships and other
transportation services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
