<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0700 03-01 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0700,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Chief Says Beating Policy Open to Soldiers' Judgment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with new developments, move up
background on trial. Pick up 9th pvs, ``Earlier testimony...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRYAT MALACHI, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's army chief of staff on
Wednesday defended the policy of beating Palestinian rioters but
acknowledged that in many cases the individual soldier decides how
much force to use.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron made the comments as he testified in the
trial of four soldiers charged with manslaughter in the beating
death of a 42-year-old Arab refugee last August.
   It was the army chief's most comprehensive explanation to date of
a policy that prompted harsh foreign criticism after pictures of
soldiers clubbing Palestinians were seen on worldwide television.
   He said beating as punishment was prohibited and force should not
be used once a riot is over. ``Deterrence is not the goal,
overcoming violence is,'' Shomron said, ``but when someone stops
resisting, that's a matter of opinion.''
   In another development Wednesday, soldiers arrested two
Palestinians who tried to stab and kidnap a Jewish settler in the
West Bank, the army reported.
   An army spokeswoman said a car ``approached in a suspicious
manner'' when a settler left his vehicle, then two men jumped out
and one tried to stab the settler while the other pushed him into
the car.
   The settler escaped and alerted soldiers, who closed the area and
erected roadblocks, the spokeswoman said. The Palestinians abandoned
their vehicle and fled on foot.
   Also Wednesday, anonymous telephone callers to a news agency and
to an Arab lawyer demanded the release of all Palestinian prisoners
held by Israel in exchange for the release of an Israeli paratrooper.
   Avi Sassportas, 21, has been missing since Feb. 16, when he
disappeared on his way home to Ashdod, south of Tel Aviv.
   Shomron, testifying before a three-judge military court, said
orders issued to commanders on Feb. 23, 1988 regarding beatings
outlined proper procedures.
   The army has contended that beatings are necessary to subdue
riots which have raged in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
since the Palestinian uprising broke out Dec. 8, 1987.
   ``Dispersing a violent demonstration must be done with force,''
Shomron said. ``Let us be clear these are not demonstrations over
food subsidies, but violent demonstrations that endanger the lives
of our soldiers.''
   ``You can beat someone to prevent an incident, disperse a violent
demonstration or to stop someone who is resisting an arrest,'' he
said.
   The three privates and a first sergeant are charged in the
beating death Aug. 22 of Hani Shami, 42, at the Jabaliya refugee
camp in the Gaza Strip. They face maximum prison terms of 20 years
if convicted.
   Earlier testimony said a stone-thrower the soldiers were pursuing
ran into Shami's house and, when Shami tried to keep them out, the
soldiers broke the door down, threw him to the ground, beat him with
a broom and kicked him.
   An autopsy determined he died of a punctured lung, and at least
12 of his ribs were broken.
   The courtroom's 50 seats were full Wednesday and relatives of the
defendants, who served in the elite Givati Brigade, were seated
behind them. Final statements in the case are expected next week.
   Defense lawyer Uziel Atzmon repeatedly asked Shomron precisely
when beatings were legal and when they were not.
   ``You are asking me about gray areas and asking for clear
answers,'' said Shomron, who spent 2{ hours on the stand. ``Soldiers
are told to use their own judgment _ how severe the situation is and
how much force is necessary.
   ``It is possible that these events will be seen as a deviation.
It shows how difficult the situation is.''
   ``I am responsible for the orders given but not for the actions
of every soldier,'' he testified. ``I expect the soldiers will
fulfill their legal orders.
   ``If officers give orders to troops that are not legal, it is no
doubt proper to investigate these orders.''
   At least 387 Palestinians have been killed in the uprising, most
shot to death in confrontations with soldiers, and 17 Israelis have
been killed. Thousands of Palestinians have been wounded or beaten.
   Six Palestinians were reported wounded by Israeli soldiers
Wednesday, three in the West Bank city of Nablus and three at the
Khan Yunis refugee camp in the Gaza Strip. Those wounded at the camp
included an 8-year-old boy shot in the chest, Arab doctors said.
</TEXT>
