<FIRST>u a AM-Henderson-Pollard 1stLd-Writethru a0772 03-01 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Henderson-Pollard, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0772,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magistrate Denies Motion to Transfer Convicted Spy's Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to CLARIFY that magistrate recommended denying
the motion, sted denied it, comments from father and warden, other details;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of convicted spy Jonathan Pollard
should be denied her request for independent medical care, as well
as her wish to be transferred from the Federal Medical Center in
Rochester, a federal magistrate recommended Wednesday.
   Magistrate Janice Symchych also recommended denying Anne
Henderson-Pollard's motions for further hearings, medical furlough
and removal of 24-hour surveillance at the Federal Medical Center.
   Henderson-Pollard, 28, who has several medical problems, alleged
in a lawsuit against the Rochester facility that what she called
inadequate care had amounted to cruel and unusual punishment. She is
serving two concurrent five-year prison terms on charges related to
her husband's spy activities.
   ``The record here supports a clear finding of no deliberate
indifference to her serious medical needs,'' Symchych said in
rebuffing Henderson-Pollard's request for an independent medical
examination and treatment.
   Federal Medical Center warden Joseph Bogan, she said, should be
``commended for his efforts to sensitively balance the medical needs
of the petitioner with the security needs of an orderly penal
administration of the Bureau of Prisons.''
   The magistrate's recommendations will go to U.S. District Judge
Harry MacLaughlin, who will make a determination, Bogan said. The
parties have 10 days to file objections, he said.
   Henderson-Pollard's father, Bernard Henderson of Secaucus, N.J.,
said he was ``appalled'' by the magistrate's recommendations but the
family had not decided whether to appeal because they had not seen
the ruling.
</TEXT>
