<FIRST>u a AM-TinyTown 2ndLd-Writethru a0836 03-01 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tiny Town, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0836,0992</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bolan, Iowa (</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `Letterman also ..., to define a standstill parade;
INSERTS 3 grafs after 12th graf, ``When they ..., to UPDATE with visitors'
activities after the show; note that `Late Night' airs in New York City
at 12:30 a.m. EST Thursday; may air late Wednesday in westerly time zones.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY54</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They oohed and aahed at Times Square and the
Statue of Liberty, then gasped when the tour bus squeezed within 2
inches of a truck as it maneuvered through Manhattan's clogged
streets on Wednesday.
   The folks from Bolan, Iowa, were clearly a long way from home.
   ``You'll never run into this traffic in Bolan,'' said Linda
Nydegger. ``I like to visit but I sure wouldn't want to live here.''
   ``We wave at everybody. They give each other the bird,'' said
Daryl McCready, comparing motorists in Bolan and Manhattan.
   The entire population of Bolan's metropolitan area _ six
Bolanites and 10 from the ``suburbs'' _ had taken David Letterman up
on his offer to visit the big city.
   Letterman, prompted by a staffer intrigued by Bolan, paid for the
Iowans to come to New York for three days and appear on his show,
``Late Night with David Letterman.''
   On the show, Letterman immediately tried to dig up the dirt on a
town where everybody knows everybody and then some. ``Do you have a
town slut?'' he asked Ruth Hansen, 73. ``If so, when she comes up,
point her out.''
   Mrs. Hansen, a 50-year resident, chuckled at that. She and
Bolan's oldest resident, Agnes DeMaris, 78, were interviewed during
Wednesday's taping of the show to air early Thursday. Then Letterman
brought the whole town onstage.
   Letterman also put on the spot Lori Nydegger, 23, a weekend
resident who helped organize a standstill parade _ it doesn't move
and spectators walk around it _ to celebrate the town's 100th
anniversary three years ago.
   ``So, you're just here for the free trip,'' Letterman said as she
blushed and shook her head. ``Let's string her up.''
   Mrs. DeMaris, who is confined to a wheelchair, said in an
interview afterwards that she didn't want to make the trip because
of her physical condition but the Letterman staff insisted on the
entire town's attendance.
   ``When they told me the rest of them couldn't go if I didn't, I
decided I wouldn't make them people stay home because of me,'' she
said. ``I'll be tired tomorrow. I'm going home on the morning flight
but it was well worth it.''
   After the show, the Bolan residents headed off for dinner at a
Beefsteak Charlie's restaurant in Manhattan, courtesy of Letterman.
   ``It's like a dream. You don't want it to stop,'' said Duane
Abrahams, who along with the others will each be paid $150 for
appearing on the show. ``We've had this red carpet treatment.
They've just rolled it out.''
   The visitors planned to watch the show during a party they were
planning for their hotel rooms at the Mayflower Hotel, where they
were staying.
   At home, friends were house-sitting all the houses in Bolan, and
the post-bowling crowd at JJ's Tavern in nearby Northwood was
expected to linger longer than usual to catch the Letterman show on
the TV above the bar.
   ``I don't think there's anybody in Worth County that won't be
watching it,'' said Diane VanHorn, a secretary in the county
sheriff's department.
   On the Manhattan tour, which included a ferry ride to the Statue
of Liberty, a bewildered Ms. Nydegger asked ``What's that?'' when a
car alarm went off for no apparent reason.
   A few minutes later, she heard a man cursing loudly, also for no
obvious reason, as he walked on the other side of the street.
   ``Oh my,'' she said. ``They get kind of mad, don't they?''
   Her brother, Loren, 17, said he was ``asked for money twice in
one block.''
   ``I'm glad I grew up where I did,'' he said.
   In Bolan, there is an antique shop, a Methodist church and the
Bolan Store Inc., which owns three-fourths of the town's property
and sells farm equipment and supplies. The store is for sale.
   Each week, about 30 people attend church services.
   ``Practically all the women are in the choir,'' Ms. Nydegger
said. ``They have to be or we wouldn't have one. My brother rings
the bell, lights the candles and brings up the offering.''
   The 103-year-old community at one time had as many as 75
residents as well as a blacksmith, a train depot, lumber yards and
stockyards, a blacksmith shop and a creamery.
   But the automobile changed everything and Bolan's population has
remained relatively stable _ and small _ the last 20 years.
   There were only five residents until Chuck Yanacheak moved into
the community last October.
   ``The other 10 of us are in the suburbs,'' McCready said, which
isn't more than a block away.
   The Iowans rarely see motorists as they drive five miles through
corn and soybean country to Grafton, which has a post office, and
Mason City, which is 22 miles away and has a McDonald's restaurant.
It's a two-hour drive to Minneapolis and 2{ hours to Des Moines.
   McCready said he and his neighbors are enjoying the trip even
though they know some people are poking fun at them.
   ``We have to laugh at ourselves too,'' he said. ``Main street is
720 feet long and it ends in a dead end in a corn field.''
   But he added, ``When we see the mess and utter confusion of New
York City, I wouldn't sell my 88 acres for 88 acres in Manhattan,
unless I could sell it and move back to peace and quiet.''
</TEXT>
