<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0716 03-01 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley Hits Campaign Trail Hours after Primary Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf, `He predicted ..., to UPDATE
with Sawyer comment.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley, fresh from his Democratic
primary triumph over Mayor Eugene Sawyer, rallied his forces
Wednesday for a three-way general election battle against a black
alderman and a Republican nominee still to be crowned.
   Daley, son of the late, six-term political boss, Mayor Richard J.
Daley, drew overwhelming white support Tuesday and benefited from
low voter turnout, especially among blacks, to oust Sawyer, a black
former alderman.
   The victory made Chicago first among the biggest U.S. cities to
have a black incumbent mayor defeated by a white in an election.
   Daley, a three-term Cook County state's attorney, now faces a
third-party challenge in the April 4 general election from Timothy
Evans, a popular black alderman who has the support of Jesse
Jackson, and who also hit the campaign trail Wednesday.
   The outcome of the Republican primary, normally barely noticed in
this heavily Democratic city, remained in doubt Wednesday. Edward
Vrdolyak, a white former Democratic alderman and Daley foe who
launched a write-in candidacy only a week ago, claimed a victory
that if upheld could cut into Daley's core constituency.
   With five weeks of campaigning ahead, Daley was up at dawn to
greet commuters and tape a television appearance.
   ``I think my father's looking down upon me, on a beautiful, warm
day in Chicago ... very proud of me, and most importantly, proud of
the type of campaign that I ran in the last three months _ reaching
out to every community,'' Daley said on ``CBS This Morning.''
   At a commuter rail station, Daley pledged to avoid racial
divisiveness in the campaign's next phase: ``I'm going to be vying
for votes of everybody throughout this city and this is a city made
up of the black community, the white commmunity, the Asian, the
Hispanic community.''
   He predicted ``a good clean election.''
   Sawyer said his political career wasn't over but suggested he
would not back Daley or Evans. ``My general sense is that I will not
endorse anyone,'' he said. ``I am thinking it through and I've got a
lot of people to talk to before I decide.''
   With 2,843 of 2,911 precincts, or 98 percent, reporting, Daley
had 481,370 votes, or 56 percent, to 367,919 votes, or 43 percent,
for Sawyer. Three other candidates shared the remaining Democratic
votes, while the GOP race between Vrdolyak and Dr. Herbert Sohn was
considered too close to call Wednesday.
   Evans, 45, previously Sawyer's chief black rival, maintained a
low profile during the primary campaign. But he began campaigning
Wednesday at 6:45 a.m., shaking hands with voters at an elevated
train station and promising to crush the ``Daley machine.''
   Vrdolyak, 51, had no formal appearances scheduled Wednesday.
   The Chicago Board of Election Commissioners said Thursday's
official canvass would determine the Republican outcome.
   With 96 percent of 2,911 percincts reporting, unofficial results
gave Vrdolyak 10,711 votes, or 45 percent, to 10,234 votes, or 43
percent for Sohn. Two other candidates each had 5 percent.
   The elections board estimated that 64.5 percent of the city's
nearly 1.55 million voters went to the polls Tuesday.
   Daley's primary triumph gave him an advantage in the general
election, a contest Democrats have won without fail since 1931.
   In Washington, Democratic Party Chairman Ronald H. Brown
congratulated Daley and offered his full support to the party
nominee. In doing so, the first black chairman of a national
political party broke with Jackson, whom he had served as convention
manager last summer.
   ``Tough contests and hard-fought politics are nothing new to
Democrats and certainly not to Democrats in Chicago,'' Brown said in
a statement. ``The emphasis for all Democrats now must be on unity
and conciliation.''
   Daley proved his effectiveness as a political organizer, winning
broad-based support among white ethnics and Hispanics in the
primary. But he must work to gain support in the black community,
analysts said.
   If Vrdolyak, a slick campaigner and nemesis of the late Mayor
Harold Washington, is declared the winner over Sohn, observers said
the white vote in the general election could be split between
Vrdolyak and Daley, giving Evans the edge.
   Washington became the city's first black mayor after winning the
1983 Democratic primary, in which the younger Daley and incumbent
Jane Byrne split the white vote.
   Washington gained support from liberal whites and Hispanics to
repeat in 1987, becoming the first mayor since the elder Daley to
win re-election. But he died in office without having annointed a
successor, touching off a war between Sawyer and Evans that caused a
deep rift in the black community.
</TEXT>
