<FIRST>u i AM-Venezuela 4thLd-Writethru a0842 03-01 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0842,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Riots in Caracas; 200 Reported Killed in Caracas in Three Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with higher deaths, injury tolls, latest
government measures; no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAR3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riots broke out Wednesday in the
western slums despite martial law, and a newspaper said more than
200 people were killed in the Caracas area alone in three days of
violence over price increases.
   At least nine people were reported killed on Wednesday.
   The newspaper El Nacional said in its early Thursday edition that
more than 1,000 people were injured and 2,000 were arrested in
Caracas since riots _ triggered by a wide-ranging government
austerity program _ began on Monday.
   The newspaper listed the names of 159 persons whose bodies were
in the Caracas morgue, which it said was ``congested with corpses.''
It said there was a ``high number of corpses in other Caracas
morgues.''
   The independent newspaper quoted unidentified police sources and
gave no details.
   Government ministers maintained that calm had been largely
restored to Venezuela, but they censored international TV broadcasts
from Caracas.
   The army began to airlift food from the interior of the country
to supply Caracas residents running low on supplies as a result of
rioting and looting.
   Sporadic gunfire could be heard just blocks from the Associated
Press office as a 6 p.m. curfew fell over the city.
   Nicole Mendoza, a Caracas resident, said soldiers were piling
people into jeeps and taking them away outside her building to
enforce the curfew, which was announced Tuesday night.
   Fighting continued in Petare, a shantytown east of the capital,
and local hospitals were full of injured, a parish priest said.
Officials refused comment on numbers of dead or injured.
   A witness reported that an army unit shot mobs sacking a food
store in Petare after loudspeaker appeals failed to stop the
looting, a doctor who lives in Palo Verde, near Petare, told The
Associated Press.
   The doctor said four people were shot to death. There was no
independent confirmation.
   The government called on workers to return to their workplaces on
Thursday, saying violence was ``practically controlled.''
   Most businesses were closed on Wednesday. Before the curfew,
Venezuelans jammed the few remaining open food stores, which were
guarded by soldiers.
   Police battled with snipers in Nueva Tacagua, a shantytown in the
hills west of Caracas, and broke up mobs of looters in Catia, also a
slum to the west of Caracas, according to Radio Rumbo, a local
station.
   An AP photographer said he saw at least four bodies of people who
had been shot Wednesday in Catia.
   In the Chapellin neighborhood of Caracas, an elderly woman died
in her apartment from a wild bullet fired during gunbattles between
army units and residents of a nearby slum, said eyewitnesses.
   Radio reporters said delinquents were trying to break into homes
in Guarenas, about 30 miles west of Caracas, while homeowners were
defending themselves with gunfire.
   Interior Minister Alejandro Izaguirre acknowledged there had been
fighting in the capital but said ``calm has been restored to the
rest of the country.''
   President Carlos Andres Perez declared martial law late Tuesday,
saying the ``incredible tragedy'' of the violence threatened
Venezuela's ``consolidation of democracy.
   ``I blame the authorities, because we warned them we would need
protection way in advance,'' said Spanish-born businessmen Manuel
Taboada, whose four shoe stores were sacked by the looters. He
estimated his losses and damages at $2.6 million.
   Bus fare increases of 30 percent to 50 percent, and price gouging
by drivers were the immediate cause of the riots, but oil accounts
for 90 percent of Venezuela's export income and the economy never
recovered from the plunge in world prices several years ago.
   Inflation is expected to reach 70 percent this year, double the
1988 level, and the foreign debt is $33 billion.
   Perez, in office only four weeks, announced a sweeping reform
package under pressure from international creditors. It includes
freeing interest rates, doubling gasoline prices and letting the
currency float, which means higher prices for imports.
   Correspondents from Spanish and West German television said
state-owned television and telephone companies refused to transmit
images of the violence overseas. A government spokesman, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said there had been restrictions imposed
because televised reports of the disturbances were ``too crude.''
   It was unclear whether the censorship was connected to the
imposition of martial law, which prohibits public gatherings,
suspends the right to privacy and freedom of the press and permits
detention without charge.
   Perez said industrialists and the Venezuelan Confederation of
Labor, the most powerful labor group, agreed to an across-the-board
raise of 2,000 bolivars a month, or about $52. That would mean a
raise of more than 50 percent for people on the minimum wage.
</TEXT>
