<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Copperfield ADV02   03-01 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Copperfield, ADV 02,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday PMs, March 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>David Copperfield Defends Illusion of Collapsing Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2 of Feb. 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A building falls on magician David Copperfield
during his latest special, but who's worried?
   The building collapse is the highlight of ``The Magic of David
Copperfield XI: The Explosive Encounter,'' a special airing on CBS
Friday.
   Copperfield is handcuffed and sealed inside a safe on the fourth
floor of the White House Hotel in Charlotte, N.C. The 13-story
landmark, built in 1924, is to be demolished by means of
strategically placed explosives and wire cables that will cause it
to collapse inward.
   As a Mozart melody plays, the crew shuts Copperfield in the safe,
sets the explosive timer and runs out of the building. The building
collapses and moments later Copperfield appears from beneath a
blanket on a steel plate.
   Magic or camera trickery?
   Copperfield was asked about suggestions that his spectacular TV
feats, such as making the Statue of Liberty or a jet airplane
disappear, are not true illusions but use camera tricks.
   ``That's not true,'' said Copperfield as he watched a tape of the
building collapse on a monitor in an editing room. He had just
arrived a few minutes before from Nashville, where he had been
performing on stage.
   ``I think a lot of magicians are jealous. When I hear that, it's
a compliment. People ask me to, say, cure a headache. I say I'm only
an illusionist. I always work in front of an audience. There were
40,000 people watching when the building came down. It was all done
in one unedited camera shot.
   ``Besides, the network is very strict. They would never permit me
to take advantage of the audience. There are people who are funnier
than me, people who are better looking. If you could do it with a
camera, they could use anybody.''
   It is the 11th special Copperfield has done for CBS. It features
such new illusions as dancing ties and an origami box. His guest is
Emma Samms of ABC's ``Dynasty,'' who participates in a levitation
illusion.
   ``I combine magic with a story and romantic music,'' he said.
``We use a lot of contemporary rock 'n' roll, from the Pet Shop Boys
to Peter Gabriel to Sting. ...
   ``It's very important for me to keep my magic current. It's an
art form that keeps growing. If more of us were doing it you'd see
more transition in magic. Since I'm one of the few who gets exposure
I feel a responsibility to guide magic into new areas.''
   As he talked the monitor in the screening room showed his various
illusions.
   He borrowed a necktie from a man in the audience and made it
dance and drink milk through a straw while Harry Belafonte sang
``Angelina.''
   The illusion using origami, the Japanese art of folding paper
into figures, begins with a small box penetrated by three swords.
Copperfield pulls out the swords and unfolds the box until it
becomes a large box. A woman then steps into it. Copperfield folds
it until it is small again. He then re-inserts the swords. Finally,
he opens the box again, and when the woman emerges she is wearing
different clothing.
   ``Emma Samms and anyone who appears on my show must sign a
secrecy agreement,'' Copperfield said. ``Even when I build the
equipment for my illusions, I give sections of it to different
builders. Members of my crew have different tasks. I do have
illusion designers, but I work out most of my own illusions. They
may suggest a different way to do it.''
   Copperfield said he also has a project in which magic is used as
therapy in hospitals around the world. ``We teach magic to patients
to help them regain dexterity,'' he said.
   ``For me for a long time magic was just a job. I was in China for
the illusion of walking through the Great Wall. Someone said, `Look,
you're doing what you want to do and here you are in China.' I
slapped myself on the face and I've been enjoying magic ever since.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   JOINS ``DYNASTY'' _ Tracy Scoggins joins ABC's ``Dynasty'' as
Monica Colby, the role she created for ``The Colbys'' several years
ago. She plays the daughter of Sable Colby (Stephanie Beacham). .. .
   ANOTHER MILESTONE _ ``The New Leave It to Beaver'' on
SuperStation TBS celebrates its 100th episode with a special story
about Wally Cleaver and Eddie Haskell. It's the only television show
in history to complete 100 episodes in its original incarnation, as
``Leave It to Beaver,'' and 100 more in its reborn form, with the
original cast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, March 2</NOTE>
