<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv05   03-01 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 05,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Federal Farm Policy Needs Steady Hand at Wheel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter makes it
plain that he intends running a tight ship through the stormy seas
where trade barriers, drought, poverty and foreclosure lurk as
monsters of the deep.
   But Yeutter also says he is not ready to keelhaul farmers and the
rest of rural America at the first sign of a budget knife. Some
things are done simply because it's right to do so, within limits.
   ``We still have to have compassion for folks who get into
economic difficulties in agriculture, often through no fault of
their own _ weather conditions, for example, like last year's
drought,'' he says. ``And we will probably want to continue special
privileges to help out young farmers so that they can gain entry in
this business.''
   Yeutter had been asked to respond Feb. 24 at his first news
conference at the Agriculture Department since joining President
Bush's Cabinet.
   The question was whether he agreed with a report by the National
Agricultural Finance Commission, which recommended, among other
things, that cuts be made in federal subsidies for agricultural
credit.
   Farming, the commission said, is a business and not a ``way of
life'' that should include government props for those who can't make
it on their own.
   ``I agree with the basic conclusion ... that farming is a
business that ought to be handled in a business-like way by
everyone, including the federal government, and that we ought not to
be running long-term welfare-like programs in agriculture,'' Yeutter
said.
   ``At the same time, however, we have to recognize that we can
achieve that laudable objective only in a gradual way,'' he added,
``and only through cooperation of our trading partners.''
   Thus, Yeutter shifted into the mode that he knows intimately
after 3{ years as President Reagan's trade representative. He led
the U.S. charge against foreign barriers to free trade and still is
a key player in the on-going Uruguay Round of negotiations under the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   For many years, since a wheat-hungry Soviet Union blew the lid
off U.S. grain exports in the early 1970s, many economists,
commodity groups, farmers and politicians have held doggedly to the
idea that foreign markets offer the potential for prying American
agriculture out of its old ruts and dependence on federal programs.
   One of the reason for federal subsidies is ``because our farmers
and our marketers have to compete with subsidized products elsewhere
in the world,'' Yeutter said.
   If other countries agree to reduce their levels of subsidization,
the United States can do likewise and eventually ``trade distorting
subsidies'' can be eliminated.
   ``I put particular emphasis on the term `trade distorting'
because lots of people here and abroad have misquoted me as seeking
to eliminate all agricultural subsidies, and I never said that,''
Yeutter said.
   ``We can continue to provide income support to farmers as we deem
appropriate, and I suspect that we will be doing so for a long
period of time, simply because farming is a volatile business and it
is going to be very difficult to reach a utopian situation where no
assistance of any kind from the government level is required for
American agriculture,'' he said.
   After his confirmation hearing on Feb. 2, Yeutter provided the
Senate Agriculture Committee with 147 pages of answers to questions
that he and the panel didn't have time to cover during the formal
proceeding. Those will be hauled out regularly as debate unfolds in
Congress on various farm programs and proposed legislation.
   For example, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, asked Yeutter about the
future of agriculture and where full-time commercial family farms
are heading.
   Yeutter replied that ``the economic structure of agriculture is
likely to continue evolving much as it has in the past'' with fewer
and larger farm units. Harkin then asked about the federal role.
   ``Federal policies should provide assistance and support to the
farm sector in a structurally neutral manner,'' Yeutter said. ``In
other words, agricultural policies should be evaluated based upon
their benefits and costs to the nation, but their implementation
should not be slanted to favor one economic structure over another.''
   Yeutter added: ``Attempting to freeze a particular structure in
place would inevitably reduce the efficiency of the sector over
time. The European Economic Community experience in agriculture is a
classic example of this.''
   The indications now show that ``a family farm structure will
continue to dominate American agriculture, and I see no reason to
tilt farm policies away from that,'' he said.
   Harkin also asked about USDA policies to help young and beginning
farmers, and whether small and medium-sized farmers should be helped
to start and stay in business.
   Yeutter said policies ``should assure there are no artificial
barriers'' to prevent entry to farming but care should be observed.
   ``Helping these folks to start farming is one thing,'' Yeutter
said. ``Helping them to stay, no matter what kind of managers they
are, is another. The latter can be enormously costly to American
taxpayers. Successful farmers are not enthusiastic about paying more
taxes in order to assist unsuccessful farmers to hang on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
