<FIRST>s e BC-WeekendTV-Whitfield Adv17-19   03-01 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Whitfield, Adv 17-19,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17-19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 17-19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lynn Whitfield Stars in ABC Miniseries `The Women of Brewster Place'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Jackee and Mary Alice are full names in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lynn Whitfield's role as a successful doctor
helps create the positive black family image in ABC's ``HeartBeat,''
and yet she's eager to range from the mainstream to do controversial
material.
   She's one of the stars of the ABC miniseries ``The Women of
Brewster Place,'' the story of a group of poor black women, which
presents an unabashedly feminist view of the troubles they have with
the men in their lives.
   The four-hour miniseries, which airs Sunday and Monday, is based
on a novel by Gloria Naylor and also stars Oprah Winfrey, Olivia
Cole, Robin Givens, Jackee, Paula Kelly, Lonette McKee, Phyllis
Yvonne Stickney, Cicely Tyson, Mary Alice, Moses Gunn, Douglas
Turner Ward and Paul Winfield.
   Winfrey, as Mattie Michael, is the central character, but the
story of each woman is told. The film is interesting and well-made.
But it is anti-male, and black men in particular take their lumps.
With few exceptions, the men are ne'er-do-wells who shirk
responsibility and desert their women.
   Mattie is an unwed mother whose teen-age son betrays her and
causes her to lose her home. Ceil (Whitfield) is abandoned by her
husband after their child dies in an accident. Kelly and McKee play
lesbians, and when McKee's character is raped by a street punk she
takes out her rage on the nearest man, the kind-hearted building
superintendent who befriended her.
   ``I'm an actress who occasionally does material written by
feminist black writers who give their impressions of black men,''
Whitfield. ``When I did `for colored girls who have considered
suicide@when the rainbow is enuf,' I was attacked outside the
theater. ...
   ``It's a writer's prerogative to write it as she sees it. But I
know for myself, I'm ready to reinforce other ideas about the
family. I think it's a tragic flaw in black literature and drama
that so much responsibility is put upon the artist to present images
that are positive. It's unfair to dump all the responsibility onto
the artist.
   ``On the other hand,'' she said. ``It's not fair that there
aren't enough projects being done that cover a wide span of black
life. So any one project done takes on so much responsibility to
present good images of our race.''
   She said now that she has begun writing she ``can assume
responsibility for what I present.''
   She has written a treatment for a romantic mystery movie, called
``Passant Blanc,'' set in New Orleans in 1929, and a presentation
for a situation comedy.
   Whitfield's role on ``HeartBeat'' as Dr. Cory Banks would seem to
come naturally. She is the granddaughter of a doctor and the
daughter of a dentist. She grew up in Baton Rouge, La., where the
Leo S. Butler Community Center is named after her grandfather.
   ``I feel so good when I play this doctor representing my family
profession,'' she said.
   She recently helped select actor Robert Gossett, a cousin of
Louis Gossett Jr., to play her husband in the series.
   ``I'm very proud of what we're doing,'' she said. ``We're not
presenting a couple that is totally perfect. We deal with our
sexuality and our inner conflicts. We don't make comment about what
it's like to be black in America. I am a black person. Being there
is enough. I think we need to look forward and enforce the concept
that we are equal.
   ``America is a competitive society. You elbow your way through.
As a black artist I can't think of a better time to be around.''
   Ceil is not that different from Cory, Whitfield says, even though
the only obvious similarities between the two would seem to be that
each has a husband and child.
   ``Ceil is a woman who has the same desires (as Cory), but without
the education or the finances to manage it,'' Whitfield says. ``She
just wasn't programmed to move up in the system. Lucillia (Ceil)
Turner is a classic case of coming from a broken home. She was
raised by her grandmother.
   ``The most important thing for her was what she never had, the
solidity of a real home. She was married to a man who had no viable
trade or profession and wasn't equipped to make a good living. She
herself was not prepared to earn a living. It's a classic case of
our social-political system and how it works.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 17-19</NOTE>
