<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth crawled at a 2 percent annual
rate in the final three months of 1988, the slowest in two years,
reflecting a worsening trade deficit and lingering effects of the
summer drought, the government said.
   The Commerce Department report released Tuesday said the slowdown
in the gross national product, the total output of goods and
services, was accompanied by a pickup in the inflation rate. Private
economists said they were disturbed by the new GNP statistics.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes fell 7.4 percent in
January, the biggest decline in two years, reflecting a return to
normal buying patterns following a December sales spurt, a real
estate trade group reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said Tuesday existing
single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.63 million units in January following a 5.7 percent rise in
December to a rate of 3.92 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has scrapped its
Premier brand ``smokeless'' cigarette after five months of market
testing, concluding that consumers didn't like the product's smell
or taste.
   The company's move announced Tuesday followed widespread
criticism of the cigarette by major health organizations. It also
marked the first significant product shift since the parent RJR
Nabisco Inc. was acquired by a private investment firm earlier this
year for a record $24.53 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. wants banks
and savings and loan associations to get its approval before seeking
so-called brokered deposits, blamed as a major cause of the S&amp;L
crisis.
   Regulations will be proposed soon requiring institutions seeking
to expand their loan portfolios through the use of the high-interest
deposits to notify the FDIC in advance, the regulatory body's
chairman William Seidman told the Senate Banking Committee on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
