<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MarketTechnolgy Bjt   03-01 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market Technolgy, Bjt,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Threatens U.S. Lead In Markets, Merc Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan threatens U.S. dominance in finance just
as it has in cars and computer chips, the president of the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange says.
   The threat of competition from Japan was the driving force behind
the Merc's decision to institute 24-hour, worldwide electronic
trading through its Globex system, Merc President William Brodsky
said at a conference Tuesday.
   ``The Japanese are something that no one ignores in the world of
industry or finance,'' he said in an interview.
   The Japanese, who once scorned innovative U.S.-invented
securities products such as stock-index futures, have begun
electronic trading in Tokyo and Osaka of stock and yen bond futures
and soon will begin trading yen currency futures in competition with
Chicago.
   The desire to keep business executed through Chicago was behind
the Merc's development of Globex in conjunction with Reuters
Holdings PLC. The system, in which investments are traded on a
computer screen, is scheduled to begin in October.
   An Australian exchange and the New York Mercantile Exchange,
which handles oil futures, have said they also will list contracts
on Globex.
   ``Innovation of this type is essential if the U.S. is to maintain
its leading competitive edge and remain a leading provider of
financial services to the world community,'' Wendy Gramm, chairwoman
of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, said when the federal
agency approved Globex on Feb. 2.
   David Ruder, the chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, has called Globex ``the wave of the future.''
   The race to round-the-clock trading, faster computers and
instantaneous global communication poses a challenge to regulators
such as the CFTC as well as to an older generation of traders.
   One eventual victim of modernization could be the local traders
on the floor of the Chicago Merc and the Chicago Board of Trade,
some of whom are being investigated for allegedly cheating their
customers.
   Some outsiders have predicted that Globex will undermine the
Merc's chaotic but time-honored ``open outcry'' trading system.
   Brodsky denied that Tuesday, saying face-to-face trading in the
pits has advantages over faceless electronic trading, which will be
prohibited during the Merc's regular hours.
   ``Why are we here today in a room when we could all be on speaker
phones in our offices?'' he asked at the conference.
   Brodsky's comments came on the second and final day of a
conference on technology and the financial markets sponsored by the
Annenberg Washington Program and Northwestern University's Kellogg
Graduate School of Management.
   In another session, Harvard University economist Lawrence H.
Summers spelled out a proposal for a tax on stock trading to
discourage socially wasteful market speculation.
   A half-percent tax could raise $10 billion a year without doing
any damage to the stock market's basic functions, said Summers, who
was the chief economic adviser to Michael Dukakis, the losing
Democratic presidential candidate.
   Summers was disputed by Louis I. Margolis, a managing director of
Salomon Brothers Inc., and by Sanford Grossman, a Princeton
University economist.
   Grossman said it was unfair to single out the securities industry
for a tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
