<DOCNO> AP890301-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Smokeless-Reax Bjt   03-01 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smokeless-Reax, Bjt,0745</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Smokeless Cigarette Flawed, But Won't End Innovations, Analysts
Say</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier, RJR Nabicso Inc.'s ``smokeless''
cigarette, was dead on arrival because of its unpleasant taste,
industry analysts said. But they predicted the failure won't
forestall other cigarette innovations designed to counter complaints
about smoke.
   ``Everyone I know who tried it thought it was really horrible,''
said Pavlos M. Alexandrakis, who follows tobacco companies for Argus
Research Corp. in New York.
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., RJR Nabisco's cigarette subsidiary,
announced Tuesday that it was withdrawing Premier from the market
after five months of testing in two states.
   ``While smokers are very interested in the concept, the current
product has not achieved adequate consumer acceptance,'' the company
said in a statement from its Winston-Salem, N.C., headquarters.
   ``This is no surprise,'' said industry analyst Emanuel Goldman.
``It was brought out stillborn.''
   Goldman, who works for PaineWebber Inc., said Premier suffered
from two fatal problems: unacceptable taste and aroma.
   ``What the company was saying was consumers will get used to it,
they'll give it an extra try,'' he said. ``That's inconsistent with
the fact that we are a nation of channel-hoppers, and if you don't
like it the first time, you're not going to try it a second time.''
   Smokers also found Premier hard to keep lit, and weren't sure
what to do with the cigarettes when they were finished since
Premiers don't burn down like ordinary butts, said analyst Lawrence
Adelman of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``I thought the project initially was revolutionary in concept,''
he said. ``I think RJR Nabisco was very bold. But the technology
wasn't there yet to satisfy consumer requirements.''
   Premier differed from ordinary cigarettes in that it didn't
actually burn tobacco. Instead, smokers lit a carbon heat source at
the tip. During inhalation, hot air passed passed over an
aluminum-encased flavor capsule and dried tobacco.
   Despite its innovations, Premier didn't eliminate health
concerns. Several health organizations, including the American
Medical Association, last year asked the U.S. Food and Drug
Admininstration to ban sales of the cigarette.
   Several analysts speculated that the timing of Premier's demise
was due to the buyout of RJR Nabisco earlier in February by Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. The New York investment firm needs to cut costs
at RJR to pay off the debt it took on in the record $24.53 billion
takeover.
   But others said Premier was doomed no matter what.
   ``I think the consumer reaction was so negative that it pretty
much was a foregone conclusion,'' Adelman said.
   KKR did not make the decision to drop Premier, said Betsy Annese,
an RJR Tobacco spokeswoman. It was a decision by the tobacco
company's management, she said, ``and they just agreed with us.''
   Adelman said RJR spent about $200 million developing Premier, and
an additional $125 million to launch the product in the test
markets. RJR had said it expected it would cost $1 billion to roll
out Premier nationwide.
   Reynolds said it had no plans to reintroduce Premier or a similar
product ``unless we have fully addressed the issues raised in the
test markets.''
   Ms. Annese said research on Premier led to much spinoff
technology, including some aspects of two brands recently put in
test markets, Vantage Excel and Chelsea.
   Vantage Excel has a new tobacco blend and special, high-porosity
paper that give off less lit-end smoke than ordinary cigarettes.
Chelsea has a distinctive aroma that is being marketed as being less
objectionable to non-smokers.
   ``We have learned an awful lot that will be helpful,'' Ms. Annese
said. ``We do not consider this to be a failure.''
   Analysts said RJR and other tobacco companies have other projects
in the works to reduce the smoke cigarettes emit _ the primary cause
of smoking restrictions and complaints from non-smokers.
   Adelman said some companies are looking at a change in the way
tobacco is packed into cigarette casings. Goldman said the biggest
innovation may come from biotechnology, which may provide new
strains of tobacco lacking many of its undesirable characteristics.
   ``The 1990s are likely to be a period of technological
breakthroughs (in cigarettes), providing you don't have an
advertising ban,'' Goldman said. He said a ban on cigarettes
advertising would prevent companies from successfully launching new
products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
