<FIRST>r f PM-GayConsumers Bjt   03-01 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gay Consumers, Bjt,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Gay Men Are `Dream' Consumers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Madison Avenue ad agencies long have ignored
the gay community in their marketing plans, but a new nationwide
study portrays homosexuals as dream consumers.
   The report by Simmons Market Research Bureau of New York,
commissioned by a marketing firm that represents 125 gay
publications, found gay men in general have higher than average
incomes, higher education levels, fewer dependents and a large
amount of discretionary income that can be spent on luxury goods.
   ``The survey basically validates what we've known all along, and
puts quantitative figures on it,'' said Joseph Di Sabato, president
of New York-based Rivendell Marketing Co., which paid for the
survey. ``The gay market is economically a dream market.''
   The report questioned 4,000 readers, mostly male, of gay
newspapers in eight of the nation's top urban markets. It asked them
about their lifestyle and spending habits, including buying patterns
in travel, liquor, electronic equipment and apparel.
   Di Sabato, who says marketing companies have largely ignored the
possibility of targeting gay consumers, said Monday he plans to use
the survey's findings to urge national advertisers to place their
messages in more gay publications.
   The Simmons survey, completed in October and released this week
by Rivedell, found gay men had an average annual income of $36,800,
more than triple the national average of $12,287 as reported in
March 1988 Census figures.
   It also found the annual income of a gay household was $55,400,
compared with a national average of $36,500.
   Sixty percent of gay men are college graduates, compared with the
average of 18 percent for consumers in general. About 35 percent of
homosexuals also have some type of post-graduate education.
   Forty-nine percent of gay men hold ``professional or managerial''
posts, compared with about 16 percent of the population at large.
   While gay men are 50 percent less likely than the population at
large to own their primary residence, they are twice as likely to
own vacation homes.
   Gay men also are twice as likely to travel than those in the
general consumer market, and seven times more likely to go to Europe
than the rest of the U.S. population.
   Di Sabato said the buying habits of lesbians are not as easy to
calculate because of the relatively few major publications expressly
addressed to them.
   ``We have been selling the legend of (gay) high income, high
education, the low number of dependents, and the large amount of
discretionary and disposable income spent on high-ticket items _
like travel and imported alcohol,'' Di Sabato said. ``But other than
the legend, there was very little to back it up.''
   Di Sibato said the few national companies that have tried
targeting gay consumers have been rewarded.
   ``Remy Martin (cognac) has done ad campaigns (in the gay press)
six weeks prior to Christmas, and in June, prior to Gay Pride Week
(nationwide), and it has paid off for them,'' Di Sibato said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
