<DOCNO> AP890301-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Zenith-AT&amp;T     03-01 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zenith-AT&amp;T,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith, AT&amp;T Partners On HDTV Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partnership between Zenith Electronics
Corp. and the American Telephone and Telegraph Co. could give the
United States an edge in the global race to dominate the
high-definition television market, Zenith's chairman says.
   Zenith and AT&amp;T announced Tuesday they were joining forces on a
$24 million effort to develop a processor-receiver and other
hardware needed to bring high-definition TV, which produces clearer,
brighter pictures, to the mass market.
   Separately, Zenith announced a $21.5 million program to develop
picture tubes for high-definition TV sets.
   Pearlman said the successful completion of the two projects would
yield ``real winning American technology ... that will allow the
U.S. to leapfrog the Japanese and Europeans'' in the mass-market
development of high-definition TV.
   Zenith, based in this Chicago suburb, and New York-based AT&amp;T
said they would spend $11 million and were seeking a $13 million
federal grant from the government to finance the
research-and-development project. They said it was the first time
two U.S. companies have combined on a major high-definition TV
research project.
   Last month, 16 U.S. electronics companies said they were
considering banding together to compete in the high-definition TV
market, but they have not yet announced such an agreement.
   The Pentagon has indicated it wants to help finance the
development of high-definition television because of its potential
military applications, and is seeking grant proposals.
   By combining AT&amp;T's integrated-circuit technology with Zenith's
television expertise, the companies hope to develop equipment for
evaluating and demonstrating Zenith's prototype high-definition TV
transmission system.
   The U.S. high-definition television transmission standard
prescribes 1,125 horizontal lines per screen, more than twice as
many as the 525 lines per screen on today's televisions, permitting
superior pictures.
   Zenith also announced a $21.5 million program to develop
large-screen versions of its ``flat tension mask'' high-resolution
picture tubes for military and consumer high-definition TV displays.
   Taylor said the company has used the tubes, which currently
measure 14 inches diagonally, in its computers for the last two
years.
   Zenith, the only major U.S.-owned producer of television sets and
picture tubes, said it was seeking $10 million from the government
to complement its $11.5 million commitment to the picture-tube
research program.
   Industry analyst James Magid of Needham &amp; Co. in New York, called
the Zenith-AT&amp;T partnership ``fantastic.''
   ``They should have a lot more partners than that,'' Magid said.
``This is a very big and important project.''
   Zenith spokesman John Taylor said the Zenith-AT&amp;T arrangement
``certainly wouldn't preclude us from teaming with others.''
   The market for high-definition television, including production
equipment and receivers, is expected to reach tens of billions of
dollars a year by the early years of the 21st century.
</TEXT>
