<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against nearly all major currencies
in moderate European trading early today. Gold prices were slightly
lower.
   Dealers said market participants sold British pounds for dollars
in Asian markets before today's release of British trade figures for
January.
   The pound fell to a three-week low against the dollar on market
expectations that the British trade deficit will widen to $3.2
billion from $2.9 billion in December.
   The pound fell in London to $1.7350 from $1.7430 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.53 Japanese yen to a closing 127.68 yen. Later, in
London, it edged up further to 127.80 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8360 West German marks, up from 1.8230; 1.5685
Swiss francs, up from 1.5535; 6.2485 French francs, up from 6.1975;
2.0730 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0555; 1,351.95 Italian lire, up
from 1,341.50; 1.1975 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2005.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $386.50 a troy ounce,
down from $386.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $386.10.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $386.10, down from $387.15 bid
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 59 cents to close at a bid
$388.26.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.84 a troy
ounce from $5.86 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
