<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-01 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly, Shares Down For Third Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar today firmed against the Japanese
yen, while share prices declined for the third consecutive day.
   The dollar, following a 1.15-yen surge Tuesday, gained another
0.53 yen and closed at 127.68 yen. It opened at 126.97 yen, the
day's low, and rose to 127.81 yen at one point.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 300.17-point
loser Tuesday, shed another 21.30 points, or 0.067 percent, closing
at 31,964.30.
   The average has lost a total of 488.19 points, or 1.51 percent,
this week after closing at a record high for the second consecutive
day last Thursday. Friday was a public holiday for Emperor
Hirohito's funeral.
   Stock traders said buying incentives were strong at the start of
today's trading following Tuesday's plunge in Tokyo and an
8.03-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York.
   But investors began selling to take profits after prices rose
across the board in the morning session, and the Nikkei went back
down, they said.
   ``There was a widely shared feeling in the market that most
shares are overpriced and they had to fall sooner or later,'' said
one dealer at a major securities company. ``So investors are anxious
to take profits when share prices gain and sell when they decline.''
   Currency dealers said the dollar was strong because of increased
demand at the start of the new month.
   The manager of a commercial bank said the dollar was oversold in
New York overnight after the second revision of the U.S. fourth
quarter gross national product growth figures.
   ``The dollar was oversold, and people are buying it back,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
