<DOCNO> AP890301-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     03-01 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Trade Deficit Widens Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened to 2.09
billion pounds, or $3.63 billion, in January from a revised deficit
of 1.76 billion pounds in December, the government said Wednesday.
   January's trade gap compared with a deficit of 1.45 billion
pounds in January 1988, the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   The financial markets had been expecting a deficit of about 1.85
million pounds and the Treasury moved quickly to say they
``shouldn't put too much emphasis'' on the figures.
   Monthly trade figures can be ``very erratic'' and ``among the
last indicators to respond to a tightening of monetary policy,''
said a Treasury spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with
British custom.
   The pound fell slightly on the news, from $1.7350 to $1.7300.
   Bryan Gould, trade spokesman for the opposition Labor Party, said
the figures show ``Britain is now an economy which cannot pay its
way and which is falling further and further behind in the
competitive race.''
   The figures showed exports totaled a record 7.37 billion pounds
in January, up from 6.9 billion pounds in December and up from 6.4
billion pounds in January 1988.
   Imports totalled a record 9.47 billion pounds in January, up from
8.66 billion pounds in December and up from 7.8 billion pounds in
January 1988.
   The December merchandise trade deficit was previously reported as
1.66 billion pounds. The government said the upward revision in the
December figures was due mainly to a revision in the seasonal
adjustments for 1988.
   With January's trade in invisible items, which covers services,
overseas investment earnings and official transfer payments,
estimated to be in surplus by 400 million pounds Britain's current
account showed a deficit of 1.69 billion pounds, compared with a
revised deficit of 1.36 billion pounds in December.
</TEXT>
