<HEAD>London Shares Firmer As Market Overlooks Trade Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were stronger around midday Wednesday,
as the market largely shrugged off government figures showing a
sharp widening in Britain's merchandise trade deficit.
   Share prices fell back momentarily after the release of the
January trade figures, but market makers notched prices higher amid
widespread relief that the figures would not lead to a further rise
in interest rates.
   The trade figures ``were dismal but hardly disasterous,'' one
dealer said.
   The trade deficit widened to 2.09 billion pounds, or $3.63
billion, from a revised deficit of 1.76 billion pounds in December,
the government said.
   By 12:30 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was 24.4 points, or 1.2 percent, higher at 2,026.8 points, little
changed from 2,025.0 just before the trade figures were released.
   The market reached its intraday high of 2,027.4 around midmorning
and then fell to its low point of 2,014.3 minutes after the results
of the data were known.
   Share turnover reached a moderately healthy 341.6 million shares.
