<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AgingAirliners 1stLd-Writethtru f0022 03-01 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Airliners, 1st Ld-Writethtru, f0022,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Agree To $800 Million Plan, FAA Moving To Impose Rules</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs of new quotes; picks up at 7th graf pvs,
Investigators into</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new plan to require $800 million in work on
aging airliners will provide an extra margin of safety, even though
the planes already are ``perfectly safe,'' an airline trade
association official said today.
   Officials of United, Delta and American airlines who worked on an
aging-aircraft task force joined Tuesday in endorsing the group's
far-reaching recommendations to increase the safety of older Boeing
airliners.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner says steps are being
taken to write the proposal into law.
   ``Collectively we decided that it was far better to be
pre-emptive in our maintenance activity rather than to wait for
problems to develop,'' Clyde Kizer, vice president of the Air
Transport Association, an airline trade group, said today on ABC's
``Good Morning America.''
   The task force, which also included other U.S. and foreign
industry and government safety experts, called for $600,000 in
modifications and replacements on each of more than 1,300 older
Boeing 747s, 737s and 727s.
   ``The aircraft that are out there right now are perfectly safe
and the activities that the airlines are taking in regards to the
maintenance were satisfactory,'' Kizer said. ``This supplies an
extra protection margin.''
   Bob Doll, United Airlines vice president for technical services,
said the proposals conform with steps the airline is already taking
to keep its older airliners in shape.
   ``We don't anticipate anything over and above what we've already
planned to do,'' said Doll.
   Kizer said the proposals had nothing to do with damage to
United's oldest 747 on a flight from Honolulu to Auckland, New
Zealand, last Friday.
   Investigators into the incident in which nine passengers were
hurled to their deaths over the Pacific Ocean say they have found no
signs of metal fatigue or corrosion associated with aging. Instead,
they have focused on possible mechanical problems with the cargo
door that ripped off along with a portion of the airliner's skin.
   Julian May, Delta vice president, said none of his airline's
fleet of 130 model 727s would be affected by the proposals right
away.
   ``It will be several years before we are affected because of
fleet age,'' he said.
   Pan Am's top executive, Thomas G. Plaskett, also endorsed the
proposal, saying that unless older airliners are restored and kept
operating, there may not be enough planes to serve the growing
worldwide travel demand.
   No airliners would be scrapped under the proposal which asks the
Federal Aviation Administration to order the work that would include
replacement of parts subject to wear rather than repeated
inspections and repairs only when they wear out.
   An official of Boeing Commercial Aircraft Co., which manufactured
the affected airliners, said the older jetliners covered by the plan
are safe and should last indefinitely if the recommended work is
done.
   ``We believe that the aircraft out there flying are safe,'' said
Ben Cosgrove, Boeing engineering vice president who sits on the task
force. But he said the work was needed to reduce the number of
regular inspections needed for older aircraft.
   The recommendations are based on 150 service bulletins issued by
Boeing, which is now to write them into a single massive bulletin
for presentation to the FAA.
   Skinner praised the task force's work as the first product of a
cooperative international government and industry effort to deal
with the problem of the world's aging airliner fleet.
   The average age of the 8,800 airliners in use around the world is
just over 13 years, and aviation experts predict that will increase
each year for several years as new airliner construction is
backlogged and few old aircraft are junked.
   Skinner said the FAA has already begun ``the internal rule-making
procedures'' needed to make the recommended work mandatory for all
U.S. airlines.
   In all, more than 1,300 airliners worldwide would be affected by
the plan, about one-third of them operated by U.S. carriers. The
recommendations would also be given to foreign airlines and
regulatory bodies, some of whom participated on the task force.
   The proposed repairs and replacements would be tied to the number
of times an airliner had taken off and landed and its time in the
sky.
   Service records of older McDonnell Douglas DC-10s, DC-9s and
DC-8s and aircraft build overseas are also being studied by task
force committees. They are due to make recommendations later this
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Iceland-Beer     03-01 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iceland-Beer,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beer Flows Freely Again After 74 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASGEIR SVERRISSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beer flowed freely in Iceland for the
first time in 74 years today as the last vestiges of prohibition
came to an end.
   Lines formed outside some of the nation's 17 state liquor stores.
Waiting patrons applauded when the Snorra Braut liquor store in
central Reykjavik opened for business at 9 a.m.
   Icelanders voted for prohibition in a 1908 referendum. The law
didn't take effect until 1915, when it was assumed the last
alcoholic beverage on the island had been drunk.
   The ban was repealed in 1933, but through a legal quirk beer with
alcoholic content above 2.25 percent remained under prohibition. A
powerful temperance lobby kept it that way until May when Parliament
voted 13-8 to lift the ban effective March 1.
   ``This is a truly historic moment in my life and the life of this
nation,'' said Pall Sverrisson, a cab driver. ``This is what we have
been fighting for, and this is what we have been dreaming of for so
long.''
   Many restaurants and bars reported their tables had been booked
weeks in advance by customers planning to celebrate.
   The luxury doesn't come cheap.
   With the government levying a hefty tax, liquor stores are
charging up to $57.60 for a 24-can case of imported beer. A glass of
beer in a bar costs $3.90 to $4.80.
   Education Minister Svavar Gestsson, who campaigned against
lifting the ban, accused the media of hyping the occasion and said
efforts to educate people on the dangers of drink ``have proved in
vain against this terrible flood.''
   Reykjavik Police Chief Boedvar Bragason said his force was on
heightened alert for drunken drivers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 0951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Drexel-Milken 1stLd-Writethru f0023 03-01 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Milken, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Dispute Milken Corercion Charges; Trader Seeks Judge Disqualification</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to clarify coercion issue; PICKS UP 3rd graf
pvs, `Milken alleged...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. voluntarily agreed to
terminate Michael Milken and withhold his 1988 pay of more than $100
million, despite claims by the prominent bond trader that Drexel was
coerced into the provisions, the government said.
   In court papers filed Tuesday, federal prosecutors rejected a
motion by Milken to have Drexel's firm's landmark securities fraud
settlement with the Justice Department thrown out or modified
because it violates Milken's rights.
   The coercion issue is at the heart of the first legal challenge
to the settlement. Milken claims that Drexel was forced to resolve
the case or face racketeering charges that included freezing the
investment firm's multibillion-dollar assets.
   Milken alleged that the government forced Drexel to have him
dismissed and his 1988 compensation, most of it in a bonus that
would far surpass $100 million, withheld.
   Acting U.S. Attorney Benito Romano called the charge of coercion
``nothing short of absurd.''
   ``To argue that Drexel, a highly sophisticated investment banking
firm, represented by numerous highly qualified attorneys, was
incapable of making a voluntary choice in this matter strains
credulity,'' Romano wrote.
   In an accompanying affidavit, Drexel Chief Executive Officer
Frederick H. Joseph said the investment firm entered into the plea
agreement with the Justice Department ``voluntarily and without
coercion after consulting with counsel.''
   The statement _ while technically accurate since Drexel endorsed
the total pact _ appeared to be at odds with earlier statements by
the company that it disputed portions of the agreement and fought to
have provisions on Milken withdrawn.
   Joseph also was quoted in earlier court papers as saying the
Milken provisions were ``unfair'' and ``horrendous'' and were
inserted at the government's insistence.
   Drexel in December agreed to pay a record $650 million fine and
plead guilty to six felonies to settle criminal securities fraud
charges with the Justice Department.
   Milken and his brother, Lowell, a senior Drexel aide who also
would lose at least half of his 1988 pay, charged that Drexel was
coerced by the government into the requirements. Neither Milken has
been charged with any criminal wrongdoing.
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood is to rule on the Milkens' motion.
   In his response, Romano also said the Milkens had failed to show
that their employment, pay and bonuses were constitutionally
protected or supported by a written contract. Joseph said neither of
the Milkens had a contract with Drexel.
   Milken, who still heads Drexel's Beverly Hills, Calif.-based
``junk,'' or high-yield, bond financing department, is one of the
biggest targets of a federal crackdown on securities law abuse. He
is expected to be indicted on fraud and racketeering charges in
connection with the government's lengthy investigation of Drexel.
   In a separate development, attorneys for Milken sought to have
proceedings halted while they ask the U.S. Supreme Court to
disqualify a judge presiding over Drexel's settlement of civil
charges with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The Milkens have asked that U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack,
who must approve the SEC pact, be disqualified because of an alleged
conflict of interest.
   The Milkens' attorneys on Monday asked the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals to issue a temporary injunction so Pollack does not make
any rulings on the SEC settlement until the Supreme Court decides
whether to consider the disqualification motion.
   The 12-member court last week refused a request to consider the
bid to have Pollack disqualified on grounds that his wife could
receive $30 million from a leveraged buyout Drexel recently helped
finance. A three-member court panel already had rejected the motion.
   If a stay were granted, it would hold up the SEC settlement,
which is in final negotiation stages. That in turn would delay
completion of the criminal plea agreement, which is contingent on
settlement of the civil charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AlliancePlant     03-01 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alliance Plant,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alliance to Open Missouri Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alliance Semiconductor Corp. says it
plans to use a moth-balled American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. plant
near Kansas City, Mo., to manufacture computer memory chips and
other products.
   If successful, Alliance would be the first new U.S. company to
enter the business of manufacturing dynamic random access memory
chips, also called DRAMS, in recent years.
   The six-year lease calls for the eventual purchase of AT&amp;T's
chip-making equipment, Robert Reid, a vice president of business
development at Alliance, said Tuesday.
   He said the Missouri site is worth between $250 million and $300
million but that Alliance will be getting the facility through a
low-interest loan of $10 million from the state of Missouri and
several Kansas City companies.
   ``We're getting a $200 million to $300 million facility for
peanuts,'' said Reid. ``We're going to use the plant as the
foundation for manufacturing a number of memory products.''
   Alliance said it hopes to generate about $500 million in annual
sales within 5 years and employ more than 1,200 workers. Its current
work force is 12.
</TEXT>
