<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AT&amp;TPriceCap 1stLd-Writethru f0032 03-01 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T Price Cap, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan to Revise Rate Structure Criticized on Hill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Patrick comments today; picks up 4th graf
pvs, But subcommittee. A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission today rejected a senator's request to delay a
controversial overhaul of AT&amp;T's rate structure despite widespread
congressional criticism of the proposed action.
   FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick told Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., he will
press ahead at a March 16 commission meeting with the plan to change
the way American Telephone &amp; Telegraph charges customers. He said
the part of the proposal covering interstate service could go into
effect July 1.
   Exon asked Patrick at the hearing of the Senate Commerce, Science
and Transportation subcommittee on communications if he would
postpone consideration of the ``rate cap'' plan until two vacancies
on the five-member FCC are filled by the Bush administration.
   The commission has been two members short since the beginning of
last year and President Bush has yet to announce choices for the
open slots.
   ``It is extraordinarily important to restructure the incentives
that we give this industry,'' Patrick told Exon today. ``We have to
begin to send a message. The sooner we start on that, the better.''
   Patrick on Tuesday told the House telecommunications and finance
subcommittee the plan could save residential customers $700 million
in the next four years while giving AT&amp;T the incentive to streamline
and modernize.
   But subcommittee Chairman Ed Markey, D-Mass., asked Patrick ``why
all the people who are purported to benefit from this plan still
oppose it and why all those who are supposed to be regulated by it
are clamoring for its immediate implementation?''
   The FCC proposal would change the two decades-old ``rate of
return'' regulation that allows AT&amp;T certain specified profits
beyond its costs.
   The new plan _ what Patrick called ``incentive regulation'' _
would place a cap on what AT&amp;T could charge customers but would
allow the company to keep any funds after costs as profit.
   Congress let the plan die last year because of concerns that
windfall profits could result at the expense of consumers, but
Patrick is moving ahead with it after making changes he says meet
congressional concerns.
   ``We've made several changes to satisfy their concerns and we'll
continue to discuss them,'' said Patrick. ``But the commission will
consider the pricing matter on the 16th.''
   Patrick's July 1 target leaves congressional critics little time
to pass an alternative that precludes the FCC.
   ``At this point, we don't have a concensus,'' said Markey.
   Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., said Congress has left a vacuum
that Patrick is filling with his action. He urged his colleagues to
``preserve our role in the regulatory process.''
   And Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., told reporters that Patrick should
postpone an FCC vote for a second time ``in new of the bipartisan
nature of the concerns expressed'' at Tuesday's hearing.
   Boucher was one of several lawmakers from rural areas who said
Patrick hasn't provided real safeguards to prevent AT&amp;T raising
rates unfairly for sparsely populated regions while giving discounts
to businesses and residents of cities.
   ``Talk may still be cheap in urban areas but it's about to get
very expensive in rural areas,'' an absent Rep. Jim Cooper, D-Tenn.,
said in a statement read at the hearing.
   Boucher told reporters Patrick ``is making movement in the right
direction, but I think it's not enough.
   ``I'd say we would have price caps in due course,'' he said.
``But under this plan, AT&amp;T could be an enormous profit machine.''
   Patrick outlined provisions that would limit AT&amp;T's ability to
raise or lower rates for various customers and said he would look at
other safeguards to ensure price changes for less populated regions
``remain within the zone of reasonableness.''
   He said AT&amp;T would have to cut overall prices by 3 percent over
four years under the FCC plan.
   Patrick also sought to mollify Congress by proposing to divide
AT&amp;T's services into three ``baskets'' _ one group including
residential and small business customers, for example _ and allowing
only limited price increases or decreases for each service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-XeroxCopiers     03-01 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Xerox Copiers,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox Introduces Three New Copiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. introduced three new copiers
today, including two low-volume models and a copier with a beveled
edge that can make copies from books without ruining bindings.
   The machines were displayed at a news conference at the company's
major manufacturing center in the Rochester suburb of Webster. Xerox
is based in Stamford, Conn.
   The low-volume copiers, the 5012 and the 5014, make 12 copies a
minute and come with Xerox's unique three-year warranty on parts and
labor and a copy cartridge guarantee.
   Xerox has always enjoyed a strong position in the mid- and
high-volume copier segments, but has not fared as well in the highly
competitive low-volume and personal copier markets.
   These new machines represent the company's attempt to increase
its presence in the low-volume market, which includes machines that
make up to 30 copies a minute, said Paul Cahn, vice president of
reprographics product support for Xerox's U.S. Marketing Group.
   ``We're aiming to set the industry benchmark for quality and
value in the low-volume range,'' Cahn said.
   The 5012 costs $2,325. The 5014, which has reduction and
enlargement capabilities, costs $2,850.
   The company's other new copier, the 5042, was designed for book
copying, mostly with the library industry in mind, Cahn said.
   It has a 35-degree slanted copying surface and a hinged cover
that will follow the shape of a book or other bound material instead
of squashing it down. It makes 35 copies a minute.
   Xerox officials said their studies found that in 1985 libraries
spent about $40 million to repair broken book bindings and they
believe the 5042 machine will help save bindings.
   The machine also features a versatile vending attachment that
will accept coins, bills and special vending cards.
   ``We have offered vending before, but it was just coins,'' said
Jim Miller, Xerox's manager of decentralized product marketing.
``And librarians told us they were tired of spending their whole day
making change for people.''
   The 5042 costs $9,470.
   All of the machines are available to buy or rent immediately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
