<FIRST>r f BC-Knight-Ridder-TV     03-01 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Knight-Ridder-TV,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agrees to Sell Oklahoma City TV Station to Iowa Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palmer Communications Inc. of Des Moines,
Iowa, has agreed to purchase Oklahoma City television station KTVY
from Knight-Ridder Inc., which has put all eight of its network
affiliate TV stations up for sale.
   The agreement between the two companies was reached late Monday.
Terms of the sale were not revealed.
   The Miami-based Knight-Ridder, whose main business is newspaper
publishing, said last month it had reached agreements to sell five
stations and was negotiating on the sale of three others, including
KTVY in Oklahoma City.
   Its remaining two stations are WTEN-TV in Albany, N.Y., and
WJRT-TV in Flint, Mich.
   Knight-Ridder, which put all eight stations up for sale last
fall, said it expected to get a total of $400 million for them.
   William J. Ryan, president and chief executive officer of Palmer,
said the purchase is part of his company's overall growth strategy.
   Palmer owns two television stations in Iowa and five radio
stations in Iowa and Florida and has interests in cable television
and cellular telephones.
   The transaction must be reviewed by the Federal Communications
Commission.
   Knight-Ridder has owned KTVY since 1986 when FCC regulations
forced Gannett Co. to sell either KTVY or Oklahoma City television
station KOCO, which Gannett already owned when it purchased the
Evening News Association stations.
   The five stations that Knight-Ridder previously disclosed it had
agreed to sell are WPRI-TV in Providence, R.I.; WTKR-TV in Norfolk,
Va.; WKRN-TV in Nashville, Tenn.; WALA-TV in Mobile, Ala.; and
KOLD-TV in Tuscon, Ariz.
</TEXT>
