<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   03-01 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher Despite Widening Trade Gap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock investors virtually overlooked news of a
wider-than-expected British trade deficit Wednesday and bid shares
higher on newly found hopes that the government might be able to
avoid raising interest rates.
   Equities were marked broadly lower immediately after the trade
figures were announced before midday, but there wasn't any selling
pressure to justify the markdown and prices soon recovered to their
best levels of the day.
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened sharply to 2.09
billion pounds, or $3.63 billion, in January from a revised deficit
of 1.76 billion pounds in December, the Department of Trade and
Industry said.
   ``There was relief that we didn't get a trade figure that implied
an immediate interest-rate rise,'' an analyst said. ``It is still
felt the authorities will avoid a rate rise if they can hope to do
so.''
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 18.9 points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,021.3.
   Volume was moderate, with 535.4 million shares changing hands,
but most of this business came on a spurt of buying interest in the
morning, dealers said. On Tuesday, turnover was a meager 357.8
million shares.
</TEXT>
