<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Sears-NewLook 1stLd-Writethru   03-01 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears-New Look, 1st Ld-Writethru,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Largest Retailer Gets New Prices, New Look</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs on stores beginning to reopen; picks up 4th
graf, ``The worst ....</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears' 824 stores across the nation began reopening today after a
42-hour facelift to complete price reductions on 1.5 billion pieces
of merchandise.
   ``People are backed up as far as we can see. It's wall-to-wall
people, said Bob Dumas, manager of the Sears, Roebuck and Co.
Northland Mall store in Columbus, Ohio.
   ``We have Christmas-quantity people, and we have better than
Christmas traffic,'' said Dumas, who estimated that more than 1,000
people waited outside for the doors to open.
   Workers changed prices Tuesday on everything _ including light
bulbs, toasters and polished door knobs _ as Sears, Roebuck and Co.
prepared for a new retailing strategy it hopes will win customers.
   Employees also had to change signs and displays, take inventory
and clean up before the openings, which occurred at noon local time.
   ``The worst was the screwdrivers,'' said Chris Skinner, a high
school freshman who spent much of the day at the Northland Mall
store in Columbus, Ohio, repricing baby booties and toddlers'
dresses. ``You had to take them all down, clean each one by hand,
then put them all back.''
   Sears intends to keep its prices low year-round, instead of
marking them up and down periodically for sales. This marks a major
change for the retailer, which helped to pioneer the concept of the
sale.
   Last year, Sears sold 55 percent of its goods at ``sale'' prices.
   The company said it still will run some sales, but for reasons
like simply clearing out lawn mowers in the fall. Otherwise, it will
use the strategy that retailers call ``everyday low pricing.''
   Sears, in adopting the strategy, joins a growing list, that
includes K mart Corp., Dayton Hudson Corp.'s Target discount chain
and Montgomery Ward and Co.
   At the Columbus store, 700 workers scrambled to the tune of
``Don't Worry, Be Happy,'' as they marked down items such as twin
canopy beds from $269.99 to $99.00, a Diehard automobile battery
from $72 to $64, and a Craftsman power drill from $59.99 to $32.62.
   Sears' new strategy meant reductions on 75 percent of its own
brands and the 1,000 other brand names it carries.
   ``I don't think they had any choice. They lost their customer
base,'' said Karen Sacks, an analyst with Standard and Poor's Corp.
in New York. ``I think Wednesday will be a madhouse at Sears. But
will they be able to re-educate their customers not to come in just
for a sale?''
   Monroe Greenstein, an analyst with the investment firm Bear
Stearns in New York, said the strategy paid off in Wichita, Kan.,
where sales rose 15 percent when Sears tested the idea last fall.
   ``And Sears will invest in an advertising campaign that, to not
hear about it, you would practically have to be comatose,''
Greenstein said.
   The cash register rings about 3,000 times a day in the
100,000-square-foot Columbus store, but the only sound in the last
couple of days was the clicking of pricing guns and muffled sounds
of store officials keeping in touch with walkie-talkies.
   About 100 high school students worked for $5 an hour to help
company officials in shirt-sleeves and scores of others with the
makeover.
   ``It's the most exciting thing I've ever been involved in in
Sears,'' said Bob Dumas, manager of the Northland Mall store and a
30-year Sears employee.
   ``It's no longer that old sea of yellow,'' he said, referring to
Sears' old yellow-with-black-lettering sale signs.
   The new signs, touting new, lower prices, are in vibrant red and
blue. In apparel, the signs are magenta and gray.
   ``They really needed to do something dramatic like that,'' Ms.
Sacks said. ``We'll just have to wait a year or two to see if it
works.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
