<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today, flattening out
after an early advance.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points
in early trading, was down 2.68 at 2,255.71 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 780 up, 578 down and
556 unchanged.
   Analysts noted that the market had shown signs since the start of
the week of recovering from the recent jolt it suffered from bad
news on inflation and a round of interest-rate increases.
   The upswing continued as rates declined modestly in the bond and
short-term money markets this morning.
   But then the bond market gave up its gains as traders studied a
government report showing stronger-than-expected gains in personal
income for January.
   And stocks followed the bond market's lead, settling back to
drift around Tuesday's closing levels.
   Coca-Cola rose { to 48\ and Columbia Pictures Entertainment was
up ] at 17[. There were reports that Coca-Cola had been approached
by several parties interested in acquiring its 49 percent stake in
Columbia Pictures Entertainment.
   Long Island Lighting added } to 14|. The company reached an
agreement with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo under which a long battle
over Lilco's Shoreham nuclear power plan would be resolved with the
demolition of the plant.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.13 to 162.62. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .32 at 322.79.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 121.75 million shares with two
hours to go.
