<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-01 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Sink On Easing Supply Signals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for rain in
Argentina's soybean fields and signs that supplies may not be as
tight as previously feared.
   Wheat futures advanced modestly due to an increase in export
business while corn futures finished mixed.
   Soybean futures plunged in the session's final 10 minutes
following forecasts for rain in Argentina later today and over the
weekend.
   The selling also reflected an increase Wednesday in the number of
notices of intent to deliver soybeans against the March contract.
   A greater number of notices indicates a greater willingness among
commercial traders to sell physical soybeans, which suggests an
easing of supply fears.
   Soybean delivery notices posted Wednesday morning totaled 9.2
million bushels compared with 4.4 million bushels on Tuesday, the
first notice day for the March contract.
   Wheat gained strength from the Agriculture Department's decision
to target Iraq for sales of 1 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices, and from reports that the Soviet Union was
bidding for 500,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.39{ a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to } cent higher with March at $2.71} a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 2{ cents lower with March at $2.03 a bushel; soybeans were
3{ cents to 12{ cents lower with March at $7.50{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
