<FIRST>r f AM-XeroxCopiers     03-01 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Xerox Copiers,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox Introduces Three Copiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. hopes a copier introduced
Wednesday will save the encyclopedias, dictionaries and other books
in libraries around the country from broken-binding syndrome.
   The Xerox 5042 has a slanted edge and a hinged cover that allow a
book or other bound material to be laid flat without squashing or
stretching the binding.
   ``We've responded very directly to a market need,'' said Paul
Cahn, vice president of reprographics product support for Xerox's
U.S. Marketing Group.
   Xerox officials said their studies found that libraries spent
about $40 million in 1985 to repair broken book bindings.
   ``This is very much of a niche kind of product, but it's the kind
of thing that will give Xerox a presence in places it wants to be,
like universities and libraries, where a lot of people will see
their name,'' said Bob Sostilio, a copier-industry analyst with
Dataquest Inc., of San Jose, Calif.
   The 5042 makes 35 copies a minute and can make reductions and
enlargements. It sells for $9,470.
   The machine also features a vending attachment that accepts
coins, bills and magnetic cards.
   ``We have offered vending before, but it was just coins,'' said
Jim Miller, Xerox's manager of decentralized product marketing.
``And librarians told us they were tired of spending their whole day
making change for people.''
   The American Library Association asked copier companies to come
up with a copier that wouldn't damage books and would make better
copies of bound materials.
   Xerox is one of two companies to offer a machine built with
libraries in mind.
   The other manufacturer, Oce Business Systems of Venlo,
Netherlands, introduced two library copiers in January, said company
spokesman John James.
   Also on Wednesday, Xerox introduced two new low-volume copiers
that are designed to keep the company ahead in that highly
competitive segment of the market, which includes copiers that make
up to 30 copies a minute.
   All three machines were displayed at a news conference at the
company's major manufacturing center in the Rochester suburb of
Webster. Xerox is based in Stamford, Conn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
