<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Travel Bjt   03-01 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Travel, Bjt,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Say Travelers Fleeing Eastern Bookings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Would-be travelers to and from South Florida and the
Caribbean were steering away from Eastern Airlines as the carrier's
Saturday strike deadline neared, travel agents said Wednesday.
   Agents said most customers were asking to change reservations or
turn in Eastern tickets. Eastern's largest union, the Machinists, is
poised for a strike if no contract settlement is reached by Friday
midnight.
   There has been a surge in ticket sales at Eastern's competitors,
said several agents interviewed Wednesday. Agents said participants
in Eastern's OnePass frequent flier program were for the most part
sticking with Eastern, but the agents were reluctant to book other
customers on the carrier.
   Eastern says anybody with a ticket for an Eastern flight that is
cancelled will get a refund or a seat on another airline.
   Besides confusing travelers in Eastern's major markets _ South
Florida, the Caribbean, the East Coast and Latin America _ the
looming strike has also raised the specter of disruption of South
Florida's lucrative ocean cruise business.
   At Miami's Happy Holidays Travel, which does about 30 percent of
its business in Eastern tickets, ``Most of them (customers) phone up
and say right away: `Please try and get me another airline,''' said
manager Beatrix Mompoint.
   ``A lot of people (are) calling up asking not to be put on
Eastern,'' said a travel agent at Miami's Barry White Travel Agent
Inc. who identified herself only as Agnes.
   In Washington, Michael DiPietro of Esplanade Travel reported that
his company remained ``hesitant'' about booking with Eastern ``until
we learn more about what is going to happen.''
   He said his agency is only booking Eastern if clients
specifically request the troubled airline.
   Even travel agents actively booking seats on Eastern said they
only do so with a warning to customers.
   Agent Galen Wightman of Capitol Hill Travel Associates said his
Washington-based company was advising customers of the possibility
of a strike, and warning that alternative arrangements might have to
be made at the last minute.
   Mompoint said agents at Happy Holidays inform customers that
Eastrern tickets `usually get accepted'' by other airlines in the
event of a strike.
   At Eastern, airline spokeswoman Cori Zywotow pledged disruption
caused by a strike would be kept to a minimum.
   ``Eastern will refund tickets on cancelled flights,'' she said.
``If you want your money back, you'll receive a full refund.''
   According to Zywotow, agreements between Eastern and other major
airlines stipulate that tickets which are endorsed by Eastern for
travel on another airline will be honored by other carriers at no
additional cost.
   That accord, she said, also covers discount-fare tickets
purchased from Eastern.
   The effectiveness of the inter-line agreement, however, was being
called into question by several other airlines _ including Pan
American World Airways, USAir, American Airlines and Trans World
Airlines, all of which have reportedly withheld unconditional
acceptance of Eastern tickets pending their own reviews of the
situation.
   Some airline analysts have said Eastern might seek protection
from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code,
which would make it difficult for other carriers to be compensated.
   South Florida's cruise lines, which carry each year nearly 4
million passengers _ most of them flown in from around the country
and abroad _ could also be adversely affected by a strike at Eastern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
