<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-01 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices slumped in late trading Wednesday,
giving up an early gain under the pressure of renewed interest-rate
worries.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points
in the early going, closed with a 15.35 loss at 2,243.04.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
633 up, 816 down and 522 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 177.21 million
shares, up from 147.43 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 209.93 million shares.
   Analysts noted that the market had shown signs since the start of
the week of recovering from the jolt it suffered last week as a
result of bad news on inflation and a round of interest-rate
increases.
   The upswing continued as rates declined modestly in the bond and
short-term money markets Wednesday morning.
   But then the bond market gave up its gains as traders studied a
government report showing stronger-than-expected gains in personal
income for January.
   By late afternoon, prices of long-term government bonds, which
move in the opposite direction from interest rates, showed losses of
about $5 for eaach $1,000 in face value. And stocks followed the
bond market's lead.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 1| at 119~; General Electric, down \ at 45; American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down \ at 30, and Union Carbide, down { at
29{.
   Coca-Cola rose \ to 48 and Columbia Pictures Entertainment was up
1\ at 18. There were reports that Coca-Cola had been approached by
several parties interested in acquiring its 49 percent stake in
Columbia Pictures Entertainment.
   AAR gained 1] to 27{ on expectations that the company's aviation
parts and services business might benefit from a push to stepped-up
maintenance work on the nation's aircraft fleet.
   Atlas Corp. rose 1{ to 26~. The company announced plans for a
2-for-1 stock split.
   Long Island Lighting added | to 14{. The company reached an
agreement with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo under which a long battle
over Lilco's Shoreham nuclear power plan would be resolved with the
demolition of the plant.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $11.22 billion, or 0.39
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .75 to 161.74.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 2.00 to 331.48, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down 1.75 at 287.11.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market edged
up .09 to 399.80. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 322.18, down .29.
</TEXT>
