<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-01 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose broadly Wednesday, benefiting
from weakness in the British pound.
   Gold prices pulled back in domestic and overseas dealings.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of $383.80 for a
troy ounce of gold bullion at 4 p.m. EST, down from $387 late
Tuesday.
   ``The weakness of the pound pushed the dollar and the deutsche
mark higher,'' said John McCarthy, chief dealer at the Amsterdam
Rotterdam Bank in New York.
   Sterling suffered due to unexpectedly bad figures on Britain's
trade performance during January and persistent doubts about
Britain's overall economic health.
   Currency dealers dumped pounds after release of the trade report.
In an effort to counter the sell-off, the Bank of England, the
country's central bank, intervened in the market, buying pounds.
   One pound cost $1.7243 in London late Wednesday, nearly 2 cents
cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7430. It was the pound's
lowest level since Oct. 11, when sterling stood at $1.7175.
   Later, the pound ended in New York at $1.72325, down from $1.7430
Tuesday.
   In the United States, dealers bid up the value of the mark on the
grounds that West German monetary authorities soon might raise
interest rates to reduce economic activity and relieve inflationary
pressures.
   European dealers had earlier sold marks amid speculation there
that prospects for higher West German interests have diminished, due
partly to the currency's strength.
   In Tokyo trading, which ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 127.68 Japanese yen, up from 127.15. Late
Wednesday in London the dollar traded higher at 128.15 yen, and in
New York the dollar finished at 128.225 yen, up from 126.89 on
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's
levels, included: 1.83675 West German marks, up from 1.82275;
1.56875 Swiss francs, up from 1.5549; 1.19875 Canadian dollars; down
from 1.19925; 6.2495 French francs, up from 6.2035; and, 1,354.25
Italian lire, up from 1,341.75.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8390 West German marks, up from
1.8230; 1.5705 Swiss francs, up from 1.5535; 6.2575 French francs,
up from 6.1975; 2.0755 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0555; 1,354.75
Italian lire, up from 1,341.50; and 1.1985 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2005.
   Gold bullion prices slid.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $384.30 a troy ounce, down from $387.50 on
Tuesday.
   In London, the major European precious metals market, gold closed
at $384.25 bid a troy ounce, down from $386.75. The closing price in
Zurich was $384.10 bid, down from $387.15.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $388.26, down from
$388.85.
   Silver prices also declined.
   On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery closed at $5.744
a troy ounce, down from Tuesday's settlement of $5.822. Silver
bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.79 a troy ounce, down from
$5.86.
</TEXT>
