<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-01 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Leap On Peruvian Strike, Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices soared Wednesday amid supply concerns
prompted by labor unrest in Peru and underlined by the small number
of copper delivery notices posted on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   On other exchanges, precious-metals futures prices plummeted;
soybean futures dropped sharply; and grain, energy, and livestock
and meat futures were mixed.
   Copper settled 3.9 cents to 8.8 cents higher on the Commodity
Exchange with the contract for delivery in March at $1.455 a pound,
the highest settlement price for the March contract since Jan. 27
but still well below the record high for spot copper of $1.6475 a
pound reached Dec. 8 on the exchange.
   The rally was sparked by news that miners in Peru, the world's
sixth-largest copper producer, would consider extending a planned
3-day strike if conditions warrant. The strike is scheduled to begin
on March 26.
   The reports stirred memories of last fall's 57-day Peruvian
mining strike, which was a major factor in copper's rise to record
price levels.
   Demand for copper remains strong and supplies continue to be
tight, a situation reflected in the slim number of delivery notices
posted Tuesday and Wednesday on the exchange.
   The delivery notices signify the intent of commercial traders to
deliver copper against the March contract, which expires on March
29. A small number of delivery notices would indicate a reluctance
or inability among copper processors to deliver the metal,
suggesting that their own supplies are limited.
   Only three delivery notices were issued Tuesday, the first notice
day, and none were posted on Wednesday.
   Analysts said the market's bullish supply-and-demand factors and
strong chart signals could lead to another run at record price
levels.
   ``It's starting to look like a replay of 1987 and 1988,'' when
copper prices reached their last two peaks, said Fred Demler, metals
economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Platinum led a steep sell-off in precious-metals futures as the
strengthening dollar and rising interest rates spurred a further
retreat of investors from precious metals, a traditional hedge
against inflation.
   Platinum settled $9.30 to $9.80 lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with April at $531.10 a troy ounce. On the Commodity
Exchange, gold settled $3.30 to $3.70 lower with April at $387.10 a
troy ounce; silver was 8 cents to 10.1 cents lower with March at
$5.744 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures dropped sharply on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid forecasts for rain in Argentina's soybean fields.
   Wheat futures advanced modestly due to an increase in export
business while corn futures finished mixed.
   The soybean sell-off also reflected a steep increase Wednesday in
the number of delivery notices posted against the March contract.
   Wheat settled 1} cents to 4 cents higher with March at $4.39\ a
bushel; corn was } cent lower to } cent higher with March at $2.71}
a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 2{ cents lower with March at $2.02} a
bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents to 12{ cents lower with March at
$7.50{ a bushel.
   Crude oil futures posted modest gains on the New York Mercantile
Exchange but prices for refined products ended narrowly mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents to 13 cents
higher with April at $18.28 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent lower
to .30 cent higher with April at 50.49 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .08 cent lower to .30 cent higher with April at 51.56
cents a gallon.
   Expectations of a demand slump weighed on the cattle futures
market at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange while pork futures gained
in a technically inspired rally.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .78 cent lower with April at
77.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .28 cent lower
with March at 82.52 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent to .65
cent lower with April at 44.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .20 cent to .50 cent lower with March at 38.67 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
