<DOCNO> AP890301-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SmokelessCigarette     03-01 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smokeless Cigarette,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Premier May Pave Way For Cigarette Revolution, Despite
Failure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc.'s high-tech, smokeless
cigarette may have been pulled from test markets, but some analysts
said Wednesday the experimental smokes could start the same sort of
product revolution that Tab did for diet soft drinks 20 years ago.
   ``I think down the road it will do real well,'' said Eric Garner,
a vice president in the Charlotte office of Carolinas Securities.
``It's a little rough, but I think the concept is good and in the
next 25 years we're going to see more companies go to this.''
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco announced Tuesday it was withdrawing its
Premier brand after five months of test marketing in Arizona and
Missouri. Smokers complained that the cigarette, which used a carbon
heat source to pull warm air over a flavor capsule and dried
tobacco, had a bad taste and smell.
   ``Everyone I know who tried it thought it was really horrible,''
said Pavlos M. Alexandrakis, who follows tobacco companies for Argus
Research Corp. in New York.
   Garner, himself a smoker, said he had tried one of the cigarettes
when RJR made a presentation to investment groups. The flavor, he
said, ``was less than thrilling, that's about all I can say.''
   ``It was a very strange thing, if you're a smoker,'' Garner said.
``There were no ashes, but you kept flicking it out of habit. It had
a strange taste because you weren't burning any tobacco, just
drawing air through it.''
   Despite his own experience with Premiers, Garner said he expects
to see similar innovations in the future.
   ``I remember the first Tabs, how terrible they were,'' Garner
said. ``They tasted just awful, but now you have diet Coke, diet
Pepsi, all these diet drinks. It really was a revolutionary product.
   ``More new products fail than succeed, so Premier's failure _ and
I'm not sure it's a total failure _ is not really surprising,'' he
said. ``You try to find out what's wrong with a product in your test
marketing and they've obviously been given some things to work on.
   ``I'm sure they'll take it back to the lab and keep tampering
with it and monkeying around with it and they'll come up with
something pretty good,'' he said. ``The consumer will tell them if
they've worked it out somewhere down the road.''
   ``This is no surprise,'' said industry analyst Emanuel Goldman.
``It was brought out stillborn.''
   Goldman, who works for PaineWebber Inc., said Premier suffered
from two fatal problems: unacceptable taste and aroma.
   ``What the company was saying was consumers will get used to it,
they'll give it an extra try,'' he said. ``That's inconsistent with
the fact that we are a nation of channel-hoppers, and if you don't
like it the first time, you're not going to try it a second time.''
   Tobacco growers initially were uneasy with Premiers because they
used significantly less tobacco than regular cigarettes, but Carlton
Blalock, executive director of the Tobacco Growers Association of
North Carolina, said he doubts farmers will be jumping up and down
with joy over Premier's demise.
   ``Everybody said from the start it would have been better had it
been a product that used more tobacco than a regular cigarette,''
Blalock said. ``But I felt like on balance it might have worked out.
   ``The cigarette had potential had it proven to be acceptable by
the public because of some of the features that it offered,
especially on sidestream smoke and the fire safety issue,'' he said.
``Had that ... been accepted as fully as it potentially might have
been, it could have more than offset the amount of tobacco used in
the cigarette.
   ``Anytime somebody in the industry tries something new and it
doesn't work out, you're a little disappointed because it well could
have a positive impact on tobacco growers down the road,'' he said.
``My guess is that they (RJR) will continue working on it. It
certainly would not make sense for them just to shelve it after all
the investment that's been put into it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
