<FIRST>r f AM-Tyson-HollyFarms     03-01 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tyson-Holly Farms,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Reserves Ruling In Poultry Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware Chancery Court judge declined
to rule Wednesday on a request by Tyson Foods Inc. to block Holly
Farms Inc. from holding a shareholders' vote on its proposed merger
with ConAgra Inc.
   Tyson Foods, the nation's largest poultry producer, has fought a
four-month battle to acquire Memphis, Tenn.-based Holly Farms, a
diversified company that is the country's fifth-largest poultry
producer.
   Tyson asked the court to stop Holly Farms from proceeding with a
shareholders' meeting to vote on the buyout.
   Delaware Chancery Court Vice Chancellor Maurice Hartnett III said
after a hearing that he would reserve his ruling on the request. He
did not say when the ruling could be expected.
   Holly Farms, which has twice spurned takeover offers from Tyson,
has reached agreement to merge with Omaha, Neb.-based ConAgra, but
the deal has been blocked in court.
   Tyson, based in Springdale, Ark., has offered $60 per share in
cash in a buyout valued at more than $1 billion. ConAgra has
proposed a stock swap valued at about $1 billion.
   The agreement would allow ConAgra to purchase key assets of Holly
Farms if the deal fails.
   Tyson argued that a shareholders' vote would be coercive and
would cause irreparable harm to shareholders.
   ``We've put our money where our mouth is _ and where it is is $85
million higher than the ConAgra offer,'' said Tyson attorney
Jonathon J. Lerner.
   Holly Farms attorney Kenneth Nachbar argued that shareholders
would be hurt if they were not allowed to vote on the merger.
   ``If the vote goes forward the shareholders could vote against
ConAgra. That's the way for a decision to be made,'' said Kenneth
Nachbar, attorney for Holly Farms. ``This is the best business
decision.''
   ConAgra's offer expires May 1.
</TEXT>
