<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BOT-Mahlmann     03-01 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BOT-Mahlmann,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board of Trade Computer System Will Improve Audit Trail, Chairman
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade is moving to employ a
computerized, off-hours trading system for competitive reasons, but
its proposed new system will provide a ``significantly improved
audit trail'' for regulating its members, the market's chairman said
Wednesday.
   In a 20-minute speech to the Chicago division of the Futures
Industry Association, Karsten Mahlmann said the Board of Trade
within weeks would publicly unveil its proposed electronic
auction-market system.
   Mahlmann said the new computerized trading method would be more
than a system for matching orders and claimed it would surpass the
Globex trading system being developed by the rival Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``The system to the greatest extent possible replicates the
trading pit as we all know it today,'' Mahlmann said.
   The Board of Trade informed its members 2{ weeks ago that it was
planning to implement the computerized system for trading during
hours when the market's trading floor is closed.
   Its purpose then was described as primarily to give foreign
investors easier access to the Board of Trade's increasing market
for U.S. Treasury bond futures, members said.
   Industry observers have said the move into computerized trading
by the Board of Trade appearently was prompted by a widespread
federal investigation of suspected fraud at the Board of Trade and
the Merc.
   But Mahlmann indicated Wednesday that market pressures were the
primary motivation.
   ``Knowing that our competitors were developing a computerized
trading system, we privately proceeded to develop our own,'' he said.
   ``If I were president of the United States...and I knew that my
neighbor competitor had a nuclear bomb, I would have no alternative
but to also develop such a weapon,'' he said.
   ``I may prefer other strategies to nuclear weapons, and I may not
necessarily use them, but I simply cannot afford to have the weapon
not in my arsenal,'' he said.
   But Mahlmann also said ``a significantly improved audit trail''
would result from a new electronic order-entry system to allow
greater regulation with minimal increased costs to members.
   Like Globex, the Board of Trade's system is to use a computer to
match orders to buy and sell contracts for future deliveries of
financial instruments. Also, like Globex, the system will be open to
other futures exchanges that wish to list their products for trading.
   But unlike Globex, which the Merc is developing in partnership
with London-based Reuters PLC, the Board of Trade system is to be
developed and owned entirely by the exchange and its members.
   Mahlmann emphasized the differences Wednesday, saying, ``It has
become obvious to me, at least, and to the exchange, that the
technology used in Globex is outdated, and as that, extremely
costly...to market users.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0313 </DOCNO>
