<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-WesternUnion     03-01 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Western Union,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Union Reports Quarter, Yearly Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPPER SADDLE RIVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Union Corp. Wednesday
reported a $244 million loss in fourth-quarter earnings, which the
telecommunications company attributed to restructuring charges
connected with a change of services.
   Western Union said the fourth-quarter loss compared to a net gain
of $105 million, or $3.99 per share, in 1987's fourth quarter.
   Sales in the final quarter of 1988 were $186.5 million, compared
to revenues of $190.9 million for the same period of 1987.
   For the year, the company said it lost $1.08 billion on revenues
of $875.9 million. That compares to a net income of $88 million, or
$2.58 a share, on revenues of $801.8 million in 1987, the company
said.
   The restructuring charges went to equipment writeoffs, severance
pay and other costs related to the company's transition ``from a
facilities-based operator of domestic telecommunications
transmission services to its role as an international provider of
value-added messaging, financial and other services,'' said Robert
J. Amman, Western Union president and chief executive.
   The company's stock closed at $2 on the New York Stock Exchange
Wednesday, up 12 cents from Tuesday.
