<FIRST>u f AM-GAFTrial     03-01 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Trial,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Opens Case in Stock Manipulation Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-GAF-Impact, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday refused to dismiss
charges or grant a mistrial in the GAF Corp. stock manipulation case
and defense lawyers called their first witnesses.
   GAF and its vice chairman, James T. Sherwin, are charged with
securities fraud and other criminal counts in an alleged scheme to
manipulate the price of Union Carbide Corp. stock in October 1986.
   U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe denied defense motions to
dismiss the charges made Tuesday, finding that ``the government has
offered sufficient evidence.''
   The judge also denied a defense request to declare a mistrial for
the second time. Lowe declared a mistrial Jan. 10, four weeks into
the case, because a prosecutor failed to disclose a report that
concluded a major piece of evidence had been altered.
   After a new jury was selected, the second trial began Feb. 1 with
opening arguments at federal court in Manhattan.
   Legal and business observers consider the GAF trial significant
because it is the first courtroom test of information stemming from
the insider trading scandals that rocked Wall Street in the
mid-1980s.
   GAF, a Wayne, N.J.-based chemicials and building materials
manufacturer, two subsidiaries and Sherwin were accused of
orchestrating a scheme to drive up the price of Union Carbide before
unloading 5 million shares acquired during an unsuccessful takeover
attempt.
   The main prosecution witness was Boyd L. Jefferies, former head
of a Los Angeles-based brokerage who struck a plea bargain with
prosecutors after being implicated by master insider trader Ivan
Boesky. Boesky, who is serving a 3-year prison sentence, did not
testify at the trial.
   After a securities fraud count was dismissed Tuesday, at
prosecutors' request, the defense sought to have the remaining eight
counts of stock manipulation, conspiracy, securities fraud and wire
fraud dismissed.
   The defense held that the government hadn't offered proof of
intent to induce investors to but stock. They sought a mistrial on
grounds that some of Jefferies' testimony, which was contradicted by
one of his associates, was hearsay.
   Lowe denied the request, however, and defense lawyers for Sherwin
called three character witnesses, including Leo Cherne, a
76-year-old lawyer and official of the International Rescue
Committee, which assists political refugees.
   Cherne said Sherwin, 54, of Princeton, N.J., had served on the
IRC's executive committee since the early 1970s with ``extraordinary
devotion and distinction.''
   The count dismissed Tuesday concerned the sale of 5 million
shares of Carbide stock in November 1986 to Salomon Brothers Inc.
The count was considered a complicating factor in an already complex
case, but Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl H. Lowenson Jr. declined to
comment on why the government dropped the charge.
   Lowe said she expected to sequester the jury during their
deliberations, expected to begin late next week.
</TEXT>
