<HEAD>Semi-Tech Increases Cash Tender Offer for SSMC to $34 a Share</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to put total value on offer and explain terms;
picks up 3rd graf, Semi-Tech ....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Semi-Tech Microelectronics (Far East) Ltd. on
Wednesday increased its tender offer for SSMC Inc. to about $241
million, two days after a group led by Malaysian investor Vincent
Tan entered the bidding war for the Shelton, Conn.-based maker of
Singer sewing machines.
   Semi-Tech, a subsidiary of International Semi-Tech
Microelectronics Inc. of Toronto, said SSMC has consented to the new
offer of $34 a share, up from $30 a share originally offered.
   Semi-Tech would buy 5.4 million shares, or about 77 percent of
SSMC stock, with $34 a share in cash, then complete the merger by
exchanging the rest of the SSMC stock for preferred stock in the new
company.
   Semi-Tech extended its tender offer, previously scheduled to
expire at midnight EST Thursday, to March 14. The company, which is
making the offer through its STM Holdings Inc. unit, said that as of
the close of business yesterday, 49,873 SSMC common shares had been
tendered under the new offer.
   Tan's group, Berjaya Corp. (Malaysia) Berhad, on Monday announced
a $33-a-share tender offer. Berjaya already owns slightly less than
10 percent of SSMC's outstanding shares, giving its tender offer for
the remaining stock a value of about $211 million.
   Its offer expires at midnight EST on March 24.
