<HEAD>Freeze May Result In Short Potato Chip Shortage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead, adds new graf after 7th graf pvs, `In Putnam ...,'
to CLARIFY that officials not predicting potato chip shortage. Version
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPUDS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cold snap that heavily damaged northeast
Florida's potatoes and blighted other crops could drive up local
vegetable prices and put a crimp in the nation's potato chip supply
this spring, officials said Tuesday.
   The potato chip industry had been counting on an early and
abundant supply of potatoes from this area this spring to replinish
dwindling stocks, said Harold Willingham, southeastern area field
manager for Frito-Lay Inc.
   But now the freeze has turned what was expected to be a bonanza
into a season of gloom for potato farmers.
   ``As good as the crop was looking it would work out about right.
It was as much as three weeks early,'' Willingham said Monday from
his office in nearby Hastings.
   The 26,000 acres of potatoes St. Johns, Putnam and Flagler
counties in northeast Florida fill a niche in the supply of chip
potatoes for a few weeks each spring because they come in earlier
than other areas.
   Emergency boards in St. Johns and Flagler counties estimated that
10 percent of the potato fields had 100 percent loss, 10 percent had
no loss and 80 percent had from 10 to 50 percent loss.
   In Putnam County, the loss was 50 percent.
   However, Willingham said he couldn't ``envision there not being
enough potato chips on the shelves for consumers.''
   Doug Zant of the Agricultural Stablization and Conservation
Service in Gainesville said the counties have been asked to submit
reports that will be sent to the governor's office for a decision on
whether damage is sufficient to request federal disaster assistance.
   ``There is some severe damage. I think the percentage of loss
will go higher,'' said Bobby White, ASCS director for St. Johns and
Flagler counties.
   The attitude among potato farmers has gone ``from optimism to
gloom,'' said Austin Tilton, Putnam Countky extension director.
   The 5,000 acres of potato plants in Putnam County sustained heavy
losses because they had been planted early and were too big to cover
with dirt to protect them from the cold, Tilton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
